{"Author": "Christopher L. Barber", "Date": "on October 19, 2017", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "This is what you get when you let children write software", "Text": "My biggest complaint about this incredibly immature device is the software. There is absolutely no comprehension of decent architecture in this thing. And yet from a hardware/technical perspective it's probably better than most. Multi-mode communication (RF+powerline), more features, more flexible, etc. The downside is that the protocol is proprietary, so you won't be connecting your zigbee or zwave gadgets to this. But back to the so-called software... I don't even know where to begin, this thing is so lame it's laughable. I'll start with most epic fail I've found so far: the device must have a lat-long position provided by the app via GPS in order to correctly set its own time zone. If you configure the device by running the app on (for example) a tablet with no GPS, you'll go through the whole \"set your location\" thing, pointing to your house on a map, and it will read back your exact address including zipcode, yet it fails to figure out what time zone you're in even with all that information at hand, and further fails to tell you that this is the case. So you, like so many others who have asked the same question in countless forum posts, are left wondering why your hub thinks it's 5 am when in fact it's actually (fill in the blank) in your local time and (if you're lucky) the porch lights are turning on at noon instead of at local sunset. As for me, I couldn't get a scheduled even to occur even when I compensated for the incorrect time zone.\n\nSo I figured that was the case, and redid the location setup using an iphone instead of a non-gps tablet, and sure enough as soon as the location was set, the hub time changed to match local time and programmed schedules starting working. This serves to point out a couple of secondary deficiencies in this amateurish design:\nThere is no way to edit the local time\nThere is no way to edit the time zone - in fact, there is no feedback of the time zone at all. If the app would just tell you what time zone it thought it was in, even the most novice user would recognize that something might not be right.\n\nGeneral app design - very incohesive, more like a random collection of screens than an integrated application. My biggest gripe in this area is the fact that you can't edit anything without going to the Settings page. We have a page for Rooms, a page for Scenes, a page for whatever, but whatever is on those pages should have a button you can touch to edit the thing. Here's an example: Click into the Rooms page, click into a room, see a page full of devices. What can you do with these devices? Nothing more than the basic function of the device, such as on/off if it's a switch. How about being able to change the name or other properties of the device right there? Not happening. You have to go to the Settings menu, then into Devices, then something else, it's just a giant hassle. Same with Scenes. Settings -> Scenes -> choose a scene -> edit it. Most of this crap on the settings page has nothing to do with settings. If I want to change what a scene does, the most obvious place to do that would be on the Scenes page. There's my scene, press and hold on the scene, go to edit mode. But that's just fantasy.\n\nThe list of rooms you create seems to have no ability to be ordered into any logical order. Even on the most outdated phone I can drag icons around to order them on a screen to suite my preferences. Not happening on this thing. I think they show up in whatever random order it occurred to you to created them in. So you might want to think that through a bit before starting in on it.\n\nApparently they took some shortcuts with the data structures used to represent schedules because it seems that two separate schedules cannot have events that are programmed to occur at the same time. I set up one schedule with an on-time set for sunset. Then, on another device or scene, I created another schedule which was meant to have an on-time of sunset, but a different off-time. The app responded with an error message telling me I couldn't have the same on-time and that I should either adjust the time or put the device in the other scene. Wtf? It's pretty obvious they're driving the schedule off a list of times where they expect to find only one unique instance of a specific time in the list. Really lame.\n\nThere seems to be no end to the stupidities I find in the app that drives this thing. The hardware's pretty good. I've read a lot of people complaining about poor longevity in the remote controlled devices. It's likely true, but consider that these are essentially digital microcontrollers and radios powered directly off of the utility line voltage in a tiny, tiny box where there is no room for a decent power supply with good transient suppression, isolation, etc. These things are prime candidates to be killed by voltage surges.\n\nOh, the remote control switches and things all come with stranded wire which you are supposed to connect to your solid 14 ga in-wall wiring. Really bad choice. This stuff is not meant to be twisted up in a wire nut. You have to be very careful to get a tight connection. Then on the other hand, the little micro on/off switch (\"micro\" is a fairly optimistic term) has screw-clamp terminals - much better choice - but the barrels of the terminals are so short you can only get about 3/16\" of bare copper in the hole without leaving exposed copper outside the hole. Honestly, I don't think these people have any real understanding of electricity.\n\nOr software, obviously."}
