{"Author": "T. H. Matheu", "Date": "on August 13, 2017", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Instructions for swapping out an old Insteon Hub", "Text": "Here is how to swap out an old Insteon Hub (ex: model: 2242-222)\nWith a new Hub (ex: model: 2245-222) in an existing environment and reconnect devices.\n\nI am leaving this review to help others in my position.\n\nI have a house full of Insteon devices: wall switches, lamp modules, lamp bulbs.\nI was able to successfully swap out my old hub for my new one and reconnect existing devices without issues.\n\nHere is what you must do:\nCall Insteon support:\nAsk them to access your account and send you a spreadsheet of all your Device List containing all your device Hub ID\u2019s (six character ID)\nThis is SUPER IMPORTANT to help you reconnect.\nThen have Insteon support delete your old Insteon account.\n\nPlug in your new Hub to power and ethernet.\n\nDelete your Insteon app, and re-download.\n\nLaunch app and setup a new account.\nFollow instructions in app to add devices using the Device ID\u2019s from the spreadsheet.\n\nYou will need to add devices one-by-one and re-create scenes and schedules.\nOnce all devices are added, test your devices.\n\nI had problems controlling light switches the first time using ON/OFF. Instead I tried to Dim the light, and that worked. They seem to want to say \u201chello\u201d to each other. Dimming rather than ON/OFF seemed to do this. After that ON/OFF also worked.\n\nAll in, this took me less than an hour for 14 devices. I had no errors, or issues.\n\nGood Luck"}
{"Author": "Geoffrey Michaels", "Date": "on August 13, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Great starter kit with 2 dimmer modules", "Text": "Great starter kit with 2 dimmer modules. This starter kit is so cheap on Amazon. With Insteon, you can do anything."}
{"Author": "Cindy", "Date": "on August 10, 2017", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "CANNOT SIMPLY REPLACE WITH A NEW HUB WHEN THE HARDWARE FAILS.", "Text": "Insteon makes a great array of switches and modules but these hubs are TERRIBLE. These hubs are slow, unreliable, have not been updated in several years. Once you go through all of the setup for a device which is slow and tedious in a poorly thought out app and finally after you have it all working just the way you want you might be happy for a while. When Alexa integration was announced it was always faster to ask Alexa to turn something off/on than it was to open the app, wait for it to stop spinng on all your devices and click on the device to turn it off. I had my hub for a couple of years and thoughI dreaded entering the app to add a new device, I have accumulated nearly 50 devices in our home now. Many of them hardwired. One is 3 stories high controlling the coach lights on our garage. Very cool, until two days ago, the hub failed. In my many purchase of hardware I ended up with a second hub from a second starter kit. I googled replace Insteon hub and was shocked to see the replacement procedure was \"START ALL OVER\". There are hundreds of angry posts about this, no one thinks about when hardware fails with something that is cloud connected anymore. It's usually a small config file that gets moved and you tap or click a few things but this requires you to literally start from scratch on all of your hard work. I emailed Insteon to verify and as of today when written the expected procedure is to delete your entire account and start from scratch. Below is my response from that support request:\n\nFrom: Insteon Support\nSent: 08/10/2017\nSubject: Insteon ID Request\n\nHello Brian,\n\nThank you for contacting Insteon.\n\nIn order to use the same email address with a new Hub then we would first need to delete the account which was registered with your old Hub once that is done you can go ahead and set up the new Hub with the same email address.\n\nUnfortunately there is no option to transfer settings from one Hub to another you will have to start over from the beginning. I can go ahead and send your device list with Insteon ID which will make your work easy because when you are adding the devices to the new Hub you can just add by inserting the Device ID.\n\nPlease confirm if you would like me to proceed with account deletion.\n\nSincerely\nInsteon Support"}
{"Author": "Amazon Customer", "Date": "on August 9, 2017", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Good for controlling lights and switches \u2013 not much else.", "Text": "It is good at controlling lights and switches-and not much else.\n\nIt makes a terrible home alarm system - which was the primary purpose for my purchase. There is no way to configure a keypad to turn off the alarm. The alarm rings the moment you walk in the door.\n\nThe garage door opener control was not compatible with my lift master garage door.\n\nThe portable remote control switch that I purchased could not be added to a scene.\n\nThe thermostat cannot be added to a scene or controlled by Alexa.\n\nThe bridge that supposed to function with MILocks Devices cannot be added to a scene or controlled from Alexa.\n\nThe tech-support people give you a different answer every time you call.\n\nI've spent about $1000, and all I can effectively do is turn my lights on and off."}
{"Author": "cookie", "Date": "on August 9, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "Great price. Works well with Alexa."}
{"Author": "Johnny", "Date": "on August 8, 2017", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Works great until it goes out", "Text": "Works great until it goes out. Purchased in April 2016 and 16 months later it's dead. Will be ordering a third unit since I don't have time to research a competitive product that will last longer. If you have some time, do the research and if you find something, please comment as I'm sure we'll need a 4th in the not too distant future."}
{"Author": "Janvi Vora", "Date": "on August 8, 2017", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "First step towards home automation", "Text": "I got my package within two days and to my surprise the packaging of the product was really cool with a clear installation guide. The hub comes with two switches and was very easy to install. This product is one of the best in the league of home automation products. because of its sleek design it looks good on my walls and doesnt lost its connection as my nest devices used to do. This product is very good for beginners who want to automate there homes.Planning to buy more products from this family. The best part is, it is compatible with my amazon echo dot and the response time is very less. As compared to other automation hubs available online this one has the best value for money. Day by day there network is growing and the hub is getting compatible with other electronic locks and motion sensors. overall its a great product for begineers and definately worth it.\nketan sharma"}
{"Author": "Dino", "Date": "on August 5, 2017", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Controls my home lighting.", "Text": "Unit was a return that was registered already with Insteon. Had to jump through hoops to get it reset. Works fine otherwise for my home lighting."}
{"Author": "Guy Manor", "Date": "on August 5, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "I bought this starter kit for a great price (mainly for the hub)", "Text": "I had the previous model of the hub - it stopped working after 4 years.\nI bought this starter kit for a great price (mainly for the hub). The setup was extremely easy. I needed to add all of my devices again but it took just a few minutes (insteon sent me all devices id). The hub is working great until now (one week of use)."}
{"Author": "Fr. John", "Date": "on July 31, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Solid product!", "Text": "Works as described. I control it with Alexa."}
{"Author": "Donna", "Date": "on July 30, 2017", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "One Star", "Text": "Sent back"}
{"Author": "Bruce", "Date": "on July 30, 2017", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "If I knew 2 years ago what I know now I would have tried some other device to make my home smart and I would not have bought 4 Echo devices ...", "Text": "I bought an Insteon starter pack at a local Menards about 18 months ago. The hub failed and I have 20 devices counting on this so I ordered it over night to replace the dead one. I contacted Insteon and if I could find my proof of purchase the will give me a new on as the warranty is 2 years. I set this on up and with help from Insteon on the phone I finally got it to work. There is no documentation on how to replace a failed hub. You have to call.\nThat is part of why I gave it only 2 stars.\n\nThe helped me and gave me an Excel spread sheet with most of the device information I needed to set up the hub. It took over an hour to get it back to working. Some devices require you to be at the device to set up.\n\nThis is the other reason. I have 2 Echo dots, a touch and a full size Echo. After I got them set up I tested their connection with my Echo devices. I deleted the old ones, asked Alexa to find the devices and the Alexa app did. What it didn't do is work. There were six devices that showed in my Alexa app that Alexa would tell me she couldn't find. I emailed for Amazon support and got a quick reply telling me to call. I called and got a representative who had no idea what I was talking about. She had never heard of Insteon devices. I had to repeat the name frequently, spell it and all she did was have me do things I already had done and then she was stuck. She bumped me up the line to a man who immediately told me that I had to contact Insteon for help. When I inquired why since it was Alexa who failed to find the devices, but who found them in the Alexa App he just continued to brush me off. It was rude and not very helpful since the Insteon Hub and Insteon App worked, and Alexa didn't. I finally hung up after he repeated the same thing to me again and would not listen or answer my question.\n\nIf I knew 2 years ago what I know now I would have tried some other device to make my home smart and I would not have bought 4 Echo devices since the support is weak at best."}
{"Author": "Maxie Death", "Date": "on July 29, 2017", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Insteon with Alexa", "Text": "Got my Echo Dot and my Insteon Home Control Starter Kit, 1 Hub & 2 Dimmer Modules \u2013 2244-372 today. Now I am an IT person, but I had 3 very stiff drinks prior to setting this up. It was still very easy (using iPhone 7 Plus). The Insteon app worked well, and Alexa was able to connect easily. Turning off lamps via Alexa works great, but dimming does not. Maybe I am using the wrong verbage. Overall I am happy and will add some additional Insteon devices."}
{"Author": "Amazon Customer", "Date": "on July 26, 2017", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Great product.. i wish it had a better description in the error message.", "Text": "I bought this \"used\" and it was registered by someone else(I did not know it was registered already). This prevented me from activating it on my mobile device. Insteon had great tech support though and switched it to my name. The only thing that could have been improved was that the message did not indicate it was already registered so I spent about 30 minutes trying to restarted it and factory reset it before calling support. The error message was like \"unable to connect\". Support was able to tell me the issue right way."}
{"Author": "Kai B", "Date": "on July 26, 2017", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Burned out after two years", "Text": "Unit broken suddenly after almost two years of use. Judging by the smell coming from the device a component seems to have burned out.\nLooking at other peoples comments both here on Amazon and the official support forum this seems does not seem to be an uncommon problem."}
{"Author": "StephenML", "Date": "on July 22, 2017", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "The price is right, but you get what you pay for.", "Text": "You'll probably be happier in the long run with a newer technology. The outlet modules also work as repeaters, so strategically placing them can help extend the signal from the base to the light switches or whatever you're trying to control. Unfortunately, the best configuration results in things working about half the time despite much trial and error using different circuits and locations. I set schedules to turn things on or off several times in a row to increase the odds of success, but frequently have an outside light on in the middle of the day or a dark porch at night. This set is tempting because it's cheap, but my experience is that it isn't very reliable. I've been working with home automation for about 25 years."}
{"Author": "Daniel S. Farkas", "Date": "on July 22, 2017", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Crap product in a captive market.", "Text": "I have had to buy two of these for each of two houses as they seem to have a design flaw that causes a component to fail destroying the printed circuit board in the process. However, there is nothing out there I know of to replace it."}
{"Author": "Stephen", "Date": "on July 18, 2017", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Stay far, far away.", "Text": "I sold all of my Insteon devices and completely left the company entirely. I've never owned such unreliable and frustrating technology in my entire life. Plus, looking through their extensive inventory of devices is quite misleading. Only some of them work with the hub.\n\nIf smart lighting is your main focus get Hue or Lutron. I personally have Hue and love it. Lutron has been recommended by my electrician who installs the brand regularly."}
{"Author": "ken", "Date": "on July 18, 2017", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "assume device when used with Amazon alexa. I would ...", "Text": "assume device when used with Amazon alexa. I would give it 5 stars except it made me retrain for all my devices instead of learning from my computer interface."}
{"Author": "MEM", "Date": "on July 16, 2017", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Windows 10 app is an embarassment", "Text": "The Insteon system is a challenging one, even for someone with a lot of tech experience. That aside, the Windows 10 app has limited functionality, very limited. Moreover its limited functionality is unreliable and quirky. I wonder that the Insteon people are not embarrassed by it. By the way, I found their help services very good. And they are fully aware -- even disgusted -- with the Windows 10 app problems. The staff is doing their best. Why is it that those in positions of responsibility do not address this problem? If you plan to use an Insteon system, you should have a smartphone to run it and then don't expect a seamless operation."}
{"Author": "Sabba Efie", "Date": "on July 12, 2017", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Must be Better", "Text": "If you have a problem - \"Forgetaboutit\" The technicians, for the most part speak with an Indian-English accent and are not easily understood. I sent the Starter Kit back."}
{"Author": "Bob Winfield", "Date": "on July 12, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "wonderful, fabulous", "Text": "Peachy, wonderful, fabulous, couldn't live without it!!!"}
{"Author": "Senior reader", "Date": "on July 6, 2017", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Cannot connect Insteon Hub 2245-22 to Kindle.", "Text": "I had an Insteon Hub Model 2242-222 that would allow me to connect and control devices with the Insteon app that was installed on my Amazon Kindle. With the new Model Insteon Hub 2245-222, I can no longer sync with that Insteon app. Is there a different Insteon app that I can download and add to my Kindle that will allow me to control the devices in my home."}
{"Author": "George Sharp Jr", "Date": "on July 6, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Excellent Home Automation Add On", "Text": "Bought a second setup for my out building. The house and out building now have designated Insteon hubs. This makes administration easier to do and keeps my automations organized. I am also using a mix of the old X10 technology."}
{"Author": "George Sharp Jr", "Date": "on July 6, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Great Product.", "Text": "I love this starter kit. I am building my automated home with this."}
{"Author": "Amazon Customer", "Date": "on July 5, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "This works great with Alexa"}
{"Author": "Ocean Fresh Vacation Rentals", "Date": "on July 4, 2017", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "This product does not work well. Does not always ...", "Text": "This product does not work well. Does not always connect to the various accessories that you are supposed to control.\n\nOff-shore customer service knows very little about the product."}
{"Author": "Dane M", "Date": "on June 30, 2017", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Works as advertised, but expect a 1-4 second delay to power on or off. Sometimes no response at all. Works with harmony", "Text": "Works as advertised spread throughout a 1800 sq foot home. I am using them to power LED strips and controlling them from my cell phone and mostly my harmony remote. there is a noticeable delay of 1-4 seconds and sometimes they dont respond at all unfortunately. But they do work. The delay exists on the Insteon app (android) as well as the harmony remote. the Insteon App is horrible. It should be properly written."}
{"Author": "Amazon Customer", "Date": "on June 26, 2017", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "didn't actually know you needed the hub for the camera...", "Text": "I needed this to hook up the insteon camera I bought. I can't seem to get the camera to work with wifi but this works well with turning on and shutting off lamps when I need them to do so."}
{"Author": "Joel Peterson", "Date": "on June 14, 2017", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Long time Insteon user, very disappointed this time.", "Text": "First of all, I'm a big fan of Insteon and have been since I started using their products in 2013. However, my system recently stopped working for no apparent reason and after spending a couple hours on the phone with Insteon Customer Service the representative stated that he had determined that my hub (2242-222) had failed and needed to be replaced; he suggested I replace it with the 2245-222 which is what came in this Starter Kit. Upon installation of the new hub, I had the SAME ERRORS! Then I was told the PC based control (HouseLinc) was no longer supported and that I would now be able to set up everything on my phone, and that it would be very easy. I asked about all the scenes I have created for the 35 Insteon devices I'm running and was told I would have to recreate them, but that I can do it on my phone and it would be very easy... So, with step by step instruction with Customer Service on the line, I connected to two of my devices in just over 45 minutes of frustration, and repetition. The technician kept suggesting that I probably need to buy a wifi extender, even though I explained to him several times that I'd been using the system for 3+ years without issue, and there were no recent changes in the home that would affect line signal nor WiFi signal. In fact, three other devices I was attempting to pair were within arm's reach of the hub, and on separate powerline phases (and I also have an Insteon powerline phase coupler)\nI was unable to pair ANY other devices.\nI kept this kit because the two dimmer modules would have cost me more than the kit, and I wanted those anyway. I've since upgraded my hub to the ISY994i/IR Pro. Now I'm back to setting things up with a PC (happily), and the new hub is working flawlessly with much more functionality than I had with the Insteon Hub.\n\nSide note; the Insteon tech guys can be very difficult to understand."}
{"Author": "K. JOHNSON", "Date": "on June 13, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Great!", "Text": "Great!"}
{"Author": "windsurfer", "Date": "on June 9, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "a must have", "Text": "a must have if you are using insteon system in your home"}
{"Author": "Vijay Chitkara", "Date": "on June 8, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Good buy", "Text": "A great advance from the ISY technology. Easy to install and set up."}
{"Author": "David Maw", "Date": "on June 7, 2017", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "so too bad I guess)", "Text": "The feature I wanted (network time) worked well, but it wouldn't connect to my old low-res Insteon IP camera (which is no longer supported, so too bad I guess)."}
{"Author": "Zeta", "Date": "on June 7, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "Great deal. Good quality product"}
{"Author": "G. Childers", "Date": "on June 4, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Good product. Could use more engineering.", "Text": "Replaced my first hub which died right at 2 years of service."}
{"Author": "Robert K. Rueckert", "Date": "on May 31, 2017", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Three Stars", "Text": "ok pain in the neck"}
{"Author": "JCooJr", "Date": "on May 30, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Easy to Install", "Text": "Great kit to start with. Easy to set-up and get going."}
{"Author": "JCooJr", "Date": "on May 30, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Works As Advertised, and Reliable", "Text": "Perfect set to start Insteon. I have three Insteon systems installed in various locations. They are reliable and do exactly as advertised."}
{"Author": "Gary I", "Date": "on May 29, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "OK"}
{"Author": "Happy in the OC", "Date": "on May 28, 2017", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "The user interface on the hubv1&v2 is poor. Communication on the hubv2 is inconsistent enough that ...", "Text": "I give up after 10 +years. After buying Smartlinc, Ezflora, Smarthub gen1, Smarthub gen2, Gen1(switches, modules, plugs, inline modules),Gen2 switches, modules,plugs,range extender), I have realized the following: I keep needing to buy more to keep the same or lower functionality. All of yhe products fail after 3-4 years. The user interface on the hubv1&v2 is poor. Communication on the hubv2 is inconsistent enough that it will leave you lights on indefinitely. The ramp rate on dimmer switches are aways changing of accidental user presses. The contact closures in the switches stop working requring hard presses until they fail completely. Finally I am an idiot for wasting all this time and money on Insteon. Don't be me."}
{"Author": "Dane B.", "Date": "on May 27, 2017", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Unreliable junk", "Text": "Unreliable junk. Wasted days of my life messing with it. Giving up."}
{"Author": "Code Cowboy", "Date": "on May 23, 2017", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Could be much better", "Text": "Handy, but very slow and it just died a week ago. Not sure why it is so slow to update all the light status in the app. Maybe its the app that is slow or Insteon protocol itself. either way it takes a couple minutes to check the status of the lights in my house ~30 lights."}
{"Author": "TBDBITL", "Date": "on May 21, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "Excellent product and they are always updating it."}
{"Author": "Michael", "Date": "on May 19, 2017", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "My first hub went bad and after several phone calls I was finally authorized ...", "Text": "So wish I had NOT invested in Insteon. My first hub went bad and after several phone calls I was finally authorized a replacement since the hub was still under warranty. The 2nd hub came and now I can't get it to work with Alexa. I called the company again and their rep I talked with was unable to help me so they have \"escalated\" the issue. As if the product wasn't a problem you have to deal with individuals that speak very poor english. Between their accents and lack of language knowledge it is extremely hard to understand them. The one today, for instance, insisted he was good at speaking english when he most assuredly was NOT. My recommendation.............buy something else."}
{"Author": "michael h", "Date": "on May 16, 2017", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Good luck getting it to work", "Text": "Mind nummingly difficult to use. All I wanted to do was set multiple outlets to turn on and off each day and work on dimming percentage of power, all which this product is capable of achieving. Good luck getting it to work. It never kept a schedule, dimming was set then eliminated by the device. Called Insteon and was told I had to set up scenes for this to work. I read the directions, set up a scene and it worked one day. The next day....nothing. You have to set up devices, rooms, scenes, and all conflict with each other. For such a simple task, this product will make you wish you purchased the old school wall outlet timers. At least they worked, were simple to use and were reliable. Insteon support was useless and could not walk me through the issue. I have purchased hundreds of items from Amazon and consider myself technically inclined. This is the first product that I had no resolution and consider a pure waste of money. It's now in a drawer. Next stop in the trash can."}
{"Author": "FORENSIC DTS, Inc.", "Date": "on May 10, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "Love this product, works EASILY to Alexa"}
{"Author": "Kyle T.", "Date": "on May 8, 2017", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Defective Out of the Box", "Text": "One of the dimmers was defective out of the box. Customer service was no help in getting it replaced, and simply didn't seem to care their product was sold in broken condition. The one dimmer that did work was nice. Not worth the price though. Plenty of competitor products that do a much better job for less money."}
{"Author": "Stacy L.", "Date": "on May 1, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "Easy install and works perfectly"}
{"Author": "Amazon Customer", "Date": "on April 30, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Need this to use your insteon products", "Text": "Works very well, but sucks that you need this to use your products"}
{"Author": "Raymond C. Cauchon", "Date": "on April 29, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Smart Way to SEE your home with these devicees!!!", "Text": "Excellent product with two controllers and now a spare hub. Great Deal."}
{"Author": "tbrengel", "Date": "on April 29, 2017", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Insteon Junk", "Text": "This is JUNK!!! I ordered one of these last year and it worked for a few months. Then I had a water heater start leaking and no alarm from Insteon. upon inspection, I found that the hub had failed, apparently on the same day the water heater started leaking. thinking that failures were rare, stupid me ordered another one in January of this year. Now, it too has the same problem, \"Fail Connecting to Hub.\" I've spent hours trying to get it to work, but note that the response from the app is the same whether the hub is on or off. There has been no response from Insteon, so I guess that this is not an exceptional situation. In any case I am done with Insteon equipment."}
{"Author": "JACK-0", "Date": "on April 27, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "EXCELLENT"}
{"Author": "Chris Hall", "Date": "on April 26, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "It works as advertised", "Text": "It seems like there are few things that just work as advertised. This product meets and exceeds expectations. It works amazingly well. Because of the size of our home network, I have a switch installed on the opposite end of our house from our router. The location is about as far away from our breaker box as it can be. Yet despite all of this, the device works perfectly. I can control my lights from my iPhone at home on the wi-fi or when we are gone. I can use my iPad and even my Apple Watch to turn on and off lights. Works great with Amazon Alexa as long as you name things correctly in the app. I put off buying this for years but when my wife got me an Alexa for a gift, I knew this was the next step. No complaints about anything. Just a great product."}
{"Author": "Cliente de Amazon", "Date": "on April 25, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "Los materiales llegaron incompletos as\u00ed:"}
{"Author": "Masco81", "Date": "on April 24, 2017", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Insteon for Smarthome Enablement", "Text": "I'm a big Insteon user and overall love their products. This hub is a replacement for the exact same model that died after 2 years; not sure what happened. My only ask would be to somehow make it easy to transfer products from one hub to another."}
{"Author": "Russell Beard", "Date": "on April 22, 2017", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "STOP DO NOT ORDER THIS HUB!!!!!!", "Text": "If you have panels more than a few years old this won't work. No where, in their documentation does it say that! Everything I could find says it supports six and eight button panels and that is all. Now Insteon support is saying my 8 button panels cannot be configured by this hub because they are too old. Probably a good piece of information that should be included in the specifications or documentation of comparability... WHICH I READ!!!!!\nMaybe they don't document the facts on purpose....sell you the hub...now you have to spend another two or three hundred dollars to replace perfectly good switches... pretty slick indeed."}
{"Author": "Shackman", "Date": "on April 21, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Consistent Performance", "Text": "Very happy with the functionality and performance. Will be switching my other home (currently X10) over this summer possibly!"}
{"Author": "L. Clair", "Date": "on April 21, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Easy to install, no issues. Great flexibility and secure.", "Text": "If your looking to get your feet wet in home automation, this is a good place to start. I plugged the hub into my network and installed the dimmer modules with no issues. Once I figured out some of the initial settings on the dimmers, setting scenes was pretty easy. It's works with my Nest and Alexa. The one thing I did discover, if you want to use it with Alexa, keep the names of the lamps and scenes simple.\n\nI also was able to get this to work with IFTTT and Stringify. Both of these apps let you control your Insteon products based on something else as a trigger. For example, when my Nest goes into AWAY mode and it's after sunset, it will turn the living room light on so the house looks occupied. The possibilities are limitless when you integrate these apps.\n\nAnother selling point of the Insteon system is network security. A friend of mine has a WEMO, when I was at his house, on his wifi, I downloaded the WEMO app and was able to control his lights, change his programming, etc. The Insteon system requires a password to access. So you don't have to worry about friends or family messing with your lights.\n\nI will be buying more Insteon products because I like the safety and security they bring. I do wish they weren't so expensive tho."}
{"Author": "Jules Weber", "Date": "on April 19, 2017", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Four Stars", "Text": "works"}
{"Author": "Gary", "Date": "on April 18, 2017", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Two Stars", "Text": "won't connect not very user friendly messages"}
{"Author": "Ken M", "Date": "on April 15, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "I love it!", "Text": "My whole house is insteon...I love it!"}
{"Author": "Fournell", "Date": "on April 14, 2017", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Beware", "Text": "Broke right at 2 years, Insteon strung me along for 1 month then said they couldn't replace it. Don't buy their products, bought their camera, never worked, light switch same thing never worked. Thermostats worked really well, but without the hub they are just overpriced thermostats. Customer support really stinks too, not a fan of these products. If you buy from 3rd party like Amazon they will only replace a malfunctioning unit if you buy a new one and have your old one shipped back to insteon, then they said they would reimburse. Beware!"}
{"Author": "D. Jordan", "Date": "on April 9, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Nice Product", "Text": "Going on three months with the hub and have had no issues to date."}
{"Author": "love2ridehd", "Date": "on April 8, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Insteon Kit is a Hit ! ! !", "Text": "This was bought as a Christmas gift. They just loved it and now have moved on to install other switches as well."}
{"Author": "ZotScott", "Date": "on April 7, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Has been running for a few months now with no ...", "Text": "Has been running for a few months now with no issues. I connected Alexa to it and I have voice activated lighting (super convenient not to have to get out of bed to turn off the lights).\n\nMy only mild annoyance is that you can't schedule two actions at the same time. You can work around this by creating a scene, but it just seems silly that you have to go through the trouble. There are definitely times when scenes are desirable, but not always."}
{"Author": "Clayton", "Date": "on April 5, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Very reliable and easy to set up", "Text": "Insteon is the way to go for home automation. Very reliable and easy to set up. Great for beginner automators!"}
{"Author": "kellen", "Date": "on March 31, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Best option for amazon Alexa home control", "Text": "I use it with amazon Alexa and it works near flawlessly. I also have a LIFX bulb which cuts in and out all the time. Can't recommend enough!!"}
{"Author": "Shawn E.", "Date": "on March 31, 2017", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Magic When Functional (but it's not always functional)", "Text": "It works well enough I suppose, however it lacks Wifi capabilities. The Insteon uses it's own proprietary wireless protocol to communicate with connected products (in my case an Insteon dimmer switch). This is fine, it just means that the device needs to be connected to the network via an ethernet cable, which in my case is on the opposite side of my home and on a different floor than the switch it is controlling. The distance between the control hub and dimmer switch causes the hub to periodically lose connectivity with the switch, effectively disabling the ability to control the lights from my phone or amazon echo. The larger issue is that the Insteon app doesn't register the connectivity problems, and will simply hang when attempting to complete an action (such as dimming the lights) until the connection is established. It's mildly frustrating, and is direct bi-product of using proprietary protocols over conventional wifi standards to communicate with remote nodes.\n\nThe negative aspects aside, when the device is working the effect is pretty flipping awesome. I can tell my Amazon Echo to dial in any light level I want from 1-100%. You can even set the fade delay, so the transition between light level settings can be instant or dramatically slow. The app isn't quite as nice other smart home devices, but it works."}
{"Author": "PTAaron", "Date": "on March 30, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Great starter kit for home automation!", "Text": "I picked this up because at the time the price for the kit was less than half the price of a hub alone - and I'm glad I did because it is awesome!\n\nThis hub allows for control of any Insteon product, but does not control x10 - which is not a deal breaker for me as I only have 1 x10 device.\n\nHub setup is very simple - everything is done through the app once you connect it to the network. Setting up scenes, schedules, and setting up devices as controllers for other devices is all extremely easy with the app.\n\nI love that I can connect to the hub from literally anywhere I have an internet connection to check the status of my Insteon devices.\n\nAnother big bonus for me is that this hub is extremely easy to control in Kodi if you are a home theater computer user. The add on CinemaVision lets you control Insteon scenes as a part of the movie experience. I did a write up on how to set it up over on the CinemaVision forum if anyone needs it.\n\nPros: easy setup; remote access is nice; so many options...\nCons; doesn't control X10"}
{"Author": "Christopher J. Shaker", "Date": "on March 24, 2017", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Not wonderful", "Text": "Like Presidential candidates, it sounds better than it is. This is my fourth home automation system, and it's got the most unreliable link to Insteon devices that I've used. I've even added four Insteon range extenders around the house, and connectivity is unreliable. I had all devices showing green in the device status page. Now, two weeks later, it is only talking to the Insteon range extenders and to the remote controlled outlet for my hot water circulation pump. WTF?"}
{"Author": "T.T.", "Date": "on March 23, 2017", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Terrible Support", "Text": "Terrible company and support. Account setup and creation was never able to fully \"go through\" to Insteon. This happened three more times, using two different phones, and three different email addresses. Support staff were unable to assist in any way other than repeating basic troubleshooting methodology (turn it off, turn it on, do a reset). Decided to send it back when they asked me to create an email address to try adding a fourth account. Still waiting on a \"cal from an expert\" I was told to expect six days ago. There are huge issues on Insteon's backend and authentication process which they are not addressing. Not worth the headache."}
{"Author": "Jackie T.", "Date": "on March 23, 2017", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "they were a big help and it works fine once I got it set up", "Text": "Had to call support because I am using a Samsung phone, they were a big help and it works fine once I got it set up."}
{"Author": "William E. Laughlin", "Date": "on March 20, 2017", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Very limited use product", "Text": "Package was on time and in good condition. Was just a little disappointed with the limitations of the hub. Very basic and will not do a lot of things I would have liked to have done."}
{"Author": "Joe P.", "Date": "on March 19, 2017", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Don't do it!", "Text": "Don't do it. There's a lot of reasons for why this isn't a great system. The biggest issue for me was that I could never get it to work. In addition to the useless nature of this poorly designed system the app wouldn't stop alerting me that it has disconnected from the base once I left my house."}
{"Author": "Jon L, South Carolina", "Date": "on March 19, 2017", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "READ AND TRUST THE REVIEWS- STAY AWAY!", "Text": "DO NOT BUY THIS INSTEON SYSTEM! The system does not perform. The installation instructions are not clear on what needs to be done for it to work properly. Upon calling tech support and finally getting someone on the phone I was able to get clear instructions on how to install everything. I wanted the hub in my Tech Closet out of sight with the rest of my hubs and servers, etc... Unfortunately there \"was too much noise on the electrical circuit.\" For the system to work and for the app to see and connect to the components it sends/receives signal through the house's electrical circuits. And with too much \"noise\" on that circuit in the closet the hub was not able to communicate effectively with the other components. The hub must have an ethernet connection to the router therefore WIFI is only used for the app to connect with the hub. Once I found a circuit with an ethernet connection near by (which is in my living room where everyone can see, much to the chagrin of my wife) I was actually able to get everything to work fine- for about a month. Now all of a sudden it stopped working for no reason. NOTHING HAS CHANGED!!!! I am done with this junk. I do not feel like spending another hour or so on the phone with tech support only to tell me I have to move it again."}
{"Author": "Bruce Lyon", "Date": "on March 17, 2017", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Not bad", "Text": "I upgraded to the Hub after my ancient USB serial hub connected to my PC gave up the ghost after over 10 years of service. I dithered between getting another USB serial PC hub and this newer hub. Decided it was time to get this all off my PC and onto my Android phone.\n\nFor the most part, I am very happy. The only shortcoming is one can not set sunrise or sunset times with an add or subtract time. I prefer things that come on at sunset be sunset minus 30 minutes so they come on before it's dark. But this is nitpicking. I just choose a set time and adjust it every month. No big deal now that I have the app on all my Android devices.\n\nI hope they do eventually build in the extra timer features that are in the old PC software but for now, it is good enough and it is nice to be freed from. The PC only software."}
{"Author": "Mike W", "Date": "on March 16, 2017", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Pretty good product", "Text": "Works well with the Echo, but there is one small problem. My bedroom lamp flickers at times and that didn't happen before installing the Insteon products."}
{"Author": "jon and michelle", "Date": "on March 15, 2017", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Stopped working after one year.", "Text": "I really loved this, but after one year it just stopped working. Indicator light doesn't even turn on."}
{"Author": "brett h boeckel", "Date": "on March 15, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "Works great with my water sensors."}
{"Author": "KenL", "Date": "on March 14, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "happy", "Text": "Item as listed, happy customer"}
{"Author": "Amazon Customer", "Date": "on March 14, 2017", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "The Insteon Hub was easy to set up", "Text": "The Insteon Hub was easy to set up, I had a little trouble with the programing of the Leak detectors, I called tech services and they help me, they were very knowledgeable"}
{"Author": "AtlantaDan", "Date": "on March 14, 2017", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Good home control", "Text": "Got this to replace one which died just a few months out of warranty. They are easy to use for small to medium set ups. The app on iPhone is OK but just OK. It is limited in flexibility with things like multiple cameras or more than one thermostat. Things like the name of the device affect it's order in the displays."}
{"Author": "Amazon Customer", "Date": "on March 13, 2017", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Terrible customer support", "Text": "Their instructions are terrible and Insteon support will not stand by their products to help the customers to configure them properly.\n\nWait times for Insteon support are up to 65 minutes (have seen this a few times) and once they pick up they will do anything to not help the customer by saying that \"it is not supported\". \"If you do not like it, return the product\" is the typical response from them.\n\nWorse customer service ever!"}
{"Author": "Tyler", "Date": "on March 11, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "Does what it's meant to do."}
{"Author": "Maryellen T Rowley", "Date": "on March 11, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Great starter set for ease of use and additional security.", "Text": "Great starter set. Simple to set up...did it myself. Works well. I have added additional bulbs and light switch. Good customer service."}
{"Author": "Robert Brunelle", "Date": "on March 9, 2017", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "One Star", "Text": "junk"}
{"Author": "Chopper", "Date": "on March 8, 2017", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Very disappointing.", "Text": "I should have read the reviews more closely. I usually do but when I got an Alexa to get my Spotify client off my MacPro and learned that it supported my Insteon lighting I jumped without looking.\n\nLet me preface the review by noting that I've been an Insteon product user since the company's first releases. In fact, my house was all X10 protocol for years before Insteon became available and I replaced all those X10 devices with Insteon. For years I've been running my Insteon devices on my Mac Pro via the Indigo 6 software and an Insteon PowerLinc 2413U controller. I initially did run into issues with noisy lines (I have several computers here) and signals not bridging across the power legs but I added two pairs of repeaters to installation and those problems went away.\n\nI received the Hub last week and was initially stoked that it was so small and easy to install. It also managed to pair up with the internet and my phone without incident. I was a happy guy. My thrill was short-lived when it failed to recognize the first device I tried to install which was running fine under Indigo. Then the second. The third was successful. Then more misses.\n\nAfter trying to install 23 currently-working Insteon devices in my house the Hub managed to link to only 13 of them. I repeated the attempts over and over again. No luck.\n\nSo I called the Hub tech support number (without a doubt the noisiest and most obnoxious \"hold\" music I've ever experienced) and spoke with a drone who blindly walked me through a knowledge base tree, asking me several times to restate my problem, asking whether I'd tried doing something we'd already just done. Attention Span: zero. Example: \"Okay, you should uninstall and reinstall the phone app. That should fix it.\" \"Dood, you just had me do that five minutes ago and the only thing that happened was that I lost 45 minutes of work adding those devices!\" The call ended with the drone saying that he had nothing else to try and promising me that a senior engineer would call me the next day, which unsurprisingly did not happen.\n\nStay away from this product. Maybe it will work for a tiny apartment using simple lamp modules but it's definitely not capable of managing a larger and more diverse Insteon installation like I have here.\n\nIn addition, I received an email last week from Insteon announcing updates to this product and was told to expect them to be installed automatically between May 2 and May 5. I was hoping this might fix at least some of the issues with this device. However, here is it May 7 and no updates were received.\n\nSix months later: I did another Hub update. It still fails to recognize half of my Insteon installation even though Indigo has no problems with it. Hopefully a competitor will see the potential market here because this company has clearly has no interest in fixing its broken product."}
{"Author": "Bubba Lipscomb", "Date": "on March 7, 2017", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "thought that this would be a great purchase to get started with my smarthome set up ...", "Text": "thought that this would be a great purchase to get started with my smarthome set up\nand it was until I plugged in one of the switches and of the two only one worked.\ngreat was to stay in business selling products that only work 50% ....called Smarthome\nand they want me to buy another module to replace the defective one and then wait for\n7 to 10 or 15 days for them to get defective module back to them and them issue me a\nrefund....gave them 3 stars but am going to lower it to two as I think how cheap that is and\nthe inconvenience in having to pay and wait for a refund for their defective product."}
{"Author": "Thomas P.", "Date": "on March 5, 2017", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Three Stars", "Text": "Insteon controllers don't consistently work with LED bulbs. App is poorly done, look for 3rd party apps."}
{"Author": "Stefano", "Date": "on March 5, 2017", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Very poor quality system", "Text": "Terrible product. Sensors lose connection and you have no idea. Water leak sensors are badly designed - I have three in front of me and spent last hour trying to get them to work and no way; they have just stopped working and/or stopped talking to the hub. Overall this sustem is really poor quality."}
{"Author": "Chris", "Date": "on March 4, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Works great with my Echo!", "Text": "This INSTEON starter kit tied to my Echo works GREAT!! I absolutely love it!! My kids love to turn the lights on and off with our Echo. I have scenes setup for the lights to go on and off when I'm not at home. I also love the fact I can be across the Country and turn my lights on and off (and see if they are on) from the app on my phone. I have an Echo, but bought this and an Echo Dot (for my bedroom) to control lights. From un-boxing to getting everything working took only about 15 minutes! FYI..it's cheaper to buy a 2nd starter kit for the plug-in modules than it is to just buy the plug-in modules by themselves."}
{"Author": "Leslie D.", "Date": "on March 2, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Works fantastic with Echo", "Text": "Just purchased a Echo device and added this item. Works fantastic ! Easy to set up (if you are tech savvy) This is a cool addition to my home"}
{"Author": "luis e. figueredo", "Date": "on March 2, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Insteon HUB", "Text": "good price and fast delivery"}
{"Author": "Scott K", "Date": "on March 1, 2017", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Just Ok", "Text": "I am giving this 3 stars because of the software. The hardware seems very high quality and reliable, but the software leaves a bit to be desired. A simple task like turning on two lights at the same time is a pain - you must create a \"scene\" with both devices to turn on at the same time, then it gets more cumbersome if you want them to turn off at different times. Another annoyance is there is no adjustment for sunset or sunrise to fine tune the times for your exact location. Other software such as X10, allow you to enter minutes before or after, from the pre-programmed times. Like I mentioned, I'd give the hardware a 5 star rating, but software is no more than a two star rating. Update - software is horrible, not at all user friendly, software is zero stars. Tired of fighting with it."}
{"Author": "J. Hirschman", "Date": "on February 26, 2017", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Amazon sells returned devices as new", "Text": "The device works very well for me (more than 25 devices connected so far), but the setup was a nightmare because my hub had already been registered by someone else in Insteon's database. Insteon's software does not deal well with that, and gave me the error message: \"Something's wrong: Something went wrong while configuring your hub.\" (Picture attached)\n\nInsteon's support is closed most of the weekend, so I was left to interpret that not-very-helpful clue, since that popped up no matter\n\nAfter a day trying to debug, including completely restructuring my wifi network to eliminate that as the source, I found a forum article where someone had a corrupted entry in Insteon's database and saw the same message. I contacted Insteon and they had it fixed by Monday, saying that the problem was not corruption, but that someone else had their information in for my hub.\n\nFrustrating that I thought I was buying a brand-new hub from Amazon, but they obviously sent me a used or returned one. when they do this, they should at least let Insteon know, so they can clear the database entry."}
{"Author": "Jeffro", "Date": "on February 25, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Works perfect with Alexia!", "Text": "Works perfect with Alexia!"}
{"Author": "Chris", "Date": "on February 25, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Great Deal!", "Text": "What a deal. 1 Insteon hub 2245-222 and 2 dimmer modules. The MSRP on the is like $150. All for $39.50 and free shipping. I bought this to replace my hub of 2 years that died. I did have problems setting it up as I had to delete my account and all that good stuff. (you will figure this out if you are upgrading) However Smarthome had me going in about 2 hours. They deleted my account as I could not. Smarthome was extremely helpful. Apparently there is currently a problem with their back end server and Android devices. Seems to set up better on iOS. I would not know. Smarthome had me take a picture of the hub and send it to them and they set it up. I started on this on a Friday afternoon and figure it would be going the next week. Wrong. I was up and running in a few hours. Thank you Smarthome!"}
{"Author": "Marvin Lipschitz", "Date": "on February 23, 2017", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "I have had it for many many months, it works about 80% of the time. The other 20% and I just leave the lights off.", "Text": "I have had it for many many months, it works about 80% of the time. The other 20% and I just leave the lights off.\n\nEDIT:\nIt Eventually stopped working entirely. Setting it up is so complex, that I am throwing out my 2 dimmers, hub and remote, rather than trying to figure out why it stopped working. I'm switching to the Z-Wave standard."}
{"Author": "R. Jonker", "Date": "on February 22, 2017", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Reasonable, not excellent", "Text": "Despite description online it does not support Sonos integration"}
{"Author": "Dr.Denim", "Date": "on February 22, 2017", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Basic functionalitly ok, outdated app. Not recommended.", "Text": "It sort of works, but the Android app (haven't tried others) is ugly, hard to use and looks like it's from the 90s. I'm only using this for a single smokebridge to get notifications in case of a fire. But when testing, the delay to notification is so long I'm not sure how much use it would be! The app is pretty useless otherwise; it only shows the smokebridge, saying \"all clear\". That's the only functionality! It once said low battery, but can't tell me where, how many smoke detectors I have (it should know right?) or let me do anything else. Does anyone even work on this anymore?\n\nAt least it was a minimum investment to learn I will not hook up a security system or door lock (lol) to this antiquated, never-updated system."}
{"Author": "Bayou Reader", "Date": "on February 22, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Good price for Insteon.", "Text": "I have been satisfied with Insteon technology for years. I am always looking for discounted prices on their products. This Home Starter Kit was on sale whereby the total cost was less than the individual Dimmer Modules. I ordered and saved money even without the need for the Hub."}
{"Author": "Amazon Customer", "Date": "on February 21, 2017", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Be ready to use tech support", "Text": "Took forever with tech support to set up. Loses connection from time."}
{"Author": "Andy B.", "Date": "on February 18, 2017", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "You'll be happy until it doesn't work anymore.", "Text": "Another suckers bet brought to you by the frauds at Insteon. Their hardware sucks, their software sucks. Don't be suckered by the dream of an automated home. Shop for an alternate technology."}
{"Author": "Sbrundle", "Date": "on February 17, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Buy it for home automation!!", "Text": "This works so well and was easy as pie to setup. I wish it could have had more modules."}
{"Author": "Dbreezy209", "Date": "on February 17, 2017", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Great Hub!", "Text": "I needed to upgrade to this hud since my other hub that still worked is now outdated. Insteon makes great products, just wished they would allow for software upgrade options so that I could've continued to use my original hub that still works. Other than the hub, I have Insteon switches and they all work great with my Alexa."}
{"Author": "Jaster Tan", "Date": "on February 16, 2017", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "One Star", "Text": "Does not work at all. Failed to connect to hub."}
{"Author": "Mauricio Santacruz", "Date": "on February 15, 2017", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Four Stars", "Text": "The box was not in a good state but the product was excellent. thanks"}
{"Author": "Within Reason", "Date": "on February 15, 2017", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Do not purchase this product.", "Text": "If you ignore that advice, I advise you to NOT attempt to set up the hub with the Android app. Use the iOS or Windows app.\n\nIf you ignore that advice, I advise you to stop now, return this and buy something else. If you try to set it up using the Android app, there is a good chance the hub will not be able to properly register with your account (even if you switch to one of the other apps) and you will have to call Insteon customer support. Their customer support is competent, and the first question they ask is \"Did you try to set up using Android?\" but you will spend quite some time on hold (over an hour for me today) before you get to talk to anyone. You'll spend another half hour or so with support, getting your account registered and the firmware updated. You'll need to email a picture of the QR code on the bottom of the hub, so make sure you have that ready.\n\nIf you ignore that advice, and are able to connect to the hub, I advise you to give up and return this before things go any further.\n\nIf you ignore that advice, any damage or injury to your home, pets, or loved ones caused by Insteon equipment being thrown in frustration is entirely your own fault, I tried to warn you. Because what's going to happen is this: either one or both of the modules will fail to reliably connect to the hub. You'll find it will show as Status:Unknown. It will randomly turn on and off. You'll be unable to add it to Scenes. You'll try everything: switching it with the one that is working, to see if it's a signal or line noise problem. Performing a factory reset. Putting it on a sine-wave UPS. Putting the hub on a sine-wave UPS. Checking sunspot activity. You'll call customer support, who will suggest that there's some sort of signal interference or line noise, while not explaining why the other module works OK in the same outlet, connected to the same lamp. In the meanwhile, the hub will continue make annoying beeps and cause lights to randomly turn on and off.\n\nIf you ignore that advice, you'll find that you've spent the better part of a day and a half struggling with what should have been plug-and-play but still doesn't work correctly. You'll box it all up, return it, and hopefully write a review that will save the next poor sap who is considering buying this."}
{"Author": "Franka60", "Date": "on February 14, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "Great price."}
{"Author": "Allison schiller", "Date": "on February 13, 2017", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Extremely disappointed", "Text": "Hour and a half waiting on hold for customer service, I ended up giving up. Cannot connect to hub. Extremely disappointed"}
{"Author": "Amazon Customer", "Date": "on February 12, 2017", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Three Stars", "Text": "Does not work with camera and cell phone router"}
{"Author": "Steven G. Ricketts", "Date": "on February 11, 2017", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Brick. Nothing more, nothing less", "Text": "Waited on HOLD for 45 minutes. Never received any help. They do not stand behind their product obviously. Did not work, no matter what I tried. The setup instructions are terrible."}
{"Author": "Jabon Mojado", "Date": "on February 10, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Very happy", "Text": "Great product.\nEasy to set up.\nIntegrates nicely with Alexa."}
{"Author": "Bradley Strecker", "Date": "on February 8, 2017", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "I think the android application is not good. Unfortunately", "Text": "I think the android application is not good. Unfortunately, I did not look at the reviews until after I purchased it. This has been going on since 2014 with a poor application. I am sure it is probably a good product; however, they need to resolve the application issue."}
{"Author": "B2", "Date": "on February 8, 2017", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Wanted to love it, but as is typical with Insteon the quality is poor", "Text": "I have been a long time user of Insteon products, since around 2006 timeframe and I have over 70 Insteon devices installed. This product peaked my interest as I wanted to use Amazon Echo to control lights. I really wanted to like this device but it is very flakey. I have had to call Insteon support 3 times and each time required resetting my account and starting over. I would also say in general that Insteon quality is sub-standard and if I had to do it over again, I would not choose Insteon for light control. I have had to replace over half of my switches and keypads. I think the keypads are the most prone to failure as I have need to replace them several times. This becomes very costly at an average of around $65/switch. After playing with this hub, I detected that many of my Insteon switches need to be replaced again, so I will be well above 100% replacement in 10 year period of time. I think I am getting about 3-7 years life out of my devices. Look for another solution."}
{"Author": "Viper", "Date": "on February 7, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "Great Product works great"}
{"Author": "Fredster", "Date": "on February 7, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "Works great !"}
{"Author": "Amazon Customer", "Date": "on February 7, 2017", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "I purchased the insteon to act as a bridge between ...", "Text": "I purchased the insteon to act as a bridge between alexa and my x10 home automation system. Insteon required me to create a scene that I could then ask Alexa to ask Insteon to do 'x'. Unfortunately the Insteon app would not allow me to develop scenes as it would not recognise any of the x10 devices i had defined to actually develop a scene. very disappointing."}
{"Author": "tberry146", "Date": "on February 6, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Works great. No issues.", "Text": "I have used this for over a week and I am very happy. I have had no issues with anything or the app (Android). I have added 4 wired dimmer switches and the setup was extremely simple. I use this with the Amazon Echo (ie Alexa turn the lights on/off, dim the lamp. Etc)"}
{"Author": "Patient Shopper", "Date": "on February 6, 2017", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Hub is useful. Failed but was replaced under 2 year warranty.", "Text": "The hub is a useful, though much more limited, backup for my indigo control program running on my imac. The previous hub I had failed -- as apparently is common within first couple of years. It has been replaced under warrantly by Insteon, but the price on this starter kit was so low, that I ordered it so I did not have to wait for the replacement to arrive. I will give the replacement hub as a gift to a friend."}
{"Author": "Someone Astonishing", "Date": "on February 6, 2017", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "INSTEON Tech Support NOT TRAINED ON ALEXA integration. Nice Product, Bad Support, Snotty Help Agent.", "Text": "The Insteon hub and 2 plug kit is a terrific deal. I noticed the price had even dropped a bit one day, so I grabbed the starter kit. It was easy to set up, but when it came to integrating with Alexa, I wasn't sure what I needed to do. There was a nice flyer in the box with their customer service number on it, which I liked. So many companies make it hard to talk to a human. So, I called and asked the agent how to connect Insteon to Alexa. He replied that Alexa isn't their product (rather smart-alecky, too). I told him I knew that, but there weren't any instructions included with the kit, so I needed some help. He again told me that Alexa isn't their product, so \"of course\" they wouldn't include instructions. Well, my TP-Link smart plug included instructions, I told him, and I didn't remember it being terribly difficult. He acted irritated and put me on hold, so he could download the Alexa app. He was not familiar with Alexa AT ALL! All the while, their hold recording keeps telling me how proud they are of working with Amazon's Alexa. While he had me on hold 5 minutes (Seriously?) to download an app, I dug out the TP-Link instructions and all I had to do was enable Insteon as a skill. So simple. Insteon customer service/tech support IS NOT TRAINED ON ALEXA INTEGRATION, AT ALL. So, although the product works very well, I dread the day I have a technical issue."}
{"Author": "RemoteControlCurtain", "Date": "on February 6, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Good product! It works", "Text": "Good product!\nIt works. I have it connected to the Insteon 2450 I/O linkc to the Electric Curtain System CL-920A by Curtain Call found in Amazon.\nNow I can open or close my curtain anywhere in the world!"}
{"Author": "Lani Morrison", "Date": "on February 6, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "Excellent product, bought it @ Christmas! \"Thank You\"!"}
{"Author": "Amazon Customer", "Date": "on February 4, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "Old one stopped functioning after a couple of years. So far, 3 months, works well."}
{"Author": "E.L.", "Date": "on February 4, 2017", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Four Stars", "Text": "this was a gift for someone else."}
{"Author": "Mark K Nahabedian", "Date": "on February 4, 2017", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Requires cloud. Privacy intrusion.", "Text": "I have been using an Instinctive smartlinc for many years and have been read-only happy with it.\n\nI considered replacing it with one of these hubs but ruled it out as soon as I learned that the hub had to be in communication with insteon's cloud servers in order to do anything. Absolutely a NO GO.\n\nInsteon's: please bring back the smartlinc and stop trying to intrude in our lives."}
{"Author": "Cameron Lemuel Mixon", "Date": "on February 4, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Good Value", "Text": "Great price for a hub and two dimmers."}
{"Author": "Kipperdog", "Date": "on February 3, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "This is a great way to get started with an automated house", "Text": "This is a great way to get started with an automated house. The hub sells for $70 and the modules for $50 each. Make sure you buy DIMMING modules unless you know you need ON/OFF. And yes, it talks to Alexa."}
{"Author": "Michael", "Date": "on February 2, 2017", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "I deleted scenes that were set to sunrise and sunset ...", "Text": "I deleted scenes that were set to sunrise and sunset. They still schedule themselves. Yes, I have checked to see if the particular switches that were turning on were part of any scene. No, they aren't."}
{"Author": "D", "Date": "on February 2, 2017", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Don't Wast Your Money!!", "Text": "Junk! Don't waste your money on this product. I purchased this controller hoping to control a few devices, that I purchased at the same time. The only device that actually worked was the water leak detector. The insteon switch item: 2466SW would not connect to controller. The switch would work manually, but what good is that. Customer Service is a joke, although it matches there products. I returned it along with all the devices I purchased, and ordered the Samsung SmartThings hub. Everything installed correctly, and within minutes I had multiple devices working with Alexa. So save yourself some aggravation and order the Samsung SmartThings hub!"}
{"Author": "Paul", "Date": "on January 31, 2017", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "This thing won't get past setup. Internet connection is ...", "Text": "This thing won't get past setup. Internet connection is working perfectly. This hub is showing a green light as being connected. Have tried the phone app, the ipad app, windows store app (ethernet connection) and nothing can see this thing. Have reset this a number of time and it doesn't work. Do yourself favor buy another brand, and stay away from this thing....."}
{"Author": "Jason Howard", "Date": "on January 31, 2017", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Fun to play with. Lots of potential.", "Text": "Used this kit so I could control the Christmas tree with my phone this year. Worked great. I definitely recommend this starter kit for anyone looking to play around and get started with smart home systems. This would be 5 stars if Insteon would combine their two HUBs into 1 - or update their new model so 1 HUB will operate the WIFI cameras and HOMEKIT devices."}
{"Author": "RealtorRon", "Date": "on January 30, 2017", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Samsung recently bought Smarthome and created Smart thing Hub", "Text": "This tech space is changing quickly. Samsung recently bought Smarthome and created Smart thing Hub. Some concern over Insteon upgrades and future compatibility, especially since i upgrade 10-15 in wall switches to control lights. At $40-50 ea it was not cheap. I am hoping that they create a compatibilty bridge for this and Zwave, Zbee products."}
{"Author": "Steven Shull", "Date": "on January 30, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Easy set up too", "Text": "Just as described. Easy set up too!"}
{"Author": "Lost Weekend", "Date": "on January 29, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "This is an easy to use system", "Text": "I'm slowly building up my Insteon home automation. This is an easy to use system. It works with Android, Windows 10 and Windows mobile. Bonus, my Amazon Alexa works with it too. Many device options to work with."}
{"Author": "buf0rd", "Date": "on January 29, 2017", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Great concept. Not for home automation savy.", "Text": "I will start with saying great product. For the plug and play professional it's exactly what is needed. However, like the heading states this is not for the IT savy. This hub doesn't allow any room for integration. If you loose Wan you CANNOT control your system. Wireshark shows a lot of traffic when items not in use. Traffic is leaving home LAN. I can see flaws from a security standpoint and that's enough for me to discontinue use. To each their own."}
{"Author": "James W.", "Date": "on January 28, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "Works great with echo"}
{"Author": "Mike Glupker", "Date": "on January 28, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "Love it"}
{"Author": "AW", "Date": "on January 28, 2017", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Very happy and better than using the poor Elk M1 Gold Insteon firmware...", "Text": "Update right at the 2-year ownership mark. Like many others that have reported, my hub died and has no power. Supposedly the C7 capacitor can be replaced and you might be able to get your hub working again. The bigger problem that is completely STUPID is that you cannot just download your hub configuration from the cloud to a new hub. WHAT?????!!!! Yep, you got it, you have to start over from scratch and it is recommended that you factory reset every single one of your Insteon devices. This is a big red flag that the design decisions at Smarthome have jumped the shark. I have a huge investment in Insteon but sadly will begin looking at migration alternatives off of this platform. The amount of time/effort I enjoy back from the automation is being sunk in managing the horrible design decisions being made by this company. At least my Elk configuration is still available and will be taking the duties back over from the silly Insteon hub design. One star because this appears to be a known issue with this device and starting from scratch is just wrong.\n\n______________________________________\n\nFor many years I've been using a very user unfriendly combination of Elk M1 Gold security panel coupled with a serial module flashed with supporting firmware and the abysmal ElkDroid app that was abandoned by its developer ($99 grrrrrr!!!!!!). The setup has worked but is very painful to use as you have to essentially re-add every device to the Elk if you lose or replace a module due to how it works. Additionally, the Elk does not support scenes and if too many devices are in a rule some or many will not receive or respond to the command. I purchased the hub for a whopping $15 even though the reviews were pretty poor. I have to say I have been nothing but pleased with it. I believe that Smarthome must have had serious issues with the hub at initial rollout and the reviews pretty much reflect a hub without the now updated firmware. Smarthome even notifies me when they plan to do maintenance and/or perform updates via email which is a pleasant surprise. Both the hub and the accompanying android app have allowed me to slowly start moving programming of time-based events off the Elk M1 Gold. The use of scenes is an added bonus which greatly speeds up delivery of commands to devices. Hope these comments help someone on the fence about this device."}
{"Author": "ABQUptown", "Date": "on January 27, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Works great with Amazon Alexa", "Text": "Works great with Amazon Alexa. Easy to install and set up."}
{"Author": "Ryan S", "Date": "on January 26, 2017", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "What a let down", "Text": "I was so hopeful because I had finally found a smart home device that provided Windows PC software for configuration of the device.\n\nHowever, the only thing worse than no Windows PC software interface is a bad Windows PC software interface that results in hours of wasted troubleshooting. This piece of ---- software cannot even find the hub. Both the PC and the hub are wired to the wifi router so it should be extremely simple for the software running on the PC to find the hub, right?"}
{"Author": "David H", "Date": "on January 25, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "Works great"}
{"Author": "Evelyn Rogers", "Date": "on January 25, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "gift"}
{"Author": "Douglas E.", "Date": "on January 25, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "I look forward to purchasing the in-wall switches and other various smart controls from Insteon in the near future", "Text": "Plugged in named each plug through the insteon app. and discovered devices with Alexa. Works exactly as I would expect them to work. Now i have schedules set up to turn on the wife's vanity lights in the morning so she is ready to go when she gets out of the shower and just simply tell Alexa to turn on front room lights as needed. The ability to be able to control when i have already left the house is a plus for the times i forget to turn off the lights. I look forward to purchasing the in-wall switches and other various smart controls from Insteon in the near future."}
{"Author": "D Dutton", "Date": "on January 24, 2017", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Previous owner forgot to delete account with insteon. Once ...", "Text": "Previous owner forgot to delete account with insteon. Once insteon customer service updated the Hub, I competed the setup without any issues."}
{"Author": "Mark F", "Date": "on January 23, 2017", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Disappointment; no customer support", "Text": "In short, Hub did not work no matter what troubleshooting steps I took. I purchased a thermostat, light switch, and lightbulb hoping to start automating my home. Based on later reviews I subsequently read, inferior system, app is poor, and I waited over 90 minutes and no one in customer service ever answered. It's a shame because their product line is extensive, but a total disappointment."}
{"Author": "Ricardo", "Date": "on January 23, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Insteon really works !!", "Text": "Works great. Shudda upgraded a long time ago."}
{"Author": "TC", "Date": "on January 23, 2017", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Not ready for primetime", "Text": "I purchased this along with several other peripherals to put together my own home security. This was next to impossible to set up, didn't work like a home security system should. I ended up returning this and all the peripherals and went with simplisafe."}
{"Author": "David Young", "Date": "on January 22, 2017", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "steer clear of this piece of crap..", "Text": "Junk. Smarthome claims of bunch of PC-based control programs work with this on their website,\nwhen in fact all these programs work for hub made by them previous to this model. Unless you\nhave a 100% Insteon household, steer clear of this piece of crap..."}
{"Author": "Christian Read", "Date": "on January 22, 2017", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Flawless after the firmware update.", "Text": "First and formost, if you can not connect via the app, it's probably due to the firmware being too old to connect to the Hub. Unfortunately you have to call customer support to push the firmware update. The android app is great it gives full control of each device on the network, and the ability to create detailed 'scenes'. Currently installed the 2475F Fanlinc which has both fan and light control. This also allows for control via Amazon Echo."}
{"Author": "Joseph Castonguay", "Date": "on January 20, 2017", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Two Stars", "Text": "Doesn't pickup signal well."}
{"Author": "A. Krumm", "Date": "on January 19, 2017", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Firmware Issuse, Must Call Support for setup.", "Text": "The 2245-222 Hub works fine for me after Calling customer support, the App will not work with the older firmware that came on the Hub. To fix this they had to push a firmware update to my Hub then it work fine, they also remotely setup my account.\nAlso I found that the Android APP will work with old X10 devices but the Windows APP on my computer will not work with X10 devices, nor will Amazons Echo.\n\nSide Note: X10 Support even rudimentary support is a nice bonus when I have 30+ X10 devices from over 15 years."}
{"Author": "R. Thomas", "Date": "on January 19, 2017", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Can someone make a reliable smarthome product?", "Text": "Take a while to get it setup just right. Does not allow more than one device or scene to schedule for sunrise/sunset. Integrates with Alexa, but not perfect. Unreliable as it loses connection with network randomly."}
{"Author": "Tim Ryan", "Date": "on January 19, 2017", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Four Stars", "Text": "Good smart home control, has lots of options and works well with Amazon's Echo/Alexa."}
{"Author": "Greg", "Date": "on January 19, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "Very pleased !!!"}
{"Author": "Amazon Customer", "Date": "on January 18, 2017", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Two Stars", "Text": "Not at all reliable"}
{"Author": "Jean S.", "Date": "on January 18, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Great Controller Hub", "Text": "Easy to install and connect. Our application is to have it control two garden fountains. We can turn on/off either one (separately), or both, using the iPhone from anywhere around the world...yes, a bit over the top, but it's nice to make sure we remembered to turn them off when away from the house."}
{"Author": "Robert Jones", "Date": "on January 17, 2017", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Great - aggravating to control it without the Echo Dot", "Text": "I have 11 lights, plugs, and dimmer modules. Integration of motions sensors is crazy frustrating, as was the iPhone app. Typical response times would be 15-20 seconds if there was even a single device it couldn't communicate with, and 3-5 seconds under best case conditions. Enter Echo Dot. The Dot latency is much lower than either the web app or the iPhone app, and it's great to be able to use voice control. They should bundle the Dot with this product, as it makes it usable. Finally, home automation has arrived."}
{"Author": "lovegreatdeals", "Date": "on January 17, 2017", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "AMONG MY WORST PURCHASES", "Text": "The required app never connected to hub. Constant \"failed connection\" message. I was on hold with Insteon support for 75 minutes. When I finally got to speak with tech person he was unable to resolve issue. Told me to wait a week for them to fix problem. I expect product to work immediately not a week after I buy it. So it was returned. The android app has overall poor reviews. But you need the app in order for it to function. If you buy this product don't hesitate to return it if you have issue."}
{"Author": "Badfinger", "Date": "on January 15, 2017", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Dont waste you time or money and you will piss your ...", "Text": "These are hit and miss to say the least mostly miss ! I finally took them all out , They seemed to work for a few days then it said could not find hub . If it cant find hub you loose evertything . Tech support is non existent ! Dont waste you time or money and you will piss your wife off in the end as well !"}
{"Author": "jrogersmn", "Date": "on January 13, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "and I love it. In contrast to other automation technologies I've ...", "Text": "Have had Insteon switches in my home for quite a while, but just started using the hub for control, and I love it. In contrast to other automation technologies I've tried, Insteon always works (I've never had an issue with a light not going on or a command being missed) and is extremely easy to setup and use. Also very easy to keep adding additional devices - unfortunately for my wallet. It would be nice to have a bit more flexibility in display including the ability to hide scenes, add custom icons (although there are a lot already) and add conditional logic to scenes, but hopefully these and other features will come in future releases."}
{"Author": "Sergio Ivan Castrejon", "Date": "on January 12, 2017", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Ok, but issues when pairs with Echo", "Text": "It's ok for what it does but integration with Echo not so good. If you link it up with Alexa you will get \"Sorry the device \"whatever you name it\" is not responding. Although there's that possibility that it may be the echoes having the issue.Anybody who allows their devices to be \"Alexa compatible\" is also at fault. If you don't have an echo you may be alright. If you do have an echo and plan to use this system with it,let's just say you've been warned."}
{"Author": "AlohaMan", "Date": "on January 11, 2017", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "The Starter kit works great with Alexa", "Text": "Even though Amazon shipped to me a used and returned Insteon Starter Kit when I ordered NEW, (which was evident because all seals were broken, no instructions and cords were in a ziplock bag) the Starter kit works great with Alexa. Scenes must be created in Insteon App and Insteon \"Skills\" enabled in Alexa App for Alexa to interact with hub/plugs. Turns lights on and dims with voice through Alexa. One dimmer module not working on dim, so requested replacement. It is GREAT to control all lights with voice. Also this Starter Kit interacts with X-10 systems which I already have so the extends the system even more. Mahalo Insteon."}
{"Author": "Grant", "Date": "on January 11, 2017", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Two Stars", "Text": "Does not work well with my other smart home devices had to return"}
{"Author": "Amazon Customer", "Date": "on January 9, 2017", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Control all the light switches and plugs or I should say outlet with easy to", "Text": "It was very simple set up right out of the box. Control all the light switches and plugs or I should say outlet with easy to use"}
{"Author": "BPQ", "Date": "on January 9, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "worked right away!"}
{"Author": "Karla Andrew", "Date": "on January 9, 2017", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Replacement...", "Text": "I do love the insteon home controls. I'm only giving this a 4 star because this is a replacement - the last one that was exactly the same type only lasted approx 6 months. I'm not sure if it overheated or what went wrong, but it quit working. We were using the lights hooked to it and needed a new hub. I'm adding the 2 additional wall units to additional lights. It is fairly easy to set up, but because it was a replacement, I had to create a new account with a new email - it wouldn't let me replace since the old unit had completely died. I couldn't log into my previous account.... So set up was a little more complicated and a little frustrating. For a new user it would be worth it though and I wouldn't let my experience dissuade you - as I'm assuming it was a fluke that the unit failed so quickly. My previous insteon had been working for a couple years but doesn't hook to the Alexa unit.... Thus the upgrade."}
{"Author": "1101", "Date": "on January 8, 2017", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "I am glad Amazon will give me my money back", "Text": "I reviewed all the reviews and new the nightmare I was getting into. In the end, I could not configure this device. The Hub properly connected to my home network. To ensure, I reset to factory settings and also reset network settings. The firmware was auto dated by 3 versions and the app would fail every single time at updating it. The problem is the Android App. I am surprise this app even runs.\n\nTo conclude, I am glad Amazon will give me my money back. I should of stuck with WeMo."}
{"Author": "jeffs99", "Date": "on January 8, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Google Home now controls Insteon", "Text": "Works great, being controlled my Harmony Remote, which is in turn controlled by Smartthings Hub which is turn controlled by Google Home. I know it's a bit complicated (and expensive), but it all works."}
{"Author": "SGA", "Date": "on January 7, 2017", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Welcome to hell", "Text": "A bit of background: I'm highly technically capable in electronics, computers, etc. I had the Insteon Hub 2242-222 model with a bunch of lights, sensors, etc. working at my home for nearly a decade. It wasn't easy getting things to work back then, but after adding a couple of range extenders and playing with their locationsThis past Christmas (2016) I was given an Amazon Echo Dot as a gift. Turns out that you need this newer Insteon Hub 2245-222 if you want to control your home through the Echo (e.g. \"Alexa turn off the lights.\").\n\nSo, I bought the 2245-222 and the nightmare began. Since I already had a working Insteon network, I thought it would be easy to just switch out the old hub for a new one. Nope.\n\nFirst, you have to delete all of your scenes, then devices, then your account (why?!) from Insteon before installing this new hub. They recommend that you write down all your device IDs to help. Then, you need to create a new account and start re-linking your devices. (I'd recommend starting with your range extenders first.)\n\nHowever, this time around, these same devices that had been working well before are all having trouble being added through the app. Strangely enough, I can see and hear that they are all communicating with the hub when I press the setup buttons and/or toggle paddles. Yet, in the app, they never completely finish getting properly added. It either doesn't see the device, fails during some part of a 10-part test, or -as in the case of one of my two range extenders- it doesn't recognize the device properly. For example, that second range extender shows up as a device that uses an On/Off toggle rather than showing \"Active\" for its state.\n\nTrying to use the ID numbers that they recommended to save makes no difference. In fact, even with the ID numbers, it seems to have exactly the same issues. Of course, I've tried different outlet locations for the hub and the range extenders. I've tried using an Android and iOS devices to configure. And I've tried to be patient. Very patient. But, you can lose your patience with a product when their Help Line has wait periods of 30 minutes, 60 minutes, or 90 minutes. (Yes, I've tried calling during the weekday and the weekend.)\n\nI'll continue trying to make this work and reaching out to Insteon's tech support (if their wait times improve) and will post the progress here if it improves. But, at this point, I'm regretting my choice to use Insteon for my home automation.\n\nUpdate:\nAfter 3 days of re-configuring my Insteon network to get this to work with it, I finally have a new working solution for all devices except one light switch. There was even more trouble with getting the settings to configure properly on the IOLink module through both the iOS and Android versions of the Insteon for Hub app. The app wouldn't allow you to choose some of the options, even though they were the appropriate combinations for the purpose I was using it for (i.e. a garage door opener). Nevertheless, the correct options combinations sometimes randomly are available. It took me an hour of saving, exiting, editing and saving again, to finally have the correct options available to save the IOLink module configuration.\n\nWorse, after all this which was to allow Alexa to control my Insteon devices, I find out that the IOLink module isn't supported through Alexa. WTF. If the Alexa \"skill\" has access to the Hub, then it should be able to control everything that the Hub controls. But, no.\n\nMy only guess as to why the Insteon skill for Alexa doesn't support the IOLink module and some other devices is because of a potential security risk. Imagine someone walking up to your window and saying, \"Alex, open the garage door!\". Okay, I get that...though I'd rather have the option to secure my system myself. But, why Insteon couldn't build this Hub to learn the previous configuration, I have no idea. Why Insteon couldn't build it to be a drop-in-replacement for the prior hub version, again, I'm at a loss to understand. Why Insteon's app is so crappy, there's no excuse for. Unfortunately for me, I have spent a considerable investment in Insteon's home automation devices, so it's a bit late for me to switch."}
{"Author": "M. YOUNG", "Date": "on January 7, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Easy setup. Works well with echo (alexa). I would highly recommend.", "Text": "Excellent starter kit"}
{"Author": "Murph", "Date": "on January 6, 2017", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Difficult to get working with Alexa / Even more difficult to get support from Insteon!", "Text": "Update 5/9/17 - Hub not receiving updates, again. Contact at Insteon that told me to reach out with any issues is not responding. Still have the original issue periodically. Where the Hub update issue was never actually resolved I'm lowering this back down to 2 stars. The amount of time spent trying to get Insteon and Alexa to work is not worth it. There are plenty of automation options out there - I would not recommend Insteon to anyone at this point.\n\nUpdate 4/3/17 - things have been working better recently. Have only had the original issue a few times since Insteon tech was able to force through an update. So far so good.\n\nORIGINAL\nYes, this product will turn your lights on/off using Alexa. However, there is a defect where if after you don't use it for a few hours, the first time you ask Alexa to turn the lights on or off it DOES actually turn them on or off, but you get an error message instead of the standard \"Ok\" message. The error says the device is not responding and to check the power supply and network connection. Clearly both of those are fine since the light does turn on or off. The error message is very annoying.\n\nContacted Insteon support who acknowledged they've heard of this issue but they said they couldn't replicate it locally. They offered zero options or suggestions. Looking online I see other people have the same issue. Why the company is playing it off as not being a problem simply because they can't replicate it locally (if that is really the case) is beyond me. Will be returning this within the next few days if they don't respond back with some more appropriate next steps.\n\nThis was a lower priced product from other brands, and I certainly feel like I got what I paid for. My mistake."}
{"Author": "MKosu04", "Date": "on January 5, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Great system for easy Christmas Tree control", "Text": "Works great to control 2 plug-in devices. I used it to control 2 indoor Christmas trees.\n\nOne note for LED lights (one tree was LED) the module will let a small amount of current through even when \"off\" so you see a slight glow in the LED.\nFor incandescent bulbs you do not see any light.\n\nThe app for iPhone makes it easy to set up devices and control them.\nI also set it up to work with my Amazon Echo.\nYou can combine the 2 controllers in a group called \"The Trees\" and then just say \"Alexa, Turn on the trees\" and they both light up. I even set it up so the 12' tree with incandescent bulbs defaults to 50% brightness. Otherwise it was way too bright.\n\nI have not yet added any other devices, so I cannot speak to the expanded use."}
{"Author": "jmay999", "Date": "on January 4, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Great product, easy to set up and use.", "Text": "These are awesome. They are so easy to set up and add additional items to the kit. It works great with the Amazon Echo and Alexa. We set one up with the Christmas tree this year. No more bending and reaching plugs to turn on the tree - all we had to say was \"Alexa, turn the Christmas Tree on\" - and it turned on. We also have these set up on lamps around the house. I would recommend this to anyone. Great product, easy to set up and use."}
{"Author": "flash33", "Date": "on January 3, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Good Starting Point", "Text": "Hooks up works well. A good starting point to build a home automation system on. Only draw back is it needs an internet connection."}
{"Author": "D. Slattery", "Date": "on January 3, 2017", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Lower your expectations and this thing is OK.", "Text": "Like all Insteon products, you should make sure your expectations are sufficiently low before purchasing. Once you don't expect much from them, you'll be satisfied. Not happy, just satisfied. The Windows 10 platform apps (mobile and desktop) seem to have an issue disconnecting devices from scenes. The interface is nice enough, but compared to HouseLinc (the prior version that was a desktop app) you lose at least 70% of the features. For example, you can't really inspect device links like you can in HouseLInc, the Sunset/Sunrise times just don't work for timers, you are unable to set ramp rates for switches, it barely works with KeypadLinc switches. Overall it's a reasonably reliable replacement for a PLM, but if you're expecting Houselinc v3, forget it."}
{"Author": "phazeone", "Date": "on January 3, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "works great", "Text": "no issues , works great"}
{"Author": "Isaac Valdez", "Date": "on January 3, 2017", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Burned up hub and Non-responsive Support", "Text": "It is with a heavy heart that I post this review. The Insteon product line is extensive and, I feel, covers every need one would have while automating their home. That is why I gave two stars. However the real concern was with their hub and technical support. Or I should say a burned-up hub and lack of response from technical support.\n\nMy Hub: While trying to figure out why our automated lights would not turn on one day I noticed the hub was non-responsive. I tried\u2026 un-plug/plug back in, new outlet on the surge strip, new surge strip, new wall outlet, new power cord. That\u2019s when I noticed faint brown spots covering the entire bottom and some on the top of the case. While I was looking closely I caught the familiar \u201cburned up\u201d smell. That\u2019s when I opened the case. Just from what I can see, there are three components and five spots on the circuit board that are burned through. That worried me.\n\nTheir Support: I used Insteon\u2019s website (the only option I could find) to send them an email request to replace the hub - twice. Each time I received a confirmation from their website but I did not receive a confirmation email nor did I ever heard back from their support team. Once again - this happened twice.\n\nIt\u2019s these two reasons together that prompted me to leave such a poor review. I understand electronics need electricity and electricity can burn things up but to me a lack of support or even a response from their support team is what ruined this vendor for me. I can provide picture of the burned up hub if needed.\n\nUPDATE: 01/10/2017 = Shortly after posting the above review I (interestingly enough) got an email from Insteon support. The end result (w/o too many details) is they went above-and-beyond to take care of my situation. They replaced my hub for free and even shipped the new unit overnight. This experience has restored my faith in Insteon's Tech Support. I will once again buy from them in the future and suggest their products to others."}
{"Author": "The skinny...", "Date": "on January 2, 2017", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Good, Good with Alexa.", "Text": "Works great with Alexa. These hub kits are cheaper than two dim switches..so i have 3 hubs. One star loss for overpricing switches by Insteon."}
{"Author": "Computerized Nurse", "Date": "on January 2, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Works great fast response", "Text": "This device works pretty flawlessly, and it is a must have"}
{"Author": "NSB45", "Date": "on January 2, 2017", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Very good device", "Text": "Great customer service. Great device."}
{"Author": "Ravindra Nagireddy", "Date": "on December 30, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Worst Customer service", "Text": "The product is good as long as it works. If it stops working, you will face the most horrible customer service in your life. They do not have a customer service email listed on their website. That explains their crooked intentions. Before you buy, try calling their customer service for some information and you will drop your plans to buy this product."}
{"Author": "kss4w", "Date": "on December 30, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "but for some reason interface is still buggy (sunrise/sunset settings do not work as expected) and appears like a beta software", "Text": "Item was delivered as promised and works. This is a replacement for a failed older insteon wall plug controller that I had from many years ago, so that i could continue using the installed switches. This new version has some additional features, but for some reason interface is still buggy (sunrise/sunset settings do not work as expected) and appears like a beta software after all these years."}
{"Author": "Cholly", "Date": "on December 30, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "It was easy to set up to control two lamps in my ...", "Text": "I use the Home Control starter kit with my Amazon Dot. It was easy to set up to control two lamps in my bedroom using the Alexa App for Android.\nI only gave it 4 stars because the hub controls Insteon devices."}
{"Author": "Hondaddy", "Date": "on December 28, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Dimmable switches for your lamps. Remote automation.", "Text": "This is the perfect home automation starter kit. This was a great deal at $43.89. You get one hub that acts as the brain of the system and two dimmable output switches. Insteon has a complete line of items for everything in your home. Very easy to setup and load the free apps on your smartphone."}
{"Author": "Lgeorge", "Date": "on December 26, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Cool stuff, works good", "Text": "Works well with iPhone and Hub app. Programmed five wall units and two plug in dimmers in thirty minutes. Set up two schemes to operate three wall units at once and two wall units with the other scheme. Works fine on my home network. Next I want to check the remote network control capability. Love the Insteon line of products so far. Highly recommend them for controlling multiple lights. Was able to gang multiple lights to function as three and four way switches and not have to run the connecting wires between the switches and light fixtures."}
{"Author": "Donald Foster", "Date": "on December 26, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Bad advertising.", "Text": "Was not necessary."}
{"Author": "Corey J.", "Date": "on December 26, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Liking it so far.", "Text": "works great with Alexa. Have had no problems and using it for over a month now."}
{"Author": "Skeet", "Date": "on December 23, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Works well", "Text": "Seems to work well. The app is a bit cumbersome, changing homes isn't all that intuitive."}
{"Author": "J. Tidwell", "Date": "on December 21, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Nice home automation setup", "Text": "This is a nice setup. I just wish it had two non-dimming plugs. It DOES work with Alexa."}
{"Author": "Amazon Customer", "Date": "on December 21, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Working well for me.", "Text": "Working pretty well so far. The included dimmer plugs are not very helpful for me as I do not really have lamps to plug into them. I have been installing switches and hooking them into the system. So far it has been a breeze with about four hookups in place."}
{"Author": "casper", "Date": "on December 20, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "One Star", "Text": "It is not very good will not stay connected to the hub. I would not recommend this product."}
{"Author": "Minmin R", "Date": "on December 20, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "One Star", "Text": "hard to install, not stable, most of the time does not work, hate it"}
{"Author": "Ramby C. Wong", "Date": "on December 20, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Got a used device when I am not supposed to.", "Text": "I purchased this kit from seller DealsPointer. In the process of setting this device up, I kept on getting an error with syncing it to the account I created. Upon many hours of trying, I contacted insteon and was told this device has an account already tried to it. I am still in the process of resolving this issue but due to the urgency and inconvenience of returning and re-buying the product I have decided to try and make it work. Very unhappy with receiving a used device and will definitely not purchase from that seller again!"}
{"Author": "Robert Sarson", "Date": "on December 20, 2016", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Three Stars", "Text": "could not get it working. But i'm sure its my fault."}
{"Author": "M. Timmins", "Date": "on December 19, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "... PC running Homeseer v2 (an incredibly powerful platform but painful for anyone to use except me", "Text": "I switched from using a PC running Homeseer v2 (an incredibly powerful platform but painful for anyone to use except me.) Instead of upgrading to HSv3, I turned off the PC. Instead of dumping my investment in Insteon peripherals (about 35 units) I thought I'd try this hub (I really wanted the Wink Hub but it's not Insteon compatible...disappointing.) However, for what this does, it works very well. All of my devices connect (except an old RemoteLinc.) I haven't figured out how to trigger events (or if it can even that.) There isn't a variable security timer (to dither on/off times so they don't appear so \"timer-ish\") and I can't figure out how to trigger scenes from other devices, events or conditions (which should be right in the wheelhouse of a connected \"hub\".) Otherwise, new device setup is simple, the mobile app is easy to navigate and communications to all my devices, across 3 stories of a 3500 sq ft house (aluminum and brick) is reliable."}
{"Author": "Rob N.", "Date": "on December 18, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Bought 2 and neither worked", "Text": "Purchased 2 of these kits, one for me and one for a gift. Could not get either hub to work. Called insteon support and after 20 minutes on the phone neither could the tech. He was going to send a replacement hub. I decided to try the gift kit I had purchased and went through all the same troubleshooting as on the first hub and couldn't get that one to show up on the network either. Returning both for a refund. Customer service tried but the product just doesn't work."}
{"Author": "Kesty", "Date": "on December 18, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Has some quirks but it works really well", "Text": "We had it setup in one evening, with Amazon's Echo. The pairing of the devices didn't work in the beginning, the instructions are not the greatest. But in the end, all the outlets, light dimmers and all other things we bought are working great. Worth every penny to set this up, never have to trek across the apartment to turn kitchen lights off. Dimming works great too."}
{"Author": "Amazon_Prime_reject2", "Date": "on December 18, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Good at what it does, but has its limits", "Text": "Works well, but limited interaction with Alexa. You can do the basics, but Alexa can't open your garage door or door locks using only the Insteon hub. Also does not integrate with IFTTT at all. That being said, easy to setup up and interface is simple and has been reliable so far."}
{"Author": "Greg S", "Date": "on December 15, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "How did I not know about this !", "Text": "Probably the coolest thing I have discovered ! With amazon echo and sonos my life is almost complete ."}
{"Author": "William Houston", "Date": "on December 15, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "The app is not pretty, and it can be hard to setup", "Text": "The nicest hardware for remotely connected switches I have come across. The app is not pretty, and it can be hard to setup, but once it's done it's worth it. I just hope the introduce Google home support soon. I use the homeboy app to control them, much nicer then the insteon app. Lots of tmdifferent hardware options, scheduling, scenes and all sorts of other things. High quality, and highly configurable."}
{"Author": "Pee Wee Herman", "Date": "on December 14, 2016", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Great system but not compatable with several LED dimmable bulbs", "Text": "Great system but not compatable with several LED dimmable bulbs. It a try it and see if it works with your dimmable LED bulbs."}
{"Author": "Timothy R Williams", "Date": "on December 13, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "worth the investment"}
{"Author": "D Rush", "Date": "on December 12, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Cool stuff. What can I say", "Text": "Cool stuff. What can I say. Had to read through the manual a few times but that's okay.Wish it had a local server instead of having to rely on an internet connection. When that big server provider got hacked a while back it was dead in the water. I don't like that Insteon! Still had local control of the remote units by pressing the buttons on the recievers, behind the couch, all crunched up trying to reach it, other than that great!"}
{"Author": "John", "Date": "on December 11, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Big improvement over X10, software needs updating", "Text": "My first impression of the Insteon 2245-222 hub is that it's a great improvement over the old X10 powerline controllers, which had issues with missed signals and limited range. Using RF signals, I can now turn lights on and off reliably, as well as dim them using the Insteon for Hub app or the RF remote control. No more guessing as to whether it will work the first time. That's a big improvement. Programming light intensity levels is easy, and the ability to create scenes is a real time saver for frequently used settings. I also like being able to schedule lights to come on at sunset, and to turn them off at a preset time. Here's where the problem lies with the Insteon for Hub software. After setting the scheduler, the on / off times do not work as expected. In my case, there is an 8 hour offset between the hub time and the actual local time. The hub location says Los Angeles, which is in the correct time zone, but the hub time is 8 hours later. The scheduler events are based on the hub's internal clock, so they happen 8 hours earlier than expected. The suggested fix is to reset the hub location, but when I try to do that under Settings, House, Location, the Insteon for Hub app crashes every time. It shows the locator map for a fraction of a second, then crashes. I see this same behavior on a Samsung Galaxy tablet and an Alcatel smartphone. Also, when I click on the \"Observe DST\" button, I see the message, \"Updating hub time\" momentarily, however there is no change to the original \"Off\" state. There needs to be a reliable way to set the local time in order for the scheduler to work properly. Hopefully this can be addressed through a hub firmware or app software update. My Insteon hub currently has version 1010 firmware and the Insteon for Hub app software version is 1.9.4. An improved web interface to the hub with a settings menu would also be nice, but right now, I'll settle for just having the correct time.\n\nUPDATE: I found a way to prevent the Insteon for Hub app from crashing. The app only crashes while setting my hub location if the Android phone's GPS is turned off. I turned on the GPS, repeated the location setup, and this time, the hub's location and time were finally updated to correct values. It would be nice if you could set the location manually in the event that there is no working GPS on the Android device, but the app exits before you can get to that point. Nevertheless, I am upgrading my review rating to four stars since the hub time and scheduler are now working. I did notice the \"Observe DST\" button still doesn't work. It's always off when running the app."}
{"Author": "H. Salsano", "Date": "on December 10, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Great at this price, or less", "Text": "Bought this at the red warehouse club for less than 30. Actually bought two, since it was cheaper than buying just one additional dimmer module. Programming is a bit of a pain at first, but some recent android app updates fixed a few issues. I wish they offered this with two On/Off modules for this price! I cannot use the dimmer modules on my rotating christmas trees, bluetooth receiver, or other electronics because of the voltage drop and the lower power capacity. Works with Alexa, so that was the whole reason for getting these."}
{"Author": "Amidmany", "Date": "on December 9, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "NOT X10 PROGRAMMABLE.", "Text": "If only I knew..... I had to dig deep to find that out.. Even the manual says you can and how to do it.. great price though. At $45 it's like getting the second dimmer free. I would not have purchased this otherwise and just stuck with my X-10"}
{"Author": "kwvargas", "Date": "on December 6, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "Works with Amazon Echo."}
{"Author": "John M", "Date": "on December 4, 2016", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "long term disappointment", "Text": "works with my Amazon Echo with no issues. set up quickly and easily. just a little pricey.\n\nUPDATE> Worked without an issue for about 2-3 weeks, then all of a sudden stopped. a lot of hard wired switches take forever to respond if they respond at all. long term disappointment"}
{"Author": "Amazon Customer", "Date": "on December 1, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Great hub for all smart devices", "Text": "Works good setup takes a while outside of that it's good"}
{"Author": "Robert R. Spencer", "Date": "on December 1, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Dropping X10 compatibility sucks", "Text": "Good job Insteon (not). There are still a lot of us out here that have a lot of $$$ invested in X10 devices, and you managed to chop us off at the knees by removing X10 compatibility. I currently have an older Insteon hub (if you want to call something purchased two years ago \"old\") and was looking forward to upgrading to the newer hub so I would have voice control capability via the Echo Dot.\n\nI'll be your \"new and improved\" hub back to Amazon as soon as it arrives on my doorstep. There's no way I'm going to spend $500+ to replace perfectly good X10 devices just so you can cost cut your hub price.\n\nYou can bet if I do upgrade my system in the future, I will avoid using Insteon."}
{"Author": "SAM", "Date": "on December 1, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Was easy to connect the hub to my home network", "Text": "Everything arrived on time and undamaged. Was easy to connect the hub to my home network, and add the two dimmer modules. Very satisfied with the product so far."}
{"Author": "John A Manis", "Date": "on November 29, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Does a nice job. I have my Logitech elite controlling my ...", "Text": "Does a nice job. I have my Logitech elite controlling my devices and there can sometimes be a 1 - 3 second lag when I am controlling my insteon light switches. I have a total of 15 insteon light switches, insteon motion, TV, audio receiver, DirecTV receiver hooked up to hub and I am satisfied."}
{"Author": "JP", "Date": "on November 28, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Smoke coming out of hub when first plugged in", "Text": "I wish I could give it more stars however if I could I would give it less than one. I had the unfortunate experience of plugging it in and noticing a faint burning electrical smell, and upon examining the unit as I was trying to set it up I noticed smoke coming out of it. So I unplugged it and given the fire hazard will not be able to set it up. Even worse is I didn't get a chance to try and set it up until I was past the 30 day return window, which is my own fault but still sucks as I'm out the money and don't have a device that can be used. I set up a number of the TP link outlets earlier today with no issue as I had gotten both in order to test and compare. So at this point I'll use the TP link outlets with my echo dot and will not be spending any more of my money on the Insteon products. Quite the shame as I was looking forward to getting the hub setup and possibly getting some of their additional products to add to my home but I'm not willing to invest any more on them when the hub smoked right out of the box. Positive note is I noticed it and got it unplugged before something worse happened.\n\nEDIT 11/30 - I decided to open up the hub to take a look (attached are a couple of pictures where on the circuit board you can see charred area and then on case you can see scorch mark). I did contact the company via there website to at least make them aware of the issue encountered. If I hear back from them I will update review."}
{"Author": "Holly Fouchia", "Date": "on November 27, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Easy setup, works great with echo dot.", "Text": "I love the insteon smart home kit. The included plug in controllers work great as signal extenders , so I just plugged them in about half way toward one end of the house and again half way to the garage. I bought some wire in light switches and installed them and they work awesome. Very easy setup. Love that it is compatible with Amazon echo!!!"}
{"Author": "Pongoxbongo", "Date": "on November 24, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Make the whole lamp smart, not the bulbs!", "Text": "A great addition to any smart household. Their dimmer modules, smart wall switches, and the like save you from buying a ton of individually smart light bulbs (adds up quick). You can convert whole multi-bulb fixtures without changing a single bulb (assuming your existing ones are dimmable).\n\nThe hub integrates easily into Alexa for Echo voice control goodness. Docking one star for it needing to be wired into your home network (just plug it into a spare port on the back of your wireless router), and the somewhat clunky Insteon mobile app. Otherwise a great, expandible package!\n\n=^_^="}
{"Author": "Rogtuf", "Date": "on November 23, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Easy install", "Text": "Easy to set up. Works well"}
{"Author": "CA customer", "Date": "on November 23, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Good choice", "Text": "Easy to set up. Not as full featured as using Universal Devices ISY 994i but much less expensive and user friendly."}
{"Author": "technojerry", "Date": "on November 22, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Very Reliable and Works Great with Alexa", "Text": "I purchased this hub as part of a starter kit at Costco, but it is the same hub. It integrates well with Amazon Alexa so the app on your phone really isn't that important as some complain about. The app is not fancy, but works will with my current 17 devices from wall outlets controlling hot water pumps to bedroom wall dimmers. The app is 100% reliable and voice commands with Alexa are in the 95%+ accuracy. I mainly use Alexa with original Echo units or the new Dot in most rooms of the house. It is great turning the corner to the Den to tell Alexa to turn the Den lights on before I enter the room or as I'm exiting. I even have a Dot installed on my Subaru using my iPhone as a hotspot and I command Alexa to turn my garage lights on by voice command before I even enter the driveway. The hub works well and it is great to have the Amazon Alexa integration."}
{"Author": "SeaQuestDSV", "Date": "on November 20, 2016", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "When it works it's awesome, when it doesn't don't count on tech support", "Text": "This is my second hub from Insteon. I had the old Hub 1 that eventually quit working so I bought the Hub 2 as a replacement. Setup was easy and flawless. Fast forward three months and the Hub has quit communicating with Insteon's servers rendering the device unusable.\n\nI submitted a support ticket last week and have yet to hear back. I tried joining the support forums but have been waiting 3 days for moderator approval on my account.\n\nIf customer service gets back to me and fixes the issue I'll be a happy camper, but right now I'm just really discouraged."}
{"Author": "Patrick R.", "Date": "on November 19, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Disappointing... Wasted over 2 hours trying to get it to connect to Insteon's server(s)", "Text": "Didnt work out of box. Messed with it for 2 hours. Im VERY proficient with routers, networks, etc... This just did NOT work. Wouldnt work with Time Warner cable modem. Would not access Insteon's server. I put on the DMZ side of router just to see if it was a firewall issue. same problem. Boxed up and sent back. I dont want to deal with downloading firmware and having to read all kinds of comments on forums just to get something that should work out of the box to do so. Disappointing. Wanted to test feasibility for a large automation project."}
{"Author": "N David", "Date": "on November 18, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Quick and easy install!", "Text": "There's not much information on this particular hub model, but for the price it was a lot cheaper than what I had seen. It works perfectly with Alexa via my echo. Quick and easy install!"}
{"Author": "Steven M. Helwig, Ph.D.", "Date": "on November 17, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "This is the worst device I've ever purchased for a smart home", "Text": "This is the worst device I've ever purchased for a smart home. The device has to be rebooted just about everytime and the remote plugs take about 5 or 6 times trying to turn them on or off. These will not work remote!!! This is a total waste of money and I will never buy an Insteon product again. Go with TP-Link"}
{"Author": "Robert G", "Date": "on November 14, 2016", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Newer model does not work with old X10. Old ...", "Text": "Newer model does not work with old X10. Old video on line shows X10 but new box doesn't show this any more."}
{"Author": "guitarwarrior", "Date": "on November 14, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Better than expected", "Text": "Not only were the two included lamp modules easy to pair but I was able to use existing decade-old Insteon lamp modules as well. These were purchased from Smarthome some 10 years ago and were being controlled by a table top module. they were pairable by typing in the 6 digit id number on the back of each. Best of all Alexa is able to control them while the table top module control with all its programs and scenes were unaffected."}
{"Author": "Shawn S", "Date": "on November 9, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "I researched the options and chose the Insteon figuring that if it wasn't perfect, I wasn't out a ton of money", "Text": "This is my first home automation system. I researched the options and chose the Insteon figuring that if it wasn't perfect, I wasn't out a ton of money. Well, I am happy I chose Insteon as its been very easy to get up and running. I now have 5 rooms set up, with wall switches or plugs, as well as the outdoor plug that we used for Halloween and now Christmas Decorations. Great system for the money! For someone like me with little tech knowledge, this is a great system."}
{"Author": "Graciezsc", "Date": "on November 9, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Great purchase", "Text": "I just bought this at Costco for $30. Set up was a. breeze and it works with my echo."}
{"Author": "AmznCust", "Date": "on November 4, 2016", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "it works as advertised and has proven to be easy to configure and add on as desired", "Text": "When the system works, it works as advertised and has proven to be easy to configure and add on as desired. However our first hub failed at a little past the warranty period and there's no way to swap out a hub. It is necessary to have Insteon support delete your account (which can take a day or two) and reset every single device, then completely rebuild everything from scratch. If we have another failure, I will be looking elsewhere."}
{"Author": "James Yarbrough", "Date": "on November 2, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Terrible product. better products out there by", "Text": "Terrible product.better products out there by far"}
{"Author": "Nick Mageloff", "Date": "on November 1, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Obsolete Software!!", "Text": "Total crap! Bought one 4-5 years ago, returned it. Returning this one as well! Using a USB device and this Hub is cool, but the software is 5 steps back! You must hard program all times and have no access to plus or minus Sunrise or Sunset like the HouseLink for the USB device has had for over 5 years. Wake up Smarthome or conside Dumbhome for a new company name! Of course the website was so poorly written and vague that you cannot determine anything conclusive. Looking into switching home automation and suggest you do the same!"}
{"Author": "P. T. Kreigh", "Date": "on November 1, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "home automatiion made easier", "Text": "Basically, I got this as a backup for server-based copy of HCA, which is also used to control my 10 (and counting) Insteon devices. The hub is useful for other things, such as remote camera access via Web browser or smartphone or on-demand control of lights, cameras, door locks, etc. while at home using keypads and/or voice-activated controllers such as Amazon Echo/Alexa."}
{"Author": "ELS", "Date": "on November 1, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Works Great", "Text": "Easy graphic setup using an iPad. Running 24 switches. Easy scene creation and scheduling. I have found that when I start getting delays in the system (for me about every 60 days) recycling the HUB power (pull plug) solves it."}
{"Author": "CRC111", "Date": "on October 31, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "I was so disappointed that there is no easy way to replace the ...", "Text": "My hub died short of 2 years. I called for replacement and their replacement policy is, they have to receive your dead unit first before they send you a replacement, which is shipped via the lowest UPS rate. When I received the replacement unit, I was so disappointed that there is no easy way to replace the old hub with the new in the Insteon system. You have to call support and have them delete your account so that you can start over as if you are doing a new install. You then associate all your devices and, if you have configured on/off schedules, you have to re-do them."}
{"Author": "Raykoch73", "Date": "on October 29, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Hub quit. Customer service not good.", "Text": "My hub quit after just 2 months. Insteon customer service doesn't seem concerned. Nearly a week and no reply."}
{"Author": "doug- florida.", "Date": "on October 27, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "This starter kit was fairly user friendly , if you follow the simple instructions ."}
{"Author": "Hamzeh", "Date": "on October 25, 2016", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Three Stars", "Text": "supports 110V only.. what a shame!!"}
{"Author": "Jim", "Date": "on October 24, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Awesome product, but the iOS app isnt great.", "Text": "Works great with Amazon Echo. I loving being about to turn off the lights from my bed at night. I wish the software was a little more intuitive though. It think they struck out with their software. Hopefully in future updates they can revamp the software."}
{"Author": "Amazon Customer", "Date": "on October 23, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Total Waste of Money", "Text": "The app will not connect to the Hub. The Echo can't see the Hub. I've tried everything that insteon recommends to make it work. 2 hours waiting for tech support to answer, but they never did. Emailed tech support. Still no answer 2 days later. So far, this was a total waste of money."}
{"Author": "Ryan Templeton", "Date": "on October 22, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Go with another system", "Text": "I'm on my 3rd controller. First 2 died. Only reason I've gone back is because it is cheaper to get another controller than replace all the peripheral devices. If given the chance to start over I would not choose Insteon."}
{"Author": "Dustin", "Date": "on October 22, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Not smart or innovative for a smart home product", "Text": "After struggling for a couple weeks with scheduling and scenes, I contacted Insteon email support to figure out why it wasn't working. I was trying to make a single scene to turn on at sunrise and off at 8am Monday-Friday. This part worked perfectly. The problem occurred when I tried to create a second scene for Saturday and Sunday to turn on at 8am. It claimed there was a scheduling conflict and that I could not create a scene to turn on at 8am when there was another scene set to turn off at the same time but on entirely different days. Insteon's support site claimed I would get a response within 48 hours but instead it took 7 days to get a response where the technician essentially told me to change the Saturday/Sunday on time to 8:30 instead of 8am. I replied back saying that would allow me to create the new scene but was not an acceptable resolution. Two weeks later, still no response so I called their support phone number and was told just to make the new scene 1 minute later instead which was still unacceptable.\n\nAnother issue I had with it was the lack of functionality of either their Android or Windows interface. When creating a schedule or scene, you have to advance the hours and minutes manually up or down one unit at a time instead of being able to type in the time you want. For example, if the time is displayed as 5:28 and you want to change it to 11:00, the easiest way would be to click the down arrow for minutes 28 times, and then the up arrow for hours 6 times. There was no keypad entry option available.\n\nNeedless to say, based on those issues alone I can see there being lots of other issues if I were to get deeper into home automation. I've returned the product and will be looking at other alternatives to Insteon. Definitely can't recommend or say anything positive about the product."}
{"Author": "Victor_Chat", "Date": "on October 20, 2016", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Not quite ready for prime time", "Text": "Still needs some work, hard to use it since it doesn't consistently work"}
{"Author": "Tom Me", "Date": "on October 19, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Skip them.", "Text": "They work, but only for now as the Internet of Things is going a different way than Insteon.\nTheir android app is probably the worst app I have ever seen. It looks like it was made 10 years ago and is garbage. Look at its reviews on Google Play. They don't care.\nIt does NOT work with Smart Things.\nNo customer support.\nGod help you if you need to change our the Hub.\nAll in all, it is good...if you were buying this 5 years ago. But almost every single competitor of theirs is doing more, has a better app design, and is cheaper than Insteon.\nMy advice, leave Insteon where they are comfortable and work in, the past."}
{"Author": "Joshua Jacobsen", "Date": "on October 18, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Quick Overview", "Text": "I wrote about this on another site, and was asked to put the same details here on Amazon.\n\nThis kit comes with an INSTEON controller hub. This is just a controller, and doesn't do anything by itself. You plug it into an ethernet port, and into your house power. It communicates with other Insteon devices primarily using your house's power lines (it sends data over your house's power wires). It connects to the internet through the ethernet, of course. You can do things with the insteon hub using computer programs, a smartphone app, and Amazon Echo. It's cloud-accessible, so you can use your phone's smarthome app from anywhere in the world to see what's turned on, and control your home. You also have an interface that makes it easy to program schedules and triggers -- e.g. Turn off all the lights at 10:00pm, or when you open a door make lights turn on automatically -- if you have all the necessary insteon devices.\n\nThis kit also comes with two dimmer controls. These plug into your wall (remember, insteon uses home power to communicate with the hub) and you plug a dimmable light into this controller. You can use the hub (from a computer, smartphone app, Amazon Echo) to turn power on and off and provide dimmer control to these controllers.\n\nOther Insteon Devices you can buy (not in this kit) include: Garage door controllers & sensor. Water sensors. Smoke & CO detectors. Thermostat. There are also cameras, but those are more a combination of network and insteon devices."}
{"Author": "M. Lawson", "Date": "on October 17, 2016", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Not a perfect solution thus far.", "Text": "The device controllers seem reliable however the hub and the apps to control it leave a lot to be desired. I'm looking into getting something to replace the hub as it's not very reliable and very limited on customization. I've had my timezone reset several times which throws off any scheduled lighting etc. Scenes seem to run sometimes and not others for no reason. Not a perfect solution thus far."}
{"Author": "Bubba", "Date": "on October 15, 2016", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Overly complicated - never worked right", "Text": "The android app that accompanies this hub is in need of an update and is very frustrating to use. I was never able to get simple actions, like scheduling turing a light on and off to work."}
{"Author": "Lee Hodge", "Date": "on October 10, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "This Thing is Great!!!", "Text": "There seems to be a lot of bad press on this device. Here is my experience...\n\nFirst, some background. I have been using Insteon devices since their inception. I have probably spent $10,000 on the product with mixed results. I used these in 2 larger homes (2,500 and 4,500sf). I now live in a small apartment in a 100 year-old building. The wiring is new, but everything is in metal boxes and conduit)\n\nI had 3 leftover Insteon LED bulbs so I thought I would try this out. I also have a Nest thermostat (don't tell the landlord). I thought I would \"risk\" 65 bucks on this, since it was the least expensive solution out there - by far.\n\n1) Initial setup was flawless. The app takes a photo of the hub's QR code and does the rest. You set up an account in about 2 minutes.\n2) found the LED bulbs with no issues are all. Just remember to search, then turn the bulbs on so they can send their \"Hey!\" signal to the hub.\n3) Insteon app is clean, simple and intuitive. I have seen some nasty programs - this is simple.\n4) Works fantastically with the Nest - no problems here.\n5) It hasn't missed a signal yet and I played with it for hours.\n6) setting up on other iDevices is a simple as loading the app and signing on. period.\n\nHere's the one I don't understand. It had remote access right out of the box. No port forwarding, no DNS. It just worked. It will remote access the devices and check status via internet with no complicated setup.\n\nThis has been the best Insteon product I have seen yet.\n\nThis model is not compatible with Apple HomeKit (which I wanted). After setting it up, it seems like HomeKit is just an extra and unneeded step in the process, since Siri never understands me anyway. The other Insteon hub is HomeKit enabled but seems to have a lot less features. Make sure you pick the one that suits your application.\n\nOther people seem to have had difference experiences. This is mine. I think this would be great for a small implementation or for a first timer."}
{"Author": "Chris & Ellen", "Date": "on October 9, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "So far so good!", "Text": "The hub died after a month or so. But Insteon swapped it out quickly. I'm still building my system, but am generally happy. Word to the wise... make sure your light switches are 4-wire (hot, load, neutral, & ground) to use the in-wall switches and dimmers. I found out that our whole house has no neutral wires in the switch boxes. If a neutral on the same circuit breaker is nearby (like in an outlet), you can fish it to the switch box and use it. That worked in a couple instances. Otherwise order the \"2-wire\" Insteon dimmers, if you have a 3-way or 4-way, find the hot switch box and install the 2-wire dimmer there, then add a mini remote paddle switch in the other switch boxes so it looks and functions normally."}
{"Author": "Friedchicken879", "Date": "on October 8, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Works nicely", "Text": "Works great. Setup was not too bad. Scenes are a bit tricky, but fun to play with."}
{"Author": "faraz zaidi", "Date": "on October 6, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Affordable home automation.", "Text": "insteon is great! The controller is easy to setup, it's nice being able to control the whole house with my phone. I'm looking forward to adding to the system in the future. It's a plus to be able to dim lamps also."}
{"Author": "Dennis philips", "Date": "on October 4, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Over 80 controlled items in my house from the lights, coffee machine, to the hot tub to the garage door to the fire...", "Text": "Controls my whole house and using insteon has saved me money and simplified everything and gives me peace of mind and security (see below).\n\nI use Alexa voice to turn on and off the lights, fountain, coffee machine, lock the gate, etc with the insteon hub. The hub let's me set up Sunset/Sunrise times for the porch lights and times for the tree flood lights to come on and off every day.\n\nI also have it automatically lock the gate when the lawn people leave it open accidentally every week.\nI get text messages when doors open or someone walks in a room when I am not at home. I also get text messages if the smoke detectors or water leak is triggered.\n\nAnd using the Harmony hub I can set several devices to respond at the same time such as the TV, blinds and dim the family room lights using just one Alexa command.\n\nI can even get fancy and use ITTT formulas. (Search web for the ways to add ITTT to Insteon.)\n\nIt also controls the thermostat and several cameras inside and out.\nAll this and I don't have to pay a monthly fee like some of the other hubs. Never had a glitch or any problems with reliability."}
{"Author": "drb", "Date": "on October 3, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Home control", "Text": "This starter kit is my first addition to my Amazon Echo ...very easy to setup...these outlets work great, switches and thermostat is next... excellent service."}
{"Author": "Amazon Customer", "Date": "on October 2, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Works great. Awesome", "Text": "They just added recognition and voice action on Scenes (\"Turn on \"SCENE\". \"Turn off SCENE\"). Works great. Awesome!"}
{"Author": "30something", "Date": "on September 30, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Alexa, turn everything off", "Text": "Awesome product, and works great with Alexa / Echo after a little configuration.\n\nI wish it worked with both Alexa and Apple HomeKit, but I don't think it works with HomeKit (yet?).\n\nInsteon light switches are a little pricey ($40-$50) but it's awesome to be able to turn on and off the lights using Amazon Echo. It also has schedules for different \"scenes\" or combinations of lights and switches, and it can also be set up with motion sensors to trigger actions. Haven't tried out their cameras yet, but I see that Insteon has HD security cameras as well.\n\nInsteon has been around for years, and with the new hubs they support the latest apps like Amazon Echo."}
{"Author": "Amazon Customer", "Date": "on September 27, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Very poor mobile app and pc app", "Text": "Very poor mobile app and pc app. Scene schedules work intermittently. Not impressed. Will buy another brand for home automation."}
{"Author": "xyz", "Date": "on September 26, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Works as described", "Text": "I already using an ISY994i, but I bought this on the belief that it would integrate with Logitech's Harmony Remote/Hub, and it does, sort of, but at no fault of this product.\n\nThe Insteon Hub is very small, generates a little heat, and is VERY easy to setup. Apparently, it requires a mobile app to operate it; there might be a desktop application for it, but I did not look for it. I have come to believe that the iPhone/iPad (which I use) support is superior than that of Android. This requires AC power and a wired RJ45 Ethernet connection (this is a typical network cable) and comes with a network cable.\n\nIt is VERY easy to link devices with this Hub, especially in comparison to the ISY99 products, however, that is the extent of its superiority to the ISY99. It can \"automate\" devices with a very limited schedule - all I could figure out was a SINGLE schedule per device for which you can choose an On time, Off time, and which days of the week. It supports scenes (a \"scene\" is a group of devices that are acted upon simultaneously), each of which has its own schedule, so you could create a scene with just one device and have more schedules.\n\nThe iPhone mobile app is fairly responsive and easy to use, but very simplistic. For example, when you choose thermostat, it shows one thermostat, but I have two - so, I created a \"room\" (a group of devices - you create \"rooms\" and assign devices to them, a device can be in more than one \"room\") called Thermostats and put both of my mine in that room.\n\nThis is a good device for the casual user, however, you want more complex programming, such as knowing \"today\" is a holiday so don't turn on the bathroom lights at 5:30am, then you would want the ISY. I use both because the Insteon Hub's mobile is so easy to use to just turn things on and off.\n\n4 of 5 stars because of the limited programming."}
{"Author": "K. Stefans", "Date": "on September 21, 2016", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Great concept and works fairly well", "Text": "Great concept and works fairly well, but the instructions are very poor and the powerline interface does not have a very good range. Power line signals have trouble making it to an adjacent room."}
{"Author": "Jim", "Date": "on September 21, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Works great for 66 bucks", "Text": "I'm a little blown away by all of the negative reviews on here. This system works fine and does what it is supposed to do. I have been very happy with Insteon in general, and with the Insteon Hub. I have about 30 devices in my home. I have not had any problems with any of them. The hub works great for creating \"scenes\" (groups of devices that work together) and scheduling either individual devices or scenes to turn on or off at certain times. I have found that adding devices and scenes through the Andriod app to be very easy.\n\nThe Insteon Hub is not a high-level device. It is pretty simple, cannot do advanced programming (conditional - if, then, else) and only works with Insteon devices. Yes, it could be improved, but it's only $66.\n\nI have added some devices to my house that cannot easily be controlled by the Insteon hub and I want conditional programming, so I am upgrading the ISY controller by Universal Devices. However, I have been very happy with the Insteon hub as a starter device."}
{"Author": "Kevin Darm", "Date": "on September 21, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Hardware is good, software leaves much to be desired", "Text": "Despite the various mixed reviews, I decided to jump in with both feet and move my house towards Insteon, and I've had about the same level of success as everyone else.\n\nThe good - setup is pretty easy. You don't NEED the app on your phone or Windows 8 computer, but it makes life easier (and even then, the app is junk - but this isn't a review on the app) - the instructions provided don't detail how to do the setup without the App, but there are instructions online. The two lamp switches that come are 2-prong and are slim enough, configured so that you can still use the upper plug on a 2-plug receptacle with the switch plugged into the lower. They also have a green / red LED to show when they are supposed to be on / off, which will help with troubleshooting.\n\nThe bad - the App sucks as mentioned above. The devices don't always do what they're supposed to do, sometimes the buttons on the sides don't work, and some times you need to reboot the system to get it all back to normal. The devices also allow a small amount of power through, even when \"off\" so if you have LED bulbs in whatever it's controlling, you'll notice a slight glow. It isn't enough to get a glow out of a regular bulb. I have been told that this charge is to monitor the on/off status of the lamp itself, so if you turn on or off the lamp from the lamps physical switch, the Insteon plug will notice this and turn itself on or off - I haven't seen that happen yet despite trying a few times. This means if you want to turn on the light, you either need to use the App (which isn't great), push the button on the side of the insteon plug (which may be behind a couch or piece of furniture), or install an Insteon remote switch to act as a controller for the lamp (not cheap).\n\nDespite all of this, I'm still happy with it. I have one in the living room and one in the bedroom. I have the one in the living room set to scenes (from the app) so it comes on in the mornings and evenings as it gets dark outside. The one in the bedroom comes on just before my alarm to help me get up. And if I turn it on before bed, I can find my way to bed in the light and then turn it off from the bed using the app on my phone. I've also found that as I add more devices to the house, the mesh network gets stronger - each Insteon device acts as a repeater for signals, so the more the merrier.\n\nAll in all, I think the Insteon hardware is pretty solid - their software is what needs some love, and I hope they start investing more into that side of the business, because great hardware with crummy user interface is worthless."}
{"Author": "Joe", "Date": "on September 15, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "With the hub it was easy to add on additional devices as needed", "Text": "Starter kit contained all you need to get started with home automation. With the hub it was easy to add on additional devices as needed. Useful IOS app that makes it easy to connect when away from home. Best feature is that is it comes with mulitple devices out of the package. Installation took just a matter of seconds and was easy to do for a non technical person. You do need internet service to have best results."}
{"Author": "JH", "Date": "on September 13, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Love it", "Text": "Works great with Amazon echo"}
{"Author": "Bumpa Rodriguez", "Date": "on September 4, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "After you find your sweet spot it's a piece of cake", "Text": "I know a lot of you are having problems with this set up and I did as well. I was able to get the hub connected correctly but couldn't get it to recognize any of my devices. After over 8 hours of troubleshooting, I ran into an Insteon suggestion that essentially said, \"Try temporarily moving Hub to a different outlet.\" Also please obey rule #1 which is no strips or surge protectors can be used. This is a biggy. Next thing is to try as many different outlets that have ethernet nearby until you have success. After you find your sweet spot it's a piece of cake. So in summary, all wall outlets are not created equal as far as this hub is concerned.\n\nBeing able to tell Alexa to turn on these devices is also a nice touch. Well worth the effort & I look forward to adding more devices to my set up.\n\nDeducted (1) star for the amount of time I spent setting this thing up."}
{"Author": "Ben Gruber", "Date": "on August 30, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Love it - super easy to install", "Text": "Love it - super easy to install, set up and use, plus good customer service and TONS of info and tips online. Had it up and running and was commanding Alexa to dim and brighten rooms in under 15 minutes. I don't get the negative reviews - it could be a little easier I guess, I had to delete and re-add one light switch out of eight, and had a little trouble with scenes, but the scheduling feature is great, and I LOVE the voice control with Alexa - you feel very Tony Stark. The app isn't great, but it's not bad, either - better than most of the competition, unless you're shelling out Hue bucks. If you have the slightest tech savvy, this is an easy and really fun/convenient start for home automation. One more tip - maybe you'll use the dimmer outlet plugs, but I haven't. I don't have tons of lamps or anything else that needs dimming. I only would've saved 15-20 bucks, but I probably would've just gotten the hub alone if I had to do it again."}
{"Author": "D. T.", "Date": "on August 28, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Insteon Hub gen 2", "Text": "Works great. I've been adding devices to my system ever since. It helps to read up on how to install the Hub (on line).. NO surge suppressing power strips should be used to install/power the Hub. Plug the Hub directly into a wall socket (or by utilizing a single line non surge suppressing extension cord.) The Hub sends and receives signals through the home electrical system and needs a clean connection to your wiring. It also sends wireless signals, but it's best to have a good electrical connection to get the most out of the Hub.\n\nIntsteon support generally is very good. Patience is definitely a virtue. If you need help, call early if you can - 6 am Pacific Time. You will need to be at least a little tech friendly to work with this type of equipment. Instructions are generally not provided with the equipment and are available on line at the Insteon web site.\n\nI have my Amazon Alexa connected to the system and now most devices can be turned on and off by voice! (The garage door I/O Linc is not compatible with Alexa at this time.)"}
{"Author": "George H. Hornbeck", "Date": "on August 26, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "I recommend this seller very highly", "Text": "This hub is much more reliable and easier to set up than another brand that I tried. It is working perfectly. Smarthome support is very helpful when I need it. I recommend this seller very highly."}
{"Author": "LennyD", "Date": "on August 25, 2016", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Difficult to set up", "Text": "Almost a good product. Hard to set up and I had to call tech support for assistance. It came close to working seamlessly, but requires some degree of maintenance and care to keep everything working."}
{"Author": "buyer", "Date": "on August 24, 2016", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "support is HORRIBLE and you can't add/subtract minutes from sunup/sunset when scheduling ...", "Text": "IT works okay for what I'm using it for, the windows client does not allow you set the location, support is HORRIBLE and you can't add/subtract minutes from sunup/sunset when scheduling something, so I'm using a custom scheduler..."}
{"Author": "slimguy", "Date": "on August 23, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "the best"}
{"Author": "Goldengoose", "Date": "on August 23, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "Everything was great!"}
{"Author": "Rick", "Date": "on August 22, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Great product but went in a different direction", "Text": "Although I did not end up using this hub, I have heard from many others that on it that it's a great product. I chose to return it because it was not compatible with certain devices that I already own."}
{"Author": "Karen Mohr", "Date": "on August 22, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "so far so good, works", "Text": "Had it about a month, so far so good, works great"}
{"Author": "TexasTripletMom", "Date": "on August 19, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Fabulous!!! - See review for tips and addt'l info", "Text": "I setup Alexa about a week before I decided to invest in this starter kit. The Home control starter kit here kit comes with the Insteon hub and two plug (two bladed socket) dimmer modules for lamps. I also purchased two of the 8 watt Insteon bulbs. Some important things to know:\n\n1) There is an app for Windows on your PC - AND for Windows Phone (I'm using Windows for Mobile 10). It worked with bulbs and plugin dimmers and I've done on-off-and dim as a test for each of my four devices. It isn't just for android and iPhone. (YAY!) Note: I was told the reason I couldn't set my location and local hub time was because I was using windows, however support was able to do this for me remotely using my hub's password < which I was asked to provide them with.\n2) You should plug your hub into an actual wall outlet, you can use an extension cord but NOT a power strip (it messes with the signal)\n3) You will need to plug this into a network port (hub, router, or wall) using the included RJ45 jacked cable. There is no Wi-Fi option.\n4) When you download the app- bring a single device online at a time. You have to start the add device process before plugging in or screwing in bulb then it'll auto-discover.\n5) It helps to use your phone/pc near the hub and device when setting up -- there's a timeout during set up you don't want to run to another room.\n6) Give your devices simple easy to use names\n7) Discover your devices from within the Alexa App\n8) Call out 'Alexa Living Lamp On' or use options like Off - dim to 50% - set to 100% - dim to 80% etc.\n9) Using the insteon app it's easy to schedule On/Off times or set schedule by night/day. Be sure to save your change in each window or it loses changes when you go back to the root scheduling page for the device. Aka- set On time and save- then go back and set off time and save.\n10) Dual Band devices like the plugins in this kit are basically signal strengtheners/repeaters. Install your closest Dual Band devices closest to the hub before installing devices farther from the hub unit.\n\nAlso - the closer you are to the hub the faster the response to your commands. I found within 15 ft, a 2 count occurs between requesting and executing a command. At a distance of probably 54 ft a 4 count occurs between request and execution. I have Alexa placed centrally within my home (which has an open hall/kitchen/living/dining concept). My hub is about 14 feet from Alexa in a direction opposite most of my 2101sqft home. At a distance of about 30 feet from Alexa, down a hallway and through a wall I was able to activate a voice command for a device about 54ft from the hub, with three walls between the device and hub. I haven't tried any farther than this, yet.\n\nOn a whole I was so emboldened by the freedom this product provides and the ease of setup I already have one more bulb, a thermostat, an outlet, and several dimmer and on/off switches on order. Currently I only have one device in any given room so I haven't tried creating groups yet - however I will be trying this as soon as other devices are installed.\n\n**** 8/29 update - I created a scene in my insteon app today, to group several fixtures together (as a start three bulbs and one plugin dimmer). While I was able to turn this scene on/off from my PC- I wasn't able to control this insteon scene from Alexa - I had to create a group for the same units directly in alexa's app instead. << just a little tip for ya :)"}
{"Author": "Carolynn S. Wiplich", "Date": "on August 19, 2016", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Not as flexible as X10 but more reliable.", "Text": "Not as flexible as X10 but more reliable."}
{"Author": "Richard S.", "Date": "on August 17, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Poor setup documentation", "Text": "Don't buy this for the following reasons:\n\n1. Setup is difficult and time consuming. You either push button combinations or manually enter addresses (not for all devices)\n2. Devices may not connect or stay connected.\n3. Schedules may run or not run.\n4. No settings backup. If it fails, you must start from the beginning again. if you placed sensors in hard-to-reach places you must retrieve them and redo button push programming. Programming apps are buggy and user hostile.\n5. Unreliable. Mine and neighbors failed within eleven months.\n6. Warranty replacement takes days.\n7. Replacement may be defective. Mine would not connect. Required call to support with requisite Hold. Required Factory reset that support did not know how to do and then a network reset. Maybe it was used.\n8. Modules are expensive and unreliable. I have already had two plugin modules fail. Hundred bucks gone.\n9. Poor setup documentation. Definitely NOT Plug n Play. If you aren't good at techie stuff don't try.\n10.Did I say unreliable. My new, maybe used hub, just ignored its first scheduled scene.\n11.Did I say don't buy this.\n12.Time to cut my loses and move on to something more reliable and better supported."}
{"Author": "Dewayne Lyles", "Date": "on August 11, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "Works like a champ"}
{"Author": "Jeffrey Lee", "Date": "on August 9, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Don't listen to the trolls. This is a great device.", "Text": "Great device. I upgraded from a previous Hub edition to allow Alexa to control my Insteon system. I am an early adopter but am not really a hacking geek. That said, I do not understand all the sniveling in these reviews about having to recreate scenes and re-link devices. Poor babies. There is no free chicken. Yes, just like getting a new computer, you will have to reload programs (and all the music you pirated using Napster). This is, after all, a new head unit for a relatively high tech system of systems. All that aside, it works like a champ. I have about 20 or so Insteon devices, installed them all myself. All of them linked quickly with no hiccups. As far as functionality with my Amazon Echo, it works great. I tell her to turn on or off something or set something to a certain percentage and she says, \"okay.\" No issues. You will have to add the Alexa skill to your Echo and create some groups using the skill software so that she can recognize what device or group of devices you want her to control. But, if you have one you are probably already familiar with that process. It's painless. Insteon was my first foray into home automation. My system has been working flawlessly for over three years. I've been using this new hub for a couple months now with no issues. It took me less than 30 minutes to go from box, to linking devices, to back to my lounge chair. I have not been disappointed."}
{"Author": "The_Def_J", "Date": "on August 8, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Great starter kit", "Text": "Great starter kit....probably would have gone with the starter kit that doesn't come with dimmers as the dimmers that come with this starter kit cannot be used with LED lighting (from what I can tell)."}
{"Author": "John Wolf", "Date": "on August 7, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Nice and easy installation", "Text": "Nice and easy installation. Had to manually input the device IDs for the initial setup but after that all is good."}
{"Author": "Mujuro", "Date": "on August 7, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Only buy if you're already invested heavily in Insteon devices", "Text": "If you're someone who is just starting out with home automation, AVOID THIS PRODUCT. Any of the other HUB-based products will likely serve you better, particularly if you're looking to integrate with some of the more popular services like IFTTT. This is because Insteon's HUB software is terrible and rather glitchy for anything but the most mundane tasks, and Insteon is a closed system that really doesn't play too well with other brands. I had purchased this because I had invested in a large number of Insteon devices years ago (back in 2007), and spent a lot of time getting everything programmed, etc., and I didn't want to replace almost 50 devices.\n\nAnd even then, I regret my decision to purchase because the Insteon Hub software doesn't recognize any existing programming, whether done through the Insteon HouseLinc software or manually through the devices themselves. In fact, the Harmony software will likely glitch and not work if you try to create scenes when you have existing programming on your devices. After speaking with Insteon support about this (they were friendly and tried to be as helpful as they could, given the limitations of the Insteon hard/software), their suggestions to me: do a factory reset of all my devices and reprogram them using the Insteon Hub software (again, which is terrible) or buy an ISY994i and try to read the existing programming and \"clean up\" any glitches the Insteon Hub software may have introduced (and this may not even work, they warned, and you'd still have to do a factory reset).\n\nI had considered the ISY994i, but opted for the Insteon Hub because it was \"natively\" supported by the Harmony (Elite) Hub and the Amazon Echo/Alexa. Don't be fooled; the integration isn't as smooth as what you'd imagine. For example, the Harmony will allow turning \"ON\" Insteon scenes through the activity screen, but there's no way to turn them OFF unless you assign the scene to a hard button. At the time of my purchase, the Echo didn't support ISY but apparently it does now. And if you're looking for deeper automation via IFTTT, Insteon isn't directly supported so you'll either need to use recipes through other devices, such as through Harmony Activities, or pay a third party a monthly fee to integrate a limited number of individual devices. This may be OK if you only have a few devices, but if you've got a whole-house set-up, you'll need some disposable income. To this end, I'm trying to learn about Insteon's API to see if I can create my own IFTTT-Insteon because I'd really hate to see my large Insteon investment go to waste, but apparently Insteon isn't granting many API keys these days, so this could just be a pipe dream.\n\nAs a final note, do NOT attach any security-related devices to the Insteon Hub. Hub communications are handled as clear text."}
{"Author": "MSPRICH", "Date": "on August 5, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "a must have for anyone looking to get in to ...", "Text": "a must have for anyone looking to get in to home automation"}
{"Author": "Matthew Myhra", "Date": "on July 31, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "cool product with lots of other add ons to buy and programmable options, semi annoying setup but easy to move forward", "Text": "for the most part the insteon works as intended and great, however it needs to be fair close to the wifrouter because setting it up requires connection to wif and is a bit of a pain at first. as long as it is range though, alexa can be used to name it what you want and find them all once setup so you can control them directly through the same wi and voice commands. you may have to get an extender for your wifi if you place is as big and two story as mine. we do use it to turn on our bearded dragons infrared and heat lamp during day and have it automatically shut it off at dusk. so it simulates real life for him"}
{"Author": "TamieC", "Date": "on July 28, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Easy to set-up, easy to operate.", "Text": "I have added 4 security cameras (2 Insteon, 2 different models), 4 door/window open and close sensors and a wet/dry sensor for near a sump pump. Easy to add devices. iOS app works on iPhone and iPad."}
{"Author": "Amazon Customer", "Date": "on July 26, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Set up was easy. Once or twice I need to reboot it ...", "Text": "Bought it to automate my home with the Amazon echo d\u00ebvice. Set up was easy. Once or twice I need to reboot it for network connectivity. I can't be certain that it's my router or not though."}
{"Author": "Franklin Johnson", "Date": "on July 25, 2016", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Works very well when you figure out how to install it.", "Text": "I like the product. I purchased the remote wall outlet. I did not even know I needed a hub. No useful instructions at all. With the hub or the outlet. The company seems to be purposely vague as to bring in customers that are not tech savvy. You tube is your best friend. Use it before you purchase the product. If you are looking for more than just a few devices you may be better off talking to someone that knows a bit about networking before making any purchases.\n\nAfter the hub and outlet were installed they have worked fine. The iphone app is easy to use. The hub froze one time. I had to manually reset it. That happens form time to time at this end of the market."}
{"Author": "California Mom", "Date": "on July 20, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "This is a fantastic kit. Setup was quick", "Text": "This is a fantastic kit. Setup was quick, it paired with the app and with Alexa in moments, and I happily ordered more On/Off pieces to plug into our outlets. WONDERFUL!"}
{"Author": "Ricker 69", "Date": "on July 19, 2016", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Two Stars", "Text": "Can't get it to work at all"}
{"Author": "Mike", "Date": "on July 18, 2016", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "If you are out of the house or worse, out of town", "Text": "I purchased a leak sensor with the 2245-222 hub. It detects water leaks, but when it does it sends an email message to my iPhone every 8-15 seconds until the leak sensor is reset. If you are out of the house or worse, out of town, your email inbox will overflow and your iPhone will receive a text message every 15 seconds until you can get home and reset it. I called Insteon and they told me it was designed that way and I had no control over how many messages (email or text) I received. This is a terrible design."}
{"Author": "Chris G.", "Date": "on July 16, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "they're really great. The problem", "Text": "When they work, they're really great. The problem? They fail all of the time.\n\nHardware:\n1-2 devices have a hardware failure every year and need to be replaced, sometimes but not always covered by warranty. Even if it's covered by warranty, you'll spend 2-4 hours waiting to get a hold of someone at SmartHome. You'll then be without a light switch for 4-5 days as it ships to you. And then you get to deal with rewiring a 120V switch or outlet. If you're handy, then it's just a pain in the ass. If you're paying someone to install these for you, that really sucks.\n\nSoftware:\nTheir software is incomprehensible to me, which is sad given that I work in technology and some degree of actual programming experience. The switches seem to lose their programming randomly and need to be reprogrammed. This can easily take 2-3 hours for my home with ~18 switches as the switches must not only be programmed to work with each other, but also the Insteon Hub app on your phone. I usually have to do this 1-2 times a year. The time-savings from being able to turn off all of the lights in my house from a single switch are nice, but this routine hassle is getting old.\n\nDon't expect to be able to rent your home to someone with these switches installed. They will drive you and your tenant crazy."}
{"Author": "Robert E. Reinheimer", "Date": "on July 16, 2016", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Beware Assumptions and Mistakes", "Text": "Beware making the mistakes that I did with this product. First, it does NOT use your home's Wi Fi network to reach other units to be controlled but creates its own and the range of that network is very limited. The hub could not detect one of the plug-in controllers in the other end of our house and I'm now reduced to buying a range extender to reach something on the same floor of the same dwelling. Second, the Quick Start guide tells us to not plug the hub into a power strip and I ignored those instructions. The hub would not work until it was plugged directly into an outlet I guess because the system ostensibly uses home wiring to reach other controllers. (See the comment after \"First\" to note how well THAT works.) Finally, I agree with other customers who have complained about the documentation that goes with this product. The setup is NOT well explained nor is it as intuitive as the product designers seem to think. And getting the interface with the Amazon Echo to work consistently has not yet succeeded. I'm not a tech idiot and rarely have the setup difficulties with other products that I have experienced with this one. I wish I had just bought more Philips HUE bulbs as THAT system is working flawlessly on its own and with the Echo."}
{"Author": "Technical Maven", "Date": "on July 16, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "A simply horrible design and implimentation!", "Text": "I started with Insteon in 2006 during a home remodel because it seemed like a well thought out and promising product line... Boy was I wrong! Terrible reliability and infuriating software and control hardware. And it just kept getting worse and worse... It seems that the 2245 has just continued their downward spiral! I can't find anything good to say about it except that it is cheap... Do yourself a favor and go a different direction!"}
{"Author": "BaR Lodge", "Date": "on July 15, 2016", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "This Starter Kit (2244-222) DOES NOT WORK with ALEXA/Amazon Echo", "Text": "This Starter Kit (2244-234) DOES NOT WORK with ALEXA. This kit has the Insteon 2242-222 Hub and will not work with Amazon Echo...to work with Alexa you will need the Insteon 2245-222 Hub to control your modules/switches. This Starter Kit does work well thru your iOS or iPad to control the dimmer modules."}
{"Author": "Judy", "Date": "on July 14, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "No Support for Hub Upgrade", "Text": "If you are upgrading from a 2242-222 to a 2245-222 be careful. Insteon has removed the X10 compatibility and the new hub can not be used with House Link software. You will also find that there is no support or documentation for upgrading from hub 1 to hub 2. Save yourself a lot of frustration and call the Insteon support number immediately. You will have to re-program all of your devices because you will have to delete and re-create your account. They really left out their current customers on this one."}
{"Author": "Saguaro", "Date": "on July 14, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "Met my expectations"}
{"Author": "Sean L.", "Date": "on July 9, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Easy to set up with no technical issues encountered so far", "Text": "Really enjoy this product and all the customization options you can do for your home automation project at an affordable price. Set up was very easy and I have not had any technical issues after a few months of use. The integration with Alexa works really well also I love being able to voice control my lights. If you are considering home automation and find the other options too expensive this is a fantastic choice."}
{"Author": "LJ", "Date": "on July 6, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Smart Home Magic!", "Text": "Works great for automating household lights. It was easy to set up. Installed the hub by plugging in the network cable and power plug. Down loaded the Insteon app in moments from the App Store. It works great with IOS. Plugged in two lights to the devices. Pressed the lower set button per device to have the app discover them. Named each device a separate name. Then had Alexa discover the devices. Works great!"}
{"Author": "lifecomp", "Date": "on July 6, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "Works great with my Alexa."}
{"Author": "Tech geek", "Date": "on July 5, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Customer Service is so terrible there's no point in buying the products. AVOID!", "Text": "Product might be good but if you ever need customer service or help, you should make sure to clear your calendar for a week. Customer service is TERRIBLE. Plan on holding for a few hours or waiting a few days for an email response asking you to call customer service. It's just not worth the trouble. If you want connected home products try anything other than Insteon. I'm ready to rip out the $2000 system I installed because every time you have a question you lose weeks of your life trying to get help."}
{"Author": "maiji", "Date": "on July 3, 2016", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Was easy to set up the hub and devices", "Text": "Was easy to set up the hub and devices.\nBut their phone app is very poor in its features.\n\nFor example, no way to set the lamp to come on at half-an-hour after sunset, or go off half-an-hour before sunrise.\nThey will come on right at sunset or go off at sunrise, but that is when most people do not need lights on, since there is sufficient brightness in the sky.\n\nThis shortcoming woudn't be so bad, were it not for the fact that there is no IFTTT (If This, Then That), which almost all the modern apps for competing systesm are now supporting.\n\nHaving buyers' remorse now."}
{"Author": "JAIRO G.", "Date": "on June 29, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Very bad experience. It didn't work", "Text": "Very bad experience. It didn't work. It didn't link to any device through app. I tried to solv the problem, following the instructions front the support center, but I couldn't solv it. I lost my money. The is the second hub I bought. It didn't work too"}
{"Author": "Orlando Cordova", "Date": "on June 27, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "Works great"}
{"Author": "SJ", "Date": "on June 25, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "I would like to say setup is a breeze", "Text": "Updated: 6/28/2016: I would like to say setup is a breeze, but it depends on your passwords and firewall setup. Few things I had issues with: The Insteon password that I created for the setup may have had a character that it did not like, not sure on this. My passwords are usually sentences (they are long - made short for this setup about 16 to 25 characters and I will try to increase later). Hopefully, you use WPA2. My router instantly rejected the MAC on this, so I had to approved the MAC, The port is written on the back of the unit; however, appears to only be used in the LAN. The router that I used on this setup doesn't give good logs, it may have been the number on the back, so I had to temporarily bring down the firewall on a range or ports, just to be sure. I did not block communication between devices on WiFi. The port appear to be your standard ports HTTP:, DHCP (I use static) DNS and HTTPS (I hope I have them all) . The big port I missed was NTP (123) going from LAN to Internet. Apparently, it goes from green to red when that port is missing and things slow down! Devices usually get found right away by the HUB, but you may need an Insteon extender (research that). If the light on the hub is solid red, check your firewall and MAC filtering (my case). I did not look which NTP servers it uses or other IP address for that matter."}
{"Author": "TestCalifornia", "Date": "on June 25, 2016", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Not a bad choice. Set up instructions need significant improvement", "Text": "Not a bad choice. Set up instructions need significant improvement. Even videos might be more helpful. Not having readily available videos or easy to use instructions makes me uneasy, especially when you compare such products to Nest or other customer friendly products."}
{"Author": "DjeAMZN", "Date": "on June 25, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "I wanted to like it, but didnt", "Text": "I wanted to like it, but didnt. Not at all sure why their products get decent reviews. Super buggy, very poor range, garage monitor extremely difficult to install. All went in the trash."}
{"Author": "qbang", "Date": "on June 18, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Great for simple home automation.", "Text": "Works as advertised. Bought this after a lot of research. needed something to turn our roof shingle/gutter heating wire on and off remotely. Worked perfectly via wifi through the winter, whether or not we were home. Wifi set up was quick and easy. Phone app works great. Can't vouch for how wide the signal range is, how the scheduled programming works, or how it works with multiple items. But as a simple device for remote on and off, it does the job."}
{"Author": "Amazon Customer", "Date": "on June 17, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "The ability to use an Apple Watch with it is pretty cool too", "Text": "Worked right out of the box to replace a PowerLinc. The ability to use an Apple Watch with it is pretty cool too. Scenes are a little harder to set up than with Indigo but the user interface is clean."}
{"Author": "beerfuzz", "Date": "on June 16, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Finally a way to get rid of her.", "Text": "Life is brighter now that Alexa turns on my lights. First time I was washing my hands and thinking man.. I wish the lights were on in here.. wait.. \"Alexa.. turn on the kitchen lights\" BAM.. daylight in my kitchen. I sold my wife the next day."}
{"Author": "Karla Andrew", "Date": "on June 15, 2016", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "A near impossible upgrade from an older model!", "Text": "I got this to upgrade our old insteon hub and work with Alexa. I assumed it would be an easy and quick upgrade - NOT! The hub doesn't have an easy way to move our old items to the new hub. Our old items include a camera - hanging high on the wall and a garage door controller on the ceiling. The set buttons and the codes for them are out of my reach! No easy way to move them.\n\nI'm still in the process of trying. Additionally I downloaded Houselinc thinking that would make it easy as I had set the old up on my old computer, but didn't realize it would need completely set up again. Another fail. Frustated! Still working on upgrading."}
{"Author": "Bruce", "Date": "on June 14, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "As advertised."}
{"Author": "Lewis", "Date": "on June 13, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Hot pile of garbage, backed by horrible customer service", "Text": "Hot pile of garbage, backed by horrible customer service. I bought a Fanlinc and hub.\nI had questions about the Fanlinc while I was installing my new ceiling fan, customer service doesn't work weekends, and when I called on Monday, took 45 minutes to get connected. Then rep was dismissive of my question and suggested I call a professional.\nThe hub I bought doesn't work (per their customer service) and I need to send it back in for a new one. It literally took me an hour to get them to admit this. Prior to that I power cycled router/model/hub at least twice, installed their app on my new ipad, newer Android Phone, AND installed their Windows 10 app (all of which obviously failed to solve the problem). Then we spend some time rolling back some firmware, in addition to logging into my router settings and taking a look at things from behind that curtain. My customer service rep patiently reminded me \"normally, this sets up in 5-10 minutes\". Oh, and again, it took 45+ minutes to get in touch with their customer support. So from start of issues to printing off shipping labels to send it back, it took me about 2 hours of doing nothing but be focused on this trash heap.\nAs someone who owns 20+ hue bulbs, a few Amazon Echos/Dots/Rachio/Ecobee, I can say without a doubt that this is the WORST smarthome product I've ever attempted to try.\nDid I mention my ceiling fan is bricked until I take it down and uninstall the FanLinc?"}
{"Author": "L'Enfant Terrible", "Date": "on June 10, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "much improved in the current iteration of firmware", "Text": "I am writing a review for this product because many of the existing reviews are quite dated.\n\nMy initial impression of this product was very poor - like 1 star at most. It failed to identify some of my devices ( I have perhaps 20 ), it would inexplicably fail to control some devices, it would fail to execute scheduled scenes, and in some cases it would simply die and require a reboot.\n\nFast forward to June 2016 and several new versions of firmware and application ( for iOS ) later and this is a MUCH better product that lives up to it's promise to a great extent. In the last several months I have had (almost) no problems of any kind. I've been able to define scenes without any problem, all my scheduled scenes have been executed flawlessly and best of all Siri integration has worked 100% of the time.\n\nIs it perfect? No, not by any means. There is still no sensor support of any kind, there is no web app, the iPad apps have layout issues and dozens and dozens of other small quibbles. But in the end when it's late and your tired and you're about to get into bed and all the lights are on throughout the house you can simply say 'Hey Siri, Lights Out' and it works!"}
{"Author": "inxs4", "Date": "on June 9, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Can't live without. Once you start, you will be addicted!", "Text": "Pretty simple to setup. I wasn't sure how this would work out, but I'm glad that I have it. I use it for turning on lights in the evening and off at bedtime. One thing that would be nice is if there was a way to tell it to turn lights on 30 minutes before sunset. Always seems that doing at sunset it's already too dark in the house. So, I just have it set for a specific time.\n\nRecently I had gotten an email saying there was going to be an update on the device. That took me by surprise, because I don't like new software updates without knowing what's included, and being given the option of not doing it. addicted"}
{"Author": "Patrick J. Kelley", "Date": "on June 8, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "East to install/set-up and love how it works", "Text": "East to install/set-up and love how it works. I use it with the Amazon Echo and the integration was seamless."}
{"Author": "Amazon Customer", "Date": "on June 2, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "One Star", "Text": "was not able to connect with alexa"}
{"Author": "Michael", "Date": "on May 31, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "The system is great! Works just like it was described and what ...", "Text": "The system is great! Works just like it was described and what I needed! Easy to set up and operate if you follow the directions!!!"}
{"Author": "Joondog", "Date": "on May 30, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Four Stars", "Text": "Can't find anybody to install. System not as simple as advertised."}
{"Author": "Jeffrey Engel", "Date": "on May 30, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "Great with Amazon Echo"}
{"Author": "BobTaylor", "Date": "on May 28, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Much better than the original version", "Text": "Much better than the original version, a lot of problems are corrected in this second generation product. So far so good, no failures..."}
{"Author": "Stu", "Date": "on May 26, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "I experienced just about all the symptoms stated by others who hated this product", "Text": "The lesson I learned is always read the reviews before purchasing. I experienced just about all the symptoms stated by others who hated this product."}
{"Author": "Charles Ho", "Date": "on May 24, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "It takes very little to set it up!", "Text": "It takes very little to set it up and it works as advertised!! Now, I can control those lamp using my phone! Thanks to Insteon, to my 8 years old niece, I am officially 'kool' now! :-)"}
{"Author": "Ray Harwood", "Date": "on May 18, 2016", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Failed at 18 months.", "Text": "Update 11/02/17: Unit failed 18 months after purchase. Status light dark, smells of burnt electronics.\n-----\nI'm just getting started with Insteon, and I've heard good and bad. So far, I'm liking it, but not really impressed with it.\n\nMy first problem was that the hub wouldn't connect to my network. I went through every troubleshooting process I could find... no luck. Then I thought, \"what's the chance they shipped a bad Ether connector with the unit?\" It's not a professional, molded connector cable... it looks hand cut and crimped. Guess what: it's a bad cable. Hub connected right up when I put a good cable on the unit.\n\nThe user interface on the iPhone and iPad does indeed seem immature, or not well thought out."}
{"Author": "Tony", "Date": "on May 16, 2016", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "it's ok for the price but if you get in ...", "Text": "it's ok for the price but if you get in to home automation you will out grow the hub in no time and upgrade."}
{"Author": "Craig Mangold", "Date": "on May 16, 2016", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Beware hub only lasts about 2 years.", "Text": "I have had the insteon system for many years starting with the 1st generation hub. I like the system but 2 years ago I upgraded both my homes to this 2nd generation hub. Within 1 week of each other both 2nd generation hubs died after only 2 years. So be prepared to buy a new replacement hub after about 2 years. Not a simple process to replace either. Since old hub is dead you can't delete because you can't communicate to it. You have to email insteon support with a picture of the bottom of hub and they have to delete before you can install replacement hub. Then you have to re-add all your devices, scenes, etc to new hub. Can be a very long task especially if you have many scenes."}
{"Author": "jaime c.", "Date": "on May 15, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "What an amazing idea. I can control absolutely everything in my ...", "Text": "What an amazing idea. I can control absolutely everything in my house, open my garage door, control every single fan, I bought remote controls, dimmers, outdoor on/off, micro modules, etc. Please do NOT leave a review of this unit unless you try 90% of their devices. After you buy all the devices, you realize that yes, there are mistakes. For example, the motion controller is absolutely horrible. I am not sure if that is the hub fault or the motion controller fault, but let me say it just doesn't work. There are bugs in the apps, for example FanLinc will work great when adding it to a scene, but then if you check the Scene again, both the Fan and the Linc says 'light' for both the fan and the light.\n\nThe most amazing thing is the thermostat, as soon as it kicks in, wow, my 2 fans (one ceiling fan, one fan for the feet) in my office and my ceiling fan in my master room turn on!\n\nMy house is now the house of the future!\n\nI cannot wait to buy Somfy motors for my shades so when the air conditioner kicks in, the house will automatically close the curtains so the house can be even cooler.\n\nWhen I go to my garage, it automatically turns on the light.\n\nOh and did I mention, after you configure all your Insteon devices, if your Insteon Central Controller Hub loses power, everything in the house keeps working!\nThe devices do NOT talk through the Hub, after you configure them, they work DIRECTLY!\n\nI do NOT imagine how the Apple Home Kit hub can be a bad product, I haven't tried that one yet, it seems like the company has focused on this Hub instead.\n\nI will also buy an Insteon Hub Pro, just to see if they can control my Philips Hue lights, and maybe I can have two hubs in my house.\n\nWill I like this Hub to work with Apple Home Kit?\nAbsolutely yes.\n\nDo I think this item is perfect?\nAbsolutely yes.\n\nI don't know, maybe next year they'll come up with something amazing, for now, this is absolutely ridiculous and will make you, the home owner, a very happy handyman!!!\n\nDId I mention I can turn on my thermostat from my Apple Watch??? ;-)"}
{"Author": "jaime c.", "Date": "on May 15, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "What an amazing idea. I can control absolutely everything in my ...", "Text": "What an amazing idea. I can control absolutely everything in my house, open my garage door, control every single fan, I bought remote controls, dimmers, outdoor on/off, micro modules, etc. Please do NOT leave a review of this unit unless you try 90% of their devices. After you buy all the devices, you realize that yes, there are mistakes. For example, the motion controller is absolutely horrible. I am not sure if that is the hub fault or the motion controller fault, but let me say it just doesn't work. There are bugs in the apps, for example FanLinc will work great when adding it to a scene, but then if you check the Scene again, both the Fan and the Linc says 'light' for both the fan and the light.\n\nThe most amazing thing is the thermostat, as soon as it kicks in, wow, my 2 fans (one ceiling fan, one fan for the feet) in my office and my ceiling fan in my master room turn on!\n\nMy house is now the house of the future!\n\nI cannot wait to buy Somfy motors for my shades so when the air conditioner kicks in, the house will automatically close the curtains so the house can be even cooler.\n\nWhen I go to my garage, it automatically turns on the light.\n\nOh and did I mention, after you configure all your Insteon devices, if your Insteon Central Controller Hub loses power, everything in the house keeps working!\nThe devices do NOT talk through the Hub, after you configure them, they work DIRECTLY!\n\nI do NOT imagine how the Apple Home Kit hub can be a bad product, I haven't tried that one yet, it seems like the company has focused on this Hub instead.\n\nI will also buy an Insteon Hub Pro, just to see if they can control my Philips Hue lights, and maybe I can have two hubs in my house.\n\nWill I like this Hub to work with Apple Home Kit?\nAbsolutely yes.\n\nDo I think this item is perfect?\nAbsolutely yes.\n\nI don't know, maybe next year they'll come up with something amazing, for now, this is absolutely ridiculous and will make you, the home owner, a very happy handyman!!!\n\nDId I mention I can turn on my thermostat from my Apple Watch??? ;-)"}
{"Author": "Gordon Belt", "Date": "on May 14, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Good Product", "Text": "It's a good product but I returned it for a different model that would work on my present automation system. No negative reflection on this product."}
{"Author": "Scientificruler", "Date": "on May 13, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Unit is Junk. Schedules do not work properly. ...", "Text": "Unit is Junk. Schedules do not work properly. Called Insteon for help, waiting times are in excess of 30 minutes. Going back to Houselinc software."}
{"Author": "H.D.Munn", "Date": "on May 11, 2016", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "INSTEON Hub not really useful", "Text": "The INSTEON Hub seems to work fine - even though I found the setup procedure \"daunting\" to say the least. I did not realize that I had to d/l an \"app\" for the thing and I had no idea how to do that or where to go in order to get the app.\n\nEven though the Hub works okay, it is of little use to me as the HD Camera that I really needed, won't work in a Windows desktop environment. The factory knew this in advance. I only found it out thru technical support (2 hours on the phone to Calif.). So, the Hub is just sitting there doing nothing.\n\nI cannot recommend either of these devices."}
{"Author": "George", "Date": "on May 11, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Love it! Works very well with Amazon Echo", "Text": "Love it! Works very well with Amazon Echo."}
{"Author": "G P", "Date": "on May 10, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Easy to setup, excellent performance", "Text": "I'm not sure why there are so many negative reviews for this product. I set it up in about 30 minutes, and that includes pairing 5 devices to it and programming scenes. Performance is fine and the app, while not the most user friendly, is reasonably straightforward to use. If you have a bunch of Insteon devices, this hub will let you control and automate them with ease."}
{"Author": "James L.", "Date": "on May 10, 2016", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "I could not get this product to work properly in ...", "Text": "I could not get this product to work properly in my house. Maybe house is too large, with 2 story and basement. Insteon tech support had 30 to 45 minute wait time."}
{"Author": "April van den Berg", "Date": "on May 10, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "Works perfect"}
{"Author": "Sandy", "Date": "on May 7, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "One Star", "Text": "Does not play with alot of devices unless you use there products. Light bulbs are the bigest ones"}
{"Author": "Amazon Customer", "Date": "on May 6, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "it sucks", "Text": "Do not buy this, it sucks"}
{"Author": "AAL", "Date": "on May 5, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Although the set up wasn't that easy (took several calls to custom service) it now functions ...", "Text": "Although the set up wasn't that easy (took several calls to custom service) it now functions great!! Customer service was awesome at helping set it up and helped me walk through everything. You will likely need customer service to help you unless you are pretty comfortable with IP addresses and setting up IP devices. I have several camera, light dimmers, wall switches and apple watch and alexa integration works great! I am very happy with the system. It is so nice to check in on the kids while I am away to see if they did what I told them to do or to see if they are in bed on time. Just about to add a few more on/off switches to turn the TV off on my kids remotely! Wahoo!"}
{"Author": "L. Bee", "Date": "on May 1, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Self monitoring system", "Text": "I have this product a little over a month, and would recommend it if you are looking to get out of monthly security payments. The products are individually price, and can be costly, with a few offered in a package. If you add up the monthly payment, installment fee, plus deposit you have to pay to security company you'll see the saving almost immediately. Work very well thus far with a notification send to my phone each time a door or window is open/closed. I hope eventually they will come up with away for owners to have link buttons for the police, ambulance, and fire department. I love it and would recommend it as an alternative to pricey security fee."}
{"Author": "Kindle Customer", "Date": "on April 29, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "Works great with Alexa"}
{"Author": "tempe time traveler", "Date": "on April 28, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "Works with Amazon Echo perfectly"}
{"Author": "Douglas E Falkenburg", "Date": "on April 27, 2016", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Not ready for prime time...", "Text": "1) No X10. I built X10 circuits into my attic stair motors and door lock controls. Look like I have some rewiring ahead. Plus I use X10 key fobs, not available with insteon. (literature I read prior to purchase promised X10 compatibility)\n2) Programming of modules flaky. Sometimes I have to single click a keypad to turn on light. Sometimes double click. Why? Don't know.\n3) Alerts: Major PITA. Sometimes work, sometimes not. Multi-email recipients delimiter? Comma? Semi? Who knows. Their baffling Email validation process hit or miss. When the basement floods or the CO detectors goes off would be nice to have reliable alerts. Alas!\n4) Alexa interface: Major trauma! Doesn't import my scenes. Ok. I'll redo them with Alexa's \"groups\". Except Alexa doesn't import/recognize the two 220V insteon relays I installed next to the service panel!!! There goes my AC controller, like \"Alexa, turn on the air conditioning\". (By the way thanks insteon for not telling me in the specs that they are only for 30A RESISTIVE loads. NTL I took them apart and found the relay inside is rated for 2hp motors)\n5) No macro support. No IR module support. So I can't have Alexa turn on my receiver, switch the input to CD, and play music thru the Dot.\n6) Programming scenes hit or miss. Sometimes weird error msg. So I start over.\n7) Bought an ISY 994i, hopefully will work better and its suppose to be programmable AND work with Alexa."}
{"Author": "D. Damato", "Date": "on April 23, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Overall I'm happy with it for the price", "Text": "Overall I'm happy with it for the price. If I paid more this may have gotten 3 stars. Had to add the two devices manually because the hub didn't find them on its own even though they were all in the same room. Also, I have to stop and restart the app a lot which is kind of annoying. I use my echo to control the devices most of the time anyway so its not all that bad"}
{"Author": "Man in MN", "Date": "on April 21, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "What a POS. Gimme the old hub back!", "Text": "Junk. Seller gave me a 'returned' unit, so I have no idea if it actually works or not.\n\nThat said, I can't get it to connect to the app, which makes it garbage to me. Was replacing an older model 2242-222 hub with this. I like the size of this, however I'm not even sure it is compatible with other Insteon software. Yes I said software. Like HouseLinc, which I've used to manage everything for the last couple years.\n\nLooks like it may be time to just move off of Insteon all together, which is annoying because I'm already heavily invested in it (light switches, outlets, modules, cameras)."}
{"Author": "Gina D.", "Date": "on April 21, 2016", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "The programming of different devices is too limited.", "Text": "I received this as a gift, as I had an idea for a \"programmable timer\" that could be set-up by an app in your phone, but Quirky went out of business before I could submit it. I told a friend about my idea, and he remarked, \"it's already been invented,\" and so he gifted this to me. The system is \"close\" to my invention, but lacks what my idea has, flexibility.\n\nThe system comes with a controller, plus two dimmer modules. The controller has to be plugged into a wall outlet (no power strip) and into your internet router (it comes with a Ethernet cable) so you can communicate to the controller via Wi-Fi, and remotely. The modules communicate to the controller, I assume, through the wiring in your wall. Install their app to your phone from your phone's app store. Launch the app, pick \"Add a Device\", plug-in a module, and press the button on the side, so the app can discover it. Easy enough.\n\nNow the problem; everything I wished to control is either an LED or fluorescent lamp. Dimmer modules do not play well with those two lamp types. When \"off,\" my LED lamps would just dim, and my fluorescent lamp would flicker. So, my next thought was to use them on \"something\" that would not react like this, but these modules are only capable of handling 300-watts (2.5-amps)! They're best suited for something I no longer use; incandescent lamps. I ended up tossing the modules in a drawer.\n\nUndaunted, and due to a Amazon Gift card, I thought I'd give this thing another chance so I purchased the basic plug-in On-Off module, and an On-Off wall switch. These two modules were great, as they were rated for 1800-watts (15-amps). The plug-in module went to control the fluorescent lamp of my aquarium, while the wall switch went to operate the porch and walk-way lights. Adding them to the app was easy, as explained before. Now the next problem; flexibility! Insteon's interface programmer, apparently, never heard of it.\n\nAs mentioned, I am controlling an aquarium lamp, and a porch light. I'd like to have them both come on a dusk, but the aquarium turn-off at Midnight, while the porch light turn-off a dawn; cannot be done! The app does not allow two \"schedules\" sharing the same \"on or \"off\" time. seems rather ridiculous and an unnecessary limit.\n\nNow, you can have two or more devices share the same schedule, and this is done through creating \"scenes,\" which are nothing more than an \"on-off\" time that allow multiple devices.\n\nTo be fair, I suppose I'm not Insteon's target customer. I think it would be better to receive the basic \"on-off\" module than the dimmers, but I suppose it's the only way Insteon can get rid of them, since most people I know no longer use incandescent bulbs. I suppose it's a plus for Insteon making additional money selling the modules one can really use.\n\nMy conclusion is this system is just OK. I wouldn't buy one if what you're looking to do is what I use it for. The inflexibility of the programming interface is very disappointing. One should be able to intermix multiple devices to share on-off times.\n\nSave your money, go to Harbor Freight, and buy regular dial timers."}
{"Author": "george skutevik", "Date": "on April 21, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "Worked good"}
{"Author": "Juan Gomez", "Date": "on April 20, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "Good deal"}
{"Author": "Joe Palma", "Date": "on April 20, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "... set this up with both wall plugs and my best thermostat. Can't wait to start expanding my home ...", "Text": "It took me 15 minutes to set this up with both wall plugs and my best thermostat. Can't wait to start expanding my home automation. I had no problems getting this set up and working"}
{"Author": "Faerie Girl", "Date": "on April 19, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "... old to work with the hub but it works great. Awesome product so far", "Text": "Wasn't sure if my wall switches were too old to work with the hub but it works great. Awesome product so far."}
{"Author": "Julien", "Date": "on April 18, 2016", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Good product doesn't hold a candle to the Phillips hue system", "Text": "I had to buy the hub because I bought a component of Instion. That would not have worked without it. The set up was a little difficult and the overall parent process was not easy compared to Phillips hue or we mow. The device will also occasionally beep I still have not figured out why."}
{"Author": "Cinderessa", "Date": "on April 16, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Great! Works very well with my Amazon Echo", "Text": "Great! Works very well with my Amazon Echo! I love telling Alexa to turn appliances off and on downstairs from the upstairs. It's convenient and pretty cool."}
{"Author": "Eric Nelson", "Date": "on April 16, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Four Stars", "Text": "Very helpful for senior citizen."}
{"Author": "Terrence C. Watson", "Date": "on April 14, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "It will be great someday", "Text": "I have had some INSTEON controlled outlets and lights in my home and home office for some time now with about equal parts success and frustration. But I am a sucker for new stuff and I truly love my roommate, Alexa, so I decided to give her something to play with and bought this, which is virtually a duplicate of what I already had but would not work with my Amazon Echo.\nAlexa brings convenience (i.e. laziness) to a whole new level. Now I can just say, \"Alexa, turn on the bug zapper\" and she will turn on the fly execution device in the greenhouse, or, \"Alexa, dim the kitchen lights to 50%\" and it will happen.\nOK, so that's the good part. The bad part is the thoroughly frustrating software app that INSTEON provides for use with or without Alexa. In concept it is great. I should be able to set schedules for various lights and outlets or even special thermostats. I should be able to tell it to turn specific lights or groups of lights at sunset and off at a particular time, or at sunrise. So far and after much email conversations with their support, I can do some of it fine and others not at all.\nWhen INSTEON (note that they are capitalizing their name each time, not me) gets it right, I will be able to just say \"Alexa, always turn on the living room ceiling lights at 20 minutes after sunset, except on Thursdays\" and she will take it from there. INSTEON has finally figured out when sunset is each day of the year by my geographic location so that part is covered."}
{"Author": "JR393", "Date": "on April 14, 2016", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Three Stars", "Text": "couldn't get it to work in a very large house"}
{"Author": "Gixxer", "Date": "on April 13, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "So far great product. Have it hooked up and working as ...", "Text": "So far great product. Have it hooked up and working as expected."}
{"Author": "A root", "Date": "on April 13, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Great product if you don't expect too much from it", "Text": "The Insteon hub works well once it's set up properly. It is true that you have to pair the hub to each of your devices, but you don't have to go back and forth between the hub and the device if you add them via the Insteon Android/iOS app. Management of the devices I already have is actually much easier using the hub rather than using the 'set' button on each device to set up scenes and responders.\n\nAmazon Echo was easy to set up to work with this hub and it's quite a bit more reliable than the Philips Hue bridge that my Echo is also connected to."}
{"Author": "Kindle Customer", "Date": "on April 8, 2016", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "A complete lie", "Text": "This item is advertised to work with Alexa (Amazon Echo), So I purchased it and after installing it it would not interface with the Amazon\nEcho at all. So I went to the Insteon website and found that the only hub that interfaces with the amazon Echo is Model Number 2245-222, so I returned it to the seller for a refund, and was refunded less than I originally paid for it. BUYER BEWARE!!!!!"}
{"Author": "R. Stanley", "Date": "on April 6, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Sorry I did it....", "Text": "Insteon servers are down....I spent hours trying to figure out why it would not connect to their servers after I replaced my router. Very disappointed with this and wished I would have went with different vendor but i have a ton of money invested in their devices. There is another controller on the market that is more complicated but at least it is more reliable. When it works it is great but it is not reliable to control my house...."}
{"Author": "wrknnwf", "Date": "on April 2, 2016", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Almost there...please fix the app so I can up my review", "Text": "The hub and modules included in this kit work fine. But I am highly disappointed in the app. I would have given this 5 starts if the app would allow me to change the location, time, ramp speed or set schedules. Other than that everything seems to be working well and it plays nicely with Alexa. When they fix the app, I will change my rating and update this review"}
{"Author": "Thomas", "Date": "on April 1, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "It was an easy set-up. I have also connected this to my ...", "Text": "It was an easy set-up. I have also connected this to my Amazon Echo which is awesome. I want to try more of the Insteon products.\nI have an apartment and I use these on my floor lamps. I have also purchased 1 of the recessed lights so I will be trying that tonight.\nThe only thing I do recommend is buying a remote for these products. because lets be honest your not always going to have your phone on you."}
{"Author": "Amazon Customer", "Date": "on March 31, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "One Star", "Text": "Will not work with Windows 10 phone"}
{"Author": "Mike Fanchin", "Date": "on March 29, 2016", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "This unit is ok for home control, but not home automation", "Text": "I have 96 devices in my home automation network and am used to a full-featured home automation system. I find the insteon hub ok for controlling a simple network but lacking in features needed for home automation.\n\nYou manage the hub and define & control devices connected to insteon modules in your home from an app installed on your phone. You can set up simple schedules to turn devices on/off by time of day or sunrise/sunset. You can read the status of insteon sensors in the home on demand, and it's supposed to be able to send you an email from \"the cloud\" when sensor status changes, but there's no way to set \"rules\" or \"events\" to instruct the hub to do something on its own when, for instance, the leak sensor detects water. The phone app is a little clunky but I would hope this will improve. It's almost like they added additional screens just to make it look more full-featured than it is: Finding where to change the name of a device after it was added was a real challenge. The variety of devices you can add seems limited also. Smoke detectors, door locks, and unique items like the SynchroLinc seem to be conspicuously absent from the Add Device list.\n\nOther posts are correct: For those of you who have existing devices you need to add them to the hub from scratch. This though, according to Smarthome, is a security feature of insteon, not a failure of the hub, and was intended to prevent someone from driving up to your driveway and getting control over your home: There is apparently no way to \"scan\" an insteon network to find/add your devices... you have to link/pair each item manually."}
{"Author": "Elizabeth", "Date": "on March 28, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Easy to install", "Text": "We got this so when we are away we can turn lights on and off with our phones without a monthly charge. Easy to install and works great. Next we are going to try the wall switches to see if they works as well as the plugs.\n\nWe would definitely recommend this product if you are looking to control lighting without monthly fees."}
{"Author": "P. Grace", "Date": "on March 27, 2016", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "I wish I'd bought the ISY994i in the beginning", "Text": "This hub is an interface, it is not a hub in the sense that it can not be programmed to control your lights as is implied.\nIt can talk to a cloud service that you program to run your home.\nYour mobile phone can talk to the cloud, and in this way your phone can control your home.\nAlternatively, you can buy an app (Houselink) for a PC that will talk to this interface, but you can't have two controllers (your PC and the Cloud) so you would lose cloud control.\nCloud \"programming\" is very basic, there are many conditionals that can't be programmed, and any internet interrupts mean you can't control your home from your phone, even if your WiFi router is fine.\nHouselink programming is better, but still crude, but does not depend on the internet, but does require a 24/7 host PC. (I have a weatherstation, so it's not a problem for me.\n\nI wish I'd bought the ISY994i in the beginning and saved myself all the frustration."}
{"Author": "Martha E", "Date": "on March 26, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "Just what my son wanted."}
{"Author": "Teresa K. Braden DO", "Date": "on March 25, 2016", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Three Stars", "Text": "does not work very well with the base unit"}
{"Author": "James Meadows", "Date": "on March 24, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "But like many of the other users", "Text": "I was hopeful that I could get the Hub to work. But like many of the other users, I found the overall setup experience quite bad. I laughed when I first opened the box and noticed the new orange sticker on the inside of the box which states, \"... please call us for installation help before you return this product to store.\" Not a good sign. I'm not going into the 2 hours I spent trying to get the product to work. But do note that it doesn't like the Android OS. You will have more luck setting it up on your Windows OS."}
{"Author": "Ken B.", "Date": "on March 24, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "One of the best options to start using Insteon", "Text": "One of the best options to start using Insteon, cheaper than buying the hub and dimmers separately and very easy to setup and use."}
{"Author": "M. Dowdie", "Date": "on March 21, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "I'm happy with the hub. Negative reviews undeserved in my opinion.", "Text": "I bought this hub in a kit along with Insteon switches and leak sensors. I've replaced the few X10 devices I already had in place and added more Insteon switches. Perhaps things have improved since some of the earlier reviews, but overall my experience has been very positive. After a few weeks, I've only seen a couple of small glitches that I can't account for and those were with adding complicated scenes and certainly weren't show stoppers.\n\nTo one reviewer's complaint about having to manually add devices, this is still true at first. You have to go touch each device the first time. To be fair, there's really no other good way to do this. The hub detects the device and gives you a chance to name it and assign it to a room. When adding devices to scenes, the hub automatically added all my wired in / plugged in devices without having to touch them again. Battery powered devices such as leak sensors and open/close sensors do require manually pressing the set button to add / change scenes.\n\nScenes and timers have worked well. Yes, there are some limitations but the hub and app will meet most people's needs. Others will need more complex PC / Mac software. Everything has been reliable so far.\n\nThe Amazon Echo integration, while it doesn't yet support scenes in full, really adds value. It's great to be able to easily control lights by voice."}
{"Author": "A Customer", "Date": "on March 20, 2016", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "For a product that's been around 11 years, it's unstable and limited....", "Text": "I've been using X-10 products from Smarthome for nearly 20 years...and I was looking forward to migrating to the new Insteon and similar functionality, but this product, despite how long it's been around, is still unstable. The desktop software to run the hub, HouseLinc, does not work with this particular model hub, so you're limited to the mobile phone software. Then when Daylight Savings Time implemented, I learned about a bug in the software that's been around for 2 years, and lights were turning on/off at odd hours, with me unable to access and set the correct time through the mobile application (it just clocked forever). Final straw was the 60 minute wait times in queue after finding no solutions in the documentation, support community or Knowledge Base. I packed it up and returned it tonight, too many limitations and glitches."}
{"Author": "NK", "Date": "on March 20, 2016", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "good, not good enough and missing critical feature.", "Text": "I bought it for the leak sensor. they both operate well, based on tests i did. alert is sent to the app and the email. However - there is no option to audio alarm to be activated at home. say you are in bed and there's a leak - you'll know about it only after turning on the smartphone or email.\nThe \"good\" part is that i placed a question on the web site a week ago, but did not get a response."}
{"Author": "Cheapskate", "Date": "on March 18, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Unreliable time waster", "Text": "Worthless time waster. Set-up is a pain, programming is non-intuitive, once programmed it is very unreliable. If you enjoy wasting huge amounts of time fiddling with this to accomplish even the simplest task, then this is for you. Once you've put in enough hours getting it to work, enjoy the moment, because it won't last. Over time I have backed off to the simplest task of many I had planned - a simple dusk to dawn on/off function for one switch and while I can get it to work for up to a month or so, it always comes undone. Logging into the app is problematic, always losing the password, making changes that don't always \"stick\", time keeps re-setting to pacific (where their servers are), \"hub not found\" on my router, although it shows up on the router itself, and on and on. I've had it for over a year now and it's value beyond a paperweight is unknown. At this point I think it would be easier to teach my cat to turn the freaking light on and off!"}
{"Author": "Gary", "Date": "on March 16, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Great Product, Horrible Documention", "Text": "Insteon does what it says it\u2019s going to do but getting it to do what you want it to do can be an exercise in frustration.\n\nWhen I connected the hub to my router it never configured itself. After moving it to several other ports it finally did. From there downloading the application and connecting to controllers was fairly easy.\n\nNow comes the frustrating part. The software that comes with the unit is totally lacking in any useful documentation. The \"quick start guide\" is very good in explaining how to set up and configure the hub and modules but when it comes to the nuances of the software app, zilch, bupkis, nada! For example after setting up dimmer module and then testing the light connected to it turns on and off one can set a \"on level\". You\u2019d think that once that \"on level\" was set it would be remembered the next time the light was turned on. Think again, it isn\u2019t. One has to create a scene, add then add a device to that scene and then set that level.\n\nAfter adding a device to scene and accessing \"scene members\" there are 3 configuration dots that allow one to edit or delete the item. If you choose the edit button there is a blue and red (color may be different on your phone or app), box. The blue box has the option for \"responder, controller or both\". No where in any documentation could I find anything to indicate what the different options are. Accessing the green option allows one to set a permanent \"on rate\" and \"ramp\" rate. Again there isn't any documentation on what a \"ramp rate\" is either.\n\nThe above is just one example of the many documentation deficiencies. I consider myself proficient with technology. However, even I was very challenged in getting Insteon to function the way I want it to function.\n\nGiven the above I\u2019m sure many users might decide to totally give up on configuring their system. Take heart, this is one company that has excellent customer support. The wait times to speak to a specialist can be lengthy but they do have a \"call back\" feature that allows you to enter your name, phone number and a brief description of your problem and they will call you back. The specialists are very patient and understanding.\n\nAs indicated above I am very comfortable with technology and have the \"Amazon Echo\". After configuring the \"connected home\" option it is possible to control Insteon using voice commands without having to use the Insteon app at all."}
{"Author": "theus", "Date": "on March 15, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Really, really bad stuff.", "Text": "I received an Amazon Echo for Christmas and immediately fell in love with it, so I decided to try home automation. The Insteon Starter Kit looked as good as anything. It didn't turn out that way. It kind of worked for a while. I plugged two lamps into the Insteon boxes and it would turn them on and off, but dimming really didn't work. Then the hub kept disconnecting from my network, and now it won't connect at all. I also bought an Insteon light switch. I never got that to work, although it did work manually.\n\nYou have to call Insteon on the phone to request a warranty return, and I didn't feel like it because I didn't like the stuff anyway. So I bought a Philips Hue Starter Kit here at Amazon and there is NO comparison! Plug in the Hue hub, push a button, screw in a couple of light bulbs, and it's amazing. You can check it out. I would not recommend Insteon."}
{"Author": "Skeeter", "Date": "on March 15, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Worst excuse of an electronic device I've ever encountered!", "Text": "This product provided me with the worst electronic experience imaginable. I've returned it, resorting to a string, two cans, and a paper towel tube for a security system - they are much more effective. This product is advertised specifically for Windows, as Microsoft has entered into a partnership with Insteon. Pffffft. It wouldn't text, wouldn't push messages, wouldn't e-mail, and wouldn't recognize their own Insteon brand camera for installation. I spent hours messing with this product, two of which were with tech support. The fine young lady was very talented and patient, but informed me that my problems were because of known \"bugs\" in their app. I'm returning it, albeit with a guilty conscience because I don't want this product to be refurbished and foisted onto some other innocent victim. Maybe we could send it to the Russians, thereby frustrating their hacking efforts of our State Department private servers. There's NO chance they could make this paperweight work either. Thanks to Amazon for their return policy! My OS is Windows 10."}
{"Author": "GLF", "Date": "on March 14, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "I love the Insteon products. Installation is easy, as is set-up, and they work great."}
{"Author": "Kelli", "Date": "on March 14, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Do not buy this item from this seller", "Text": "This item is no longer supported by the Insteon network. I could not figure out why it did not work and after speaking to Insteon Customer service, the told me that this item will not work and will need to be shipped back to them for replacement."}
{"Author": "parisa", "Date": "on March 14, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Time to migrate away from X10", "Text": "I've been an X10 household for decades with lots of frustrations. Everything runs well for a year or more then suddenly plug in units don't respond. Recently, I don't know what happened in my house or nearby, but the X10 system is getting almost completely unreliable. So I decided to go for the Insteon starter kit. All worked well setting up on my iphone. The app is a tiny bit challenging but I'll get used to it. I was sad that you need Windows 10 operating on a PC for the app to work on a PC. And the app does not work on my kindle. Does not find the hub. Hoping that Insteon gets that fixed. But.....based on only a few days of testing I have reliability back! Goodbye X10. Actually I'll continue to use X10 here and there. And I'm waiting on my Amazon Echo \"Dot\" for lighting control (among other things). Even found my old iphone 4 works with the app so will keep that around for light control. I think I will miss not having table top control units like X10 had and I know Insteon has something that will act like a table top control unit but I'm going to force myself to use the phone app and Echo."}
{"Author": "FPK", "Date": "on March 10, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "Piece of cake to install."}
{"Author": "Roger Cash", "Date": "on March 8, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "A real bargain", "Text": "I already have Insteon installed in my house and I'm now setting up my daughters house. I bought two of these starter kits as it was cheaper than buying the extra plug in modules separately and I now have a spare hub. This particular hub plays well with the Amaxon Echo so the house is now voice controlled along with the scheduled Insteon app."}
{"Author": "superdeeduper", "Date": "on March 8, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "insteon is almost worthless. works about 75% of the ...", "Text": "insteon is almost worthless. works about 75% of the time. is not backward compatible with x10 as they say it is. my x10 stuff works about 88% of the time making it more reliable than insteon. very frustrating."}
{"Author": "Scott Laliberte", "Date": "on March 7, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Super Easy to set up and use", "Text": "Super Easy to set up and use! Connect it to my Amazon Echo and it works great. Just name your devices specific names so that Echo can distinguish between them."}
{"Author": "BritVic", "Date": "on March 6, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "Excellent"}
{"Author": "Michael Blackstone", "Date": "on March 4, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Awesome Product.", "Text": "Awesome product. Quick and easy set up. Works well. Very stable."}
{"Author": "Brad Bishop", "Date": "on March 3, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "... is my third Insteon hub (all different models) and like the others", "Text": "This is my third Insteon hub (all different models) and like the others, it is a real piece of crap. I can't believe I fell for their marketing promises again. Clumsy setup, poor documentation, unbelievably poorly designed software and interfaces. The worst part however, is that if (and that's a big \"if\") you get some of it working, you an bet it will mysteriously stop working at some point for no apparent reason. Press the button for the dining room light--will it light? Who knows! It's like Vegas only you're guaranteed to lose. I will never again purchase an Insteon product. Ever."}
{"Author": "PierreLab", "Date": "on March 3, 2016", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Great to talk to Echo, that's it", "Text": "Our house is powered by Insteon since 10+ years, we run HCA software and we are quite happy with it. Unfortunately Echo only supports the Hub so I bought a Hub so we can nicely ask Alexa to turn lights on and off - this works well.\n\nThe hub is not easy to setup, you have to go through ALL switches, modules, outlet to set them up in the Hub, no network discovery. To create scenes with existing devices, you need to go back to all devices you ant to include in the scene! We have some 40+ devices. Schedule are not really good for example you want to lit the patio lights an hour before sunrise, you can't. The only options are sunrise or a set time.\n\nGood bridge for Echo and that's it."}
{"Author": "jim", "Date": "on March 1, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "One Star", "Text": "gift I don't know"}
{"Author": "Tri", "Date": "on February 29, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "Love it"}
{"Author": "Camilo Solano", "Date": "on February 22, 2016", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Three Stars", "Text": "Where'ste some devices can't connect even they're close to the hub"}
{"Author": "Robert R. Page", "Date": "on February 20, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Good smaller hub.", "Text": "I connected this item with my newly purchased Amazon Echo, and am very happy. I already had the previous hub, and have installed over 20 other insteon devices. The most difficult part was linking all my devices to the new hub. What I did was in the old hub, go to [Devices], [Edit Devices], select device, scroll down and find the Insteon ID (XX.XX.XX) for each device, and enter that number when asked to add additional device to the new hub. After a couple of button presses, the hub and Alexa work well together. Alexa cannot operate the Nest thermostat. This is the only hub that will work with Alexa, but will not work with Siri. you can run both hubs at the same time, but you will need to populate each hub separately, you can not copy and paste, or import the data. I found that keeping the two hubs separated by several inches helped to improve responsiveness. Unfortunately you still cannot set up timers, or use IFTTT with this hub."}
{"Author": "Mr songui", "Date": "on February 18, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "Very effective .. Just this hub don't work with x10 devices\ud83d\ude21\ud83d\ude21"}
{"Author": "E. Potter", "Date": "on February 16, 2016", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Not so bad, but dishonest support claims", "Text": "So far, I don't have many devices - only smoke detectors, using the smoke bridge. In my small setup, things work ok from the bridge perspective. However - a significant factor in selecting the Insteon line over competing ones was their claimed support for Windows phones, which turns out to not be true. Hence 2 stars."}
{"Author": "jkenn", "Date": "on February 15, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Good start but needs work!", "Text": "Not easy to set up and use. Always loosing its link with Amazon Echo"}
{"Author": "J. Palmeri", "Date": "on February 9, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Setup was quick and easy and by using this version of the Hub you ...", "Text": "Purchased this to start my home automation project. Setup was quick and easy and by using this version of the Hub you can control your devices by voice using the Amazon Echo, integration was simple, and also from the Inteon app on your smart phone. This version of the Hub will not work with the Apple HomeKit so you can't control your devices with Siri but with interacting with the Echo seems easier since it's always listening and you don't have to worry about having your phone with you at all times."}
{"Author": "Pilchard", "Date": "on February 9, 2016", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "My review of the Smarthome Insteon Hub has some good news and some bad", "Text": "This is a good news, bad news product. It may be 5 stars if you fit what it can do, or 1 star if you can't. The Insteon Hub 2 as depicted is the newer Insteon hub model, the older model had a small web server. There seems no easy way to access any local web server feature on this device. It connects via Ethernet cable to my local network. There are apps to support this on Microsoft Windows 8 and 10 (in the app store), Apple OS and Google Android operating systems. My personal experience is with Android and Windows 10, for me there is no Apple device in my home.\n\nThe app presents pre-defined icons fitted on a graphical screen. Words to describe and or label devices. Adding a device to the Insteon hub is easy, just enter the type of device, and decide if you want to connect to it by ID or by pushing a button on the device to activate. Either way adding devices is easy. It's up to you to create your home name, room names, scene names, and device names.\n\nFor me it was easiest to start with my home, just give it a name like home and it's good. Similarly rooms are more or less free style. They get alphabetized in a folder called rooms. Scenes are also easily named, but usually require a device.\n\nDevice control takes time, even if you are using a cell phone attached to your local Wi-Fi. Control also works over Internet (you can be away from home and use cellular data to control devices in your home).\n\nThere is an Insteon Hub app in the Microsoft Windows 8 and 10 app store (for desktop / laptop users). It is very similar to the Android app, though it seems a bit bugged as I write this review. First there is an error message on launch that push notifications couldn't be established. This is fine, but it comes up as a notification on each launch. It would be nice to not have it.\n\nRegarding support, it's not good. My Fanlinc devices (which control overhead fans) work well on the Android app, but on the Windows 10 app version only light is available. The Insteon Hub interface for Alexa seems unable to operate anything but a fan light when using a Fanlinc module. This makes it impossible to control the fan blades (paddles?). Customer service isn't of much help.They wanted to remotely access my computer, when denied, their suggestion was to uninstall and reinstall the Windows app (didn't work).\n\nIntegration with the Amazon Echo is also a bit messed up. Echo reads devices, but not scenes. The result is she doesn't understand that a room may have a number of lights, but a scene may set different groups of lights. This can be overcome by duplicating the scene into the Echo app on a smart phone and adding something called a group. A group is like a scene, but is stored on the Amazon Echo, and will drive each device in the scene from the Echo. There is no way to automatically relate Amazon Echo Groups with Smarthome Insteon Hub scenes. This is a failure of Amazon and Smarthome to get along, my guess is this won't be resolved. Smarthome is busy with the recently launched Hub Pro which only works with Apple products.\n\nThere is an older version of software to control an Insteon network, it seems designed for Windows 7 and is text centric (not icon centric). This version of the Insteon Hub software does work under Windows 10, though device support is an issue. Smarthome has released support for newer devices, but it isn't automatically updated as the Windows 7 app seems no longer supported. After determining where the update files were to support my Fanlinc, I restarted the app and have had no issue controlling fanlinc devices from this app. Though the app won't sync with the Insteon Hub, so you'll have to reproduce everything. Tech support from Smarthome indicated the Microsoft app store was the only Insteon Hub control product for Windows 8 and 10, that the Windows 7 Houselinc 2 would not run under Windows 10. This is not true. Of the few calls made to Smarthome, never was any good advice offered or a solution found to any issue. The Windows 10 app does have one feature the Windows 7 lacks, the Smarthome Windows app 10 controls my microphone.\n\nCurrently there are 31 Insteon devices on my network, and 3 X10 devices. X10 support isn't very good on the newer interfaces and it is going, but there seems unnecessary difficulty getting X10 to work well. Others have reported very small limits to the number of Insteon devices, so far, my 31 devices all work and are controlled by the local Insteon Hub without issue.\n\nThe good news / bad news is as follows, if you use an Android App, good news, you'll like the Insteon Hub, if you use Windows 7, you may not like it much as you'll need to fiddle with device set up and synchronization for changes made by other apps doesn't work. If you use Windows 8 or 10 and install the Smart Hub app from the Microsoft Store, well it will work, but has some gliches, like broken fanlinc support or nuisance notifications that reflect a broken signaling interface that can't be turned off.\n\nFor me at this time, the Insteon Hub is a crossover device. Eventually I'll be using Homeseer. I wish Smarthome was working better to help with the interfaces on Windows. For basic scene management this is a decent device, for larger homes, or more complex situations (with triggers and what not) a more advanced controller is necessary.\n\nThe Insteon Hub does not support triggers or events. There is limited support for a timer (a scene or device can be turned off at a specific time or sunrise / sunset). However only one device or scene can use the same time (this means if want multiple devices turned on at sunset a scene will have to be built as only one sunset timer is permitted). Interaction with the Amazon Echo is not always accurate, often the Echo will report it turned on or off a device, but the device failed to perform the function. The supposed Insteon feedback to be certain a signal gets to its destination fails in this pairing. It isn't clear to me if the failure is at Amazon or Smarthome, but a highly likely guess is Smarthome.\n\nRecently at a hacker conference, the Insteon network was hacked using wireless. Apparently there is some use of xor and a crc to try and prevent seeing clear signals, but this is easily defeated. A $60 Raspberry Pi like device with 915Mhz capable wireless interface can spy on and control an Insteon network, with good antennas at some distance. The hackers indicated Insteon has a command to turn off RF for all it's devices, but only companies that sign a non-disclosure agreement have access to this.\n\nThus our Insteon networks are not secure, and are quite hackable. We may use these for lights and what not, but maybe not for door locks.\n\nSigh."}
{"Author": "Jerry from Florida", "Date": "on February 7, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Invest in the ISY-999 instead - this device is a waste of your time and money", "Text": "This is a terrible product and I would avoid purchasing if possible.\n\nOur house has been automated using Insteon technology for close to 10 years. We had been using Universal Devices ISY-99 which was end of life and finally broke down. The Insteon hub looked like a great value compared to replacing it with an ISY-999 so we thought we would give it a try. The initial setup to register the Hub to the iPhone app worked well but the experience was terrible after that. For example, we turn on our outside lights at sunset and sundown and turn on a couple lights in the house at sunset. It took 15 minutes to setup the sunset/sunrise \"scene\" and then we learned that you can't have two scene's use the same time trigger. It took 40 minutes to undo the sunset/sunrise scene, 30 minutes to do a sunset scene and 20 minutes to create a sunrise scene.\n\nThe biggest disappoint was the iPhone app. It takes two minutes to initialize and the information is useless. In addition, it didn't support the Insteon lawn sprinkler device, didn't understand the garage door package they sell and looks like it was put together by a kindergarten class during recess.\n\nI recommend you invest in the Universal Devices ISY-999 which is much easier to use, works inside or outside your home, and has great options to creating complex activities in seconds, and understand the wide range of Insteon devices you can add to your home."}
{"Author": "Brian", "Date": "on February 6, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Great now that it is working.", "Text": "Had some troubles at first, but now am controlling my garage, porch lights, and leak sensor. The house of the future is here and I love it! I initially had difficult with schedules of my lights, but that was due to the hub not being on the right time. Had to reset and that seemed to fix it. Now working great!"}
{"Author": "Timothy J. McDermott", "Date": "on February 6, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "You can do much better...", "Text": "Although I'm a big fan of Insteon in general, the Hub is real disappointment. Compounding its inherent design flaws is its unreliability and bugginess. If you are looking for a well designed and stable automation hub for Insteon, look no further than Universal Devices ISY94 series. Although somewhat more complicated than Insteon's version, it isn't hampered by its design limitations or erratic behavior. For example, one is not inexplicably limited to having only one device scheduled for dusk and dawn operation. As an added bonus, the ISY devices can be upgraded to support Z-Wave and Zigbee wireless protocols in addition to IP communication, providing for near \"Universal\" interoperability in environments containing any of these device types. This is of particular importance for those wishing to include devices such as locksets which do not have an Insteon equivalent. UDI's technical support, while not instantaneous, is exceptional. Not only do they know their product inside and out, the also know Insteon products as well. Check them out."}
{"Author": "Joseph P. Devincentis", "Date": "on February 6, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Works great, range seems a bit limited", "Text": "Works great, range seems a bit limited, but a range expander makes everything fine. Toughest part was realizing that you need this to go with the 2634-222. But, works reliably, the iphone app for controlling the devices is super easy to use, works great (iphone 4s)."}
{"Author": "Timothy H. Clark", "Date": "on February 1, 2016", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Expensive", "Text": "Expected this to work with my existing X10 products. So far, I haven't found a way to make it work with them. New Insteon products are MUCH more expensive than X10 products."}
{"Author": "Zeke Evaro", "Date": "on January 31, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Interfaces nicely with Logitech remote.", "Text": "Works great. I used this to interface with my Logitech Harmony Elite Remote. Now I'm controlling multiple things in my home with one remote."}
{"Author": "kimray", "Date": "on January 30, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "After years of service my other controller hub went out ...", "Text": "After years of service my other controller hub went out. This is the newer, smaller version and it works perfectly."}
{"Author": "TimV", "Date": "on January 29, 2016", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Needs support for SmartThings", "Text": "Works fantastic with my Amazon Echo (Alexa), allowing the family to turn both Insteon and Phillips Hue lights on and off. But I REALLY want to control my existing Insteon devices (I have about a dozen) via SmartThings. Other than this purchase to get Amazon Echo support, I have stopped buying any more Insteon devices until there is proper integration with SmartThings."}
{"Author": "Amazon Customer", "Date": "on January 27, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Got a few of their switches which were very easy to install", "Text": "Purchased this kit for controlling a few lamps but quickly caught the fever for adding more control to my house. At first the wife was skeptical, but once I loaded the App on her IPhone and started to use it, she began to ask what other connected products can we purchase. Got a few of their switches which were very easy to install. Now she's dimming lights left and right and loves setting mood lighting at night - where previously she'd spend 10min walking around the house after sunset, she hits a scene button and its done in an instant."}
{"Author": "Eric M. Mays", "Date": "on January 25, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "This hub allows for easy integration and simple scene and timing control", "Text": "I have used Insteon products in the past. This hub allows for easy integration and simple scene and timing control."}
{"Author": "azezal", "Date": "on January 24, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "One Star", "Text": "It does not work at all, neither does the smartphone app."}
{"Author": "ANTHONY FIORENTINO", "Date": "on January 24, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "Very easy to link to my echo"}
{"Author": "S. Palermo", "Date": "on January 23, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Probably good for a novice. Waste for me.", "Text": "I bought this solely to be able to turn lights on and off with my Echo. The hub requires every device be added manually via smartphone. I already have a network of nearly 100 devices on an ISY994i. There was no way I was going to add every one of them in manually. Wasted $80 on this thing because now the Echo integrates with the ISY directly."}
{"Author": "Aaron", "Date": "on January 20, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Four Stars", "Text": "So far it's great."}
{"Author": "Ken F.", "Date": "on January 20, 2016", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Disappointed.", "Text": "Bought it to automatically turn lights off and on based on time of day. I cannot get this function to work at all."}
{"Author": "Steve", "Date": "on January 17, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Overpriced Hacker CRAP!", "Text": "Shame on me. I am such an idiot. Smarhome/Insteon products used to work. They were totally kludgey, but they worked. Within the last 5 years, they have just become hacker junk. I have spent nearly $5000 with Smarthome. I replaced every single device that was more than 2 years old. I have a VERY SIMPLE setup. Exterior and Christmas lights only. Nothing else. I have phase coupler. I have the repeaters. I have 10 dual band devices. I bought the new hub pro. What is \"Professional\" about a product that can't even find a single device in my house. When I first installed the app, there was an option to add devices by ID, now the option is gone and all it does is just say \"Searching\". Come on. You charge $1,000 to get even a simple setup and it won't even work??! This is totally BS. I am going to go to an open source platform like Zigbee...at least I will have some control over it."}
{"Author": "USERBOSCO", "Date": "on January 16, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Changed from 2 to 4 stars - System works well and support did, too", "Text": " Revised 1/19/16\n\nPros: Easy set up, easy configuration (except time), works w/ Echo\nCons: Relatively weak signal (meaning, don't hide the hub in a credenza or closet, etc....)\n\nOkay, I just had a customer service experience 180 degrees from the first. Tech support was immediate and right on the money. I only have three (3) devices (all wall switches, 1 dimmer) and they are sync'ed with Echo. Grouped outdoor lights are on timer and now work as expected thanks to time adjustment. Echo/Alexa work perfectly with the devices."}
{"Author": "D215", "Date": "on January 16, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Could not connect...", "Text": "Admittedly I did buy an open box, every outlet and switch in my house is insteon controlled with Indigo, I just bought a Harmony Elite remote and wanted to control my living room lights with the remote and Indigo does not work with Elite. I plugged in the hub the status light was red and when I tried to set it up with the app it said that the device was not connected to the internet after several tries I reset the network settings. The first time I tried the unit beeped 6 times (it was supposed to beep three). I tried again and it beeped three times scanned the code STILL not connected to the internet. I tried to add the device manually, no hub detected so I upgraded the firmware. After the firmware update was complete I had a green status light YAY I though but sadly it could not connect to the internet, Tried the shipped ethernet and two others and still no internet? Its going back, might be different with a brand new unit, I don't know that I will bother though"}
{"Author": "Mike", "Date": "on January 13, 2016", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Good home automation platform.", "Text": "Really like the Insteon platform, added light controsl, HD camera, and water leak sensors. Can control my lights from my iPhone, Apple watch and with Alexa voice commands on the Amazon Echo. Get camera feeds on my browser, iPhone, and watch get water leak alerts via push notifications on my iPhone. Will add more device controls in the future."}
{"Author": "WBoweIII", "Date": "on January 13, 2016", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Frustrating and weak - If you own a Harmony Hub it really helps", "Text": "The Insteon hub is weak at best. The App for Windows is buggy and lacks features. It does not seem to get updated often and is ignored. I purchased this hub in the first few weeks it came out (over a year ago) as of today the web interface still says Beta and doesn't do much. The Android app is clumsy and convoluted and most importantly it is not designed for a tablet and will not rotate to landscape mode which makes using it on a tablet terrible.\n\nIf the hub is offline you cannot login to any app or the web page to administer anything. My hub died a little after 1 year and I had to get it replaced. There is no apparent way for you to replace your own hub without calling and sitting on hold for 40+ minutes. Then they have to delete your account and cannot just re-assign your hub to that account. You are better off just using a new email address and setting everything up again.\n\nI have used insteon for years but this product just makes me wish I had gone Z-Wave... There is no advanced features and overall it is just really hard to use.\n\nOn the bright side... The Logitech Harmony Hub has really nice integration with the insteon hub. This allows you to use your insteon devices from the Logitech remote or app. This integration is the only reason this device gets 2 stars. The logitech app is WAY better and hides some the utter lack of features.\n\nI have not tried Insteon Cameras but I can only imagine how horrible it would be to use this app on a tablet. The resolution of the camera would be squished up or you would have to rotate it one way to view and the other to use...(this is speculation)\n\nI am also REALLY bothered by Insteons hub apparent strategy. They made a 2nd Hub Pro that only works with Apple and I have heard they are making another hub that is \"Internet of Things\" compatible instead of making one nice hub that works across all platforms. There seems to be a real lack of consistent effort and strategy on insteons part.\n\nTo sum up this review - this hub is FRUSTRATING\n\nAs I write this review I have just had my 3rd Dimmer in 12 months go south so I have to call Insteon (Smarthome) again.\n\nOn the positive side - Once you finally get to someone the support people are VERY helpful and SUPER willing to replace and/or support the product. Kudos to whomever runs that support department because I have ALWAYS had a great customer service experience with them."}
{"Author": "Starwander", "Date": "on January 10, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Terrible product and would avoid like the plaque", "Text": "Purchased this product and downloaded the installation app. Went through the process and hub was not detected. Watched their online installation instructions and their video actually is incorrect as it asks you to scan the bottom of the device as part of the start-up process; however the app never takes you through this step! Searched their online technical assistance and did all the steps without resolution of the problem. Even went to various forums for advice and everything I tried still did not work. Terrible product and would avoid like the plaque, at least from my experience. They need to get their act together and make a product that is easier to install."}
{"Author": "John B.", "Date": "on January 6, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "I installed them yesterday and couldn't be happier. The installation", "Text": "After the frustration of trying to get a WeMo light switch and wall plug to work and failing miserably, I returned the WeMo products to Amazon and purchased the Insteon hub, light switch and wall plug. I installed them yesterday and couldn't be happier. The installation, setup and configuration was straightforward and simple. No connectivity issues whatsoever. Linking them to my Amazon Echo was a walk in the park. Since the Insteon app knows where the hub is physically located in the world, it is able to recognize time zones, daylight savings time and the sunrise and sunset on a particular day. Consequently, setting up a scene that turns the lights on and off at sunset and sunrise was also very easy. In summary, the products work as advertised and I would definitely recommend them.\n\nOne note of caution, if you want to link an Insteon hub to your Amazon Echo you must purchase this specific model of the hub as it is the only one currently supported by Amazon Echo."}
{"Author": "West of Side", "Date": "on January 3, 2016", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Insteon has the absolute worst tech support you will ever come across", "Text": "Insteon has the absolute worst tech support you will ever come across. I am very technical and use other home automation products like CastleOS and mFi with no issues at all. For some reason my Insteon Hub won't work right, it won't update it's firmware at 2 a.m. like it is supposed, and the mobile app won't recognize the device.\n\nYou would think their tech support would be ready and willing to help a customer, WRONG. This is how it goes:\n\n- Submit support request on their website, it says they will get back you in 24-48 hours.\n- Wait a week, nothing, so submit another one.\n- Wait a week, nothing again, so submit another one.\n- Repeat two more times....\n- Finally get a response from one of my requests, but it's jut basic questions like it is connected to wifi....duh\n- Reply to their response.......then wait a few more weeks...\n\nDon't bother with these products."}
{"Author": "S. Moon", "Date": "on January 3, 2016", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "GREAT with Amazon Echo!", "Text": "Updated an older hub to take advantage of Amazon Echo integration. Glad I did! It's a lot of fun to be able to have Alexa turn lights on and off (our house has an extensive Insteon installation) on command. And a lot more convenient when your hands are full. Highly recommended if you already have the necessary infrastructure for a smart home.\n\nThe only issue I've found is that in rooms with a great many three-way circuits (our Rec Room has three), Alexa has trouble distinguishing which device to control. The hub could be better integrated if the Amazon Echo was also able to activate Insteon scenes, which can be scripted to control multiple devices."}
{"Author": "C. Hodrick", "Date": "on December 31, 2015", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "I received the item in a timely manner. Not happy to see that this week it is 28.00 less! Easy to set up.", "Text": "Could be easier"}
{"Author": "Andrew", "Date": "on December 31, 2015", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Great automation", "Text": "I have insteon controlling my theater and other devices. Pretty awesome stuff!"}
{"Author": "Jay Corry", "Date": "on December 30, 2015", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Fine when it works", "Text": "Can't log into my account....been on hold with customer service for over an hour.\n\nFine when it works. If I new what I know now, I would have went with z-wave and the Samsung hub instead."}
{"Author": "cb3431", "Date": "on December 28, 2015", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Beware!!!", "Text": "It does not work with daylight savings time - schedules stop working and the time does not update. I'm on my third hub. Will it be number 4 after the next daylight savings time change? There has been no update to the software so I'm thinking another replacement is in my future. I only wish I knew before the return window expired.\n\nCons:\n-Very slow to login\n-Very slow to interact with any device\n-Functionality depends on the app platform\n-Apps are not updated to support advertised functionality\n-Tech support is not helpful\n\nPros:\nHonestly can't think of a single one."}
{"Author": "C Wiz", "Date": "on December 23, 2015", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Easy connection, has been working", "Text": "Used with Dual band 240V controller. Easy connection, has been working well"}
{"Author": "lewis goldstein", "Date": "on December 20, 2015", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "The Insteon systems has worked the best. I tried for a while with all the ...", "Text": "I have been trying to get a home automation system working for a while.\nThe Insteon systems has worked the best.\nI tried for a while with all the Z-wave ones that are out there, but they were difficult to get paired with the system.\nThe Insteon in almost mindless\u2026 that being said Im pretty good with tech stuff and still the Zwave one's (which there are several) the pairing was a nightmare.\nHad the insteon up and running in minutes."}
{"Author": "J. C. Thorne", "Date": "on December 20, 2015", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Just a pretty poor half baked product", "Text": "Just a pretty poor half baked product. It cannot find devices on your network, you have to manually link each one by pressing its link button. If you try to enter the device ID it just never finds them. The ONLY reason I don't return this is its Echo integration. I'll link a few devices for Alexa to control and not bother trying to do anything else with it. Its no ISY thats for sure. I've gotten used to beta grade half baked product releases from SmartHome over the years but this is among the worst."}
{"Author": "Shawn-Bob", "Date": "on December 18, 2015", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "Handy stuff."}
{"Author": "Frank Chao", "Date": "on December 18, 2015", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "I bought a set of solution including HUB, Thermostat ...", "Text": "I bought a set of solution including HUB, Thermostat, motion sense, on/off controller, door module, water leaking module. They are not working, very hard to associate with the HUB, only one unit can associate to the HUB. Very hard to use, don't buy it."}
{"Author": "EZ writer", "Date": "on December 18, 2015", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Bought this hub from Amazon Warehouse sales (which means it ...", "Text": "Bought this hub from Amazon Warehouse sales (which means it was a return). Did not work. Turned out previous owner had set up an account for it with Insteon and this blocked me from registering it. Finally got that sorted, but it still wouldn't work. An hour on the phone with tech support and the verdict was Defective. Returned to Amazon - no problem there.\nIn short, I won't buy another unit from Warehouse Deals.\nSave yourself some headaches and buy the hub only as new - not a used return."}
{"Author": "Monti", "Date": "on December 15, 2015", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "Love it"}
{"Author": "M G-rod", "Date": "on December 15, 2015", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "After being in computers & technology for over 30 years ...", "Text": "After being in computers & technology for over 30 years, I expecting some compatibility is built in by default. I would need to redo thousands of dollars at $50 a switch."}
{"Author": "BuddhaP", "Date": "on December 6, 2015", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "caused what appears to be secondary network problems", "Text": "Product works sometimes and Alexa has difficulty turning the lights on, and even when she succeeds, she says there are network issues. The more serious issue is that the TWO pioneer receivers VSX822 and VSX1123 both started to develop network issues as soon as the device was plugged in, and in use. This caused me to reset the receivers network settings several times... several hours of work. Finally called customer support- but they told me that receiver problem has nothing to do with the device - which may be true, but you be the judge. After removing the Insteon device and unplugging it all my network issues with the receivers disappeared! The Insteon hub at best, worked only some of the time, so it is going back"}
{"Author": "Lawrence R. Mastropolo", "Date": "on December 4, 2015", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Alexa, turn on the Christmas tree!", "Text": "Telling Alexa to \"turn on the Christmas tree\" amazes our granddaughter. I've just started to install other switches and devices. My first hub was defective but that was my fault for purchasing a repackaged item. Amazon issued a refund with no problems and I ordered a new hub. Installation took less than 10 minutes including finding the new receptacle and adding the hub and outlet to Echo."}
{"Author": "Kurt P.", "Date": "on December 2, 2015", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "it doesn't work with HouseLinc which I use to detect and fix bad links.", "Text": "After my SmartLinc Controller 2412N died for the second time, I got one of these units. Unfortunately, it couldn't add some of my switches no matter where I moved the unit. Additionally, it doesn't work with HouseLinc which I use to detect and fix bad links."}
{"Author": "Peter Khalil", "Date": "on November 29, 2015", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "doesn't pass the mom test", "Text": "Too complicated, doesn't work with Siri / HomeKit, didn't work with multiple devices and most importantly didn't pass the mom test ... returned the next day."}
{"Author": "Adam", "Date": "on November 27, 2015", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Disappointing", "Text": "Box and mobile app are slow to respond. Leaves a lot to be desired. Faster to walk across the house to control lights then use app."}
{"Author": "Video Nut", "Date": "on November 24, 2015", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "... I have it connected with Amazon Alexa that was easy and I got it all up and working controlling ...", "Text": "Works well and replaced the other Insteon controller that connected to a PC (forget the name) I have it connected with Amazon Alexa that was easy and I got it all up and working controlling 30 switches from Alexa in one afternoon."}
{"Author": "J. bright", "Date": "on November 16, 2015", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "I am very pleased with this purchase", "Text": "I am very pleased with this purchase. It would have gotten 5 Stars but....The Range of the Insteon Hub is definitely limited (Spec says 250 feet)....Through in a few walls and it goes way down. I had to purchase the Range Extender. Now it works perfectly through out my entire house."}
{"Author": "cdburns123", "Date": "on November 16, 2015", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "it connects great and now that it works with the Echo", "Text": "Software needs some help. For example, you can set an alert, but you can't schedule the alert. Meaning, I can have a text message to my phone every time a door opens...but I can't state, only between the hours of 10pm and 5pm. So, every day I have to set it when I go to bed or leave the house...then unmark through the day. Other than that, it connects great and now that it works with the Echo, even better....although only some devices."}
{"Author": "ShopSmart", "Date": "on November 15, 2015", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "So disappointed in their product", "Text": "Spent an hour resetting, submitting, researching and can not even get the HUB to connect with APP. So disappointed in their product. Also, have begun to see first two switches that we've had for 2 years begin to fail."}
{"Author": "Kindle Customer", "Date": "on November 9, 2015", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Four Stars", "Text": "Works fine after we got help with setup"}
{"Author": "Amazon Customer", "Date": "on November 5, 2015", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Works ok BUT....", "Text": "I hooked my hub up 2 days ago, linked my LG 3 and Galaxy S5 smart phones to and all works well and as advertised to this point. I'm using the Insteon Android app version 1.8.5.\nBut the issue I'm having is with my Kindle Fire HD (3rd generation) tablet. It offers the Insteon app. which I downloaded and attempted to connect to my new hub. It will not connect to my Insteon hub, I tried a couple different attempts still will not connect. Very frustrated and hopeful Amazon or Insteon will fix this."}
{"Author": "Peter Reyes", "Date": "on November 5, 2015", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Four Stars", "Text": "Easy set-up. Works great."}
{"Author": "Kindle Customer", "Date": "on November 4, 2015", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Works well! REST API is very cool!", "Text": "So far so good. It certainly does what it says it will do. I have setup a number of devices with ease. The camera is very nice, one thing to note, it is only 2.4GHZ. I upgraded to 5GHZ and it took awhile to figure out the issue. Once setup, the clarity of picture is amazing.\n\nOne thing to look out for, if you have a device (like garage door opener / plugin) that is not RF and only powerline, then adding an outlet or switch that is both can help with connectivity issues. In my case, the device was right next to the hub, but couldn't reach it because it was powerline only and was on an electrical sub panel. By adding a light switch in the garage everything worked perfectly. It really is true what the instructions say, the more devices you add, the better Insteon works as it will use both RF and powerline to make a mesh of a network across your home.\n\nI just started working with the REST API. The web site API instructions are very good. I didn't notice at first, but they actually show working code examples in 14 languages like PHP, VB, Ruby, Java, etc. I tried Javascript first (AJAX call from a page running on Apache), but the Insteon site rejected my connection (doesn't allow calls from another domain). I am now working with a node.js based approach and it works really well. One thing that was not intuitive for me, the Production site to connect to is https://connect.insteon.com/api/v2/. It is on the API site, but not the clearest."}
{"Author": "Rishi", "Date": "on November 2, 2015", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Four Stars", "Text": "Pretty good.. but scheduler is a bit flaky"}
{"Author": "R. Hummel III", "Date": "on October 31, 2015", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Wonderful for Amazon Echo control of Insteon devices", "Text": "It's great for being able to control my lights with my Amazon Echo (5 STARS!), but lacking in programming capability that is available with the Universal Devices programmable hub for Insteon switches."}
{"Author": "maalund", "Date": "on October 31, 2015", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "Works great with Alexa"}
{"Author": "Mark Buckland", "Date": "on October 31, 2015", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Insteon works but it is ugly", "Text": "It works, just. Very slow arduous task to set scenes. You have to walk to each device just to adjust a level in a scene. Communications on the Instron network is slow. The Inteon app is a joke. Really horrible. It works but ugly."}
{"Author": "Aaron", "Date": "on October 30, 2015", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Can I rate this zero stars???", "Text": "I have been using Insteon for years, and they seem to have perfected the art of producing attractive devices that have a lifespan shorter than a glass of milk on a summer day.\nDay 1: installed the hub. It sort-of worked\nDay 2: Discovered that when my mobile phone connected to a different wifi network I had to restart the phone in order to see the hub again. Well, that's just stupid.\nDay 3. Hub died. No longer connects. Just a red light on and no amount of factory resets make it work It also smells like burnt plastic.\nDay 4. Contacted support via phone. No answer, no returned call\nDay 5. Attempted to contact support via their web page and was greeted with \"Unable to send form. Please try again later.\" Tried again later. Multiple times. No luck.\nDay 5, evening: wrote this review, in disgust.\n\nSo, in all, no I CANNOT recommend this product. In all, I can not recommend ANY Insteon product. Save your money.Buy a different brand home automation system. I'm going to."}
{"Author": "Amazon Customer", "Date": "on October 29, 2015", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Works as Advertised", "Text": "I bought the Insteon hub 2245-222 a little over two weeks ago. It came as part of a startup package that was sold at Costco. Upon first connecting it, the hub updated itself to the latest software version (you will need a smartphone - I have an iPhone 6S). Then I place the two lamp modules were I wanted them and went through the discover protocol and they connected just like that. Couldn't have been easier. Since that went so well, I ordered an Insteon LED light for my outdoor garage light fixture. The bulb came and worked as advertised. Haven't had any issues with any of the components. I have had a X-10 system for many years (seems like at least 20 years), so am used to how that system functions and bought Insteon to start phasing our my many X-10 devices.\n\nMy biggest complaint is that multiple scenes can't use any of the same times used in another scene (or device). For instance, I have my main floor indoor lights come on at sunset and go off at 11 PM (yes I can get over not having the flexibility of X-10 plus and minus sunset times). But I want to have my garage outdoor light come on at sunset also and go off at sunrise. But the system won't let me do that since sunset has already been used in another scene. This is a mind boggling shortcoming that needs to get fixed. I had to just pick a time for the outdoor light to come on and will have to adjust that time manually as the seasons change.\n\nHave read many of the reviews on this site and haven't had any of the problems or failures mentioned in some reviews. I am pleased and will keep adding incrementally to the system.INSTEON 2245-222 Central Controller Hub"}
{"Author": "Echo Customer", "Date": "on October 27, 2015", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Very easy to set up and I am very pleased", "Text": "The Insteon hub and water sensors do exactly what I wanted them to do. Very easy to set up and I am very pleased.\nUpdate 11-28-2015\nI am now using IFTTT and if a leak is detected my cell phone will ring to alert me of the leak"}
{"Author": "Sergio V.", "Date": "on October 22, 2015", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "Perfect thanks"}
{"Author": "Anthony Davis", "Date": "on October 21, 2015", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "The Last Straw for Insteon", "Text": "I have been an Insteon user from the start, and have about 30 devices in the house. This has been a downhill spiral, and every time a new method of controlling them comes out, I have this irrational optimism that this time Smarthome will have figured it out.\n\nNope.\n\nThis hub is the latest in a series of increasingly serious disappointments. It claims to be Insteon compatible, but it turns out that it is only compatible with a secret list of Insteon devices. Some of my devices are on the list, some aren't. You might wish to call technical support for clarification or help, but be prepared for 1.5 hours of waiting on hold to get through.\n\nThe central problem with this device is that even if everything worked as the app says it should (and it flat out does not), it still is terrible. You can set a scene up, but if anything goes wrong during the setup, you're left with a huge mess. The individual Insteon devices each keep a database of what they're supposed to do, and the links in each database have to be synchronized with the other devices (controllers and responders) for everything to work well. Apparently nobody told the Smarthome software designers this, as they don't have any way to deal with broken links, which happen for lots of real-world reasons, including that they just have flaky programming from this flaky hub.\n\nIf you have more than two devices or two scenes, this spirals completely out of control. Quickly nothing responds correctly and you're running around the house poking all the light switches *for hours* doing this \"manual linking\" thing that should not be required in the first place.\n\nSmarthome has demonstrated repeatedly that they are perfectly happy leaving their customers high and dry without firmware updates or support for things we've wired into our houses.\n\nAs a pretty good expert on Insteon, I say STAY AWAY!"}
{"Author": "Shawn McMillan", "Date": "on October 20, 2015", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "Great"}
{"Author": "T. R. Akin", "Date": "on October 20, 2015", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Great Product for home Automation", "Text": "As opposed to some negative reviews, I found this hub to be easy to work with once I figured out how to get my 8 Insteon Link switches to get found. It identified my Nest Thermostat easily. I have set up several Scenes easily. I look forward to buying other Insteon products as well. Oh and may I add that my Amazon Echo easily joined with the Insteon Hub and recognized everything that connected to it."}
{"Author": "jselmo", "Date": "on October 18, 2015", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Welcome to home automation.", "Text": "I was skeptical about the technology but have to admit I was surprised at how well this works. Set up was extremely easy. The only issue I have is the app could stand some improvement as it is really not user friendly. That is an app issue and not the product itself. The product works flawlessly and compliments my Amazon Echo. Both products communicate well with one another."}
{"Author": "Deb", "Date": "on October 16, 2015", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "We monitor our home remotely with our phones", "Text": "We love the INSTEON system and use the cameras to monitor our home remotely with our phones. It is so easy to peek into our home and especially handy when the alarms are tripped and we need to access the situation from afar. It is also a comfort to know I we can keep an eye on our elderly pet when we are from home. The system was a bit tricky to get integrated with our computer server and cell phones. However, the INSTEON representative at the customer service line was patient and walked us through the set up!"}
{"Author": "J. Reihsen", "Date": "on October 14, 2015", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Insteon Hub Products are a Terrible Mess", "Text": "Be careful, this device doesn't support Apple Homekit. I have the 2242-222 which is not compatible with my Harmony remote, Amazon Alexa or Apple Homekit. Very dissapointing indeed! This an unmitigated disaster.\n\nUpon purchase, there is no way to tell that there is a hodgepodge of Insteon hub products with various (in)compatibilities. The 2242-222 does not connect with any non-Insteon software/devices. The Hub Pro (2243-222) enables Apple Homekit but not Harmony, the 2245-222 enables Harmony devices and Alexa, but not Homekit.\n\nWhat a mess! They have apparently made their products with no regard to future upgrades. I have learned my lesson about Insteon. No more!"}
{"Author": "Bob Lasky", "Date": "on October 10, 2015", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Great product and amazing support", "Text": "Their products are great and their tech support is amazing. They are in America and they talk to you... not at you."}
{"Author": "G. Crawford", "Date": "on October 5, 2015", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "Works great."}
{"Author": "Rudy Moore", "Date": "on October 5, 2015", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "The web interface looked poor and behaved badly - I tried adding a device ...", "Text": "I just returned this 2245-222.\n\nMy primary objection is that it's going backwards in features. The hub will not act as a modem. It does not support X10. It does not have support for HouseLinc and other software products that Smarthome has put out previously.\n\nIn addition it's \"cloud based\" which means that a network connection must be available for it to work. The web interface looked poor and behaved badly - I tried adding a device by ID number (since it's part of a MicroLinc which is installed inside a lamp and there is no access to the 'set' button). The device was communicated with and added, but uncontrollable.\n\nLooks like I have to find a new way to program my Insteon switches... or get rid of them altogether. No wonder Home Automation has been promised since the 70s and never successfully delivered."}
{"Author": "David Roehr", "Date": "on October 4, 2015", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "-The whole system actually works pretty well. I can see the status of my ...", "Text": "This review is based on bringing up a new Insteon system install to replace/update an old X10 system using the now unsupported Smarthome USB 1132CU PowerLinc controller.\nI am using the android app as the Ux method. Primary use is security lighting and home status monitoring.\n\nPluses:\n-The hardware is well made, looks plenty solid.\n-The whole system actually works pretty well. I can see the status of my various lights and sensors, and (after I removed a signal booster) the older X10 receiver modules still work.\nA leak or a door opening can send an alert in a second or so, and can also send an email message.\n-Adding new modules is fairly painless, select it from the app add device screen, a button press on the module, a few beeps from the hub and you're done!\n\nMinuses:\n- The software is still pretty primitive. The UX in general feels like as Beta 1 version (ie only the minimum must have main features implemented) not a shipping product.\n1) Only one schedule can be made with dusk dawn, and no random option to simulate \"human activity.\n2) X10 modules can't be part of any scenes\n3) There's no conditionals, like \"If the front door is opened between 8PM and 6 AM, send an alert\".\n4) The applet drops the connection when I go offsite and won't reconnect when I return, I have to exit and restart the applet.\n5) I expected to be able to easily manage controllers, responders, and their links. It appears you can only manage these by scenes and it doesn't seem to import existing links.\n6) I also expected to be able to manage mapping controllers to older X10 modules, this feature seems to be entirely missing.\n\nSince the minuses appear to be all software issues, hopefully the Insteon team will be addressing them via a software update soon."}
{"Author": "M. Cruzan", "Date": "on October 3, 2015", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Updated: The Insteon Hub does not work with Echo/Alexa", "Text": "Whether this device will work right off will depend on what you use to control it with. So far I have had the best luck using the app for Android. It seems to be updated with more features and has functioned nearly flawlessly. I suspect the IOS app is similar but I have not tried it. At the time I am writing this review the desktop Windows app does not work well at all and it is not updated. The Windows phone app works fine, but does not have all the features that the android apps has. I expect they will get around to updating the windows apps eventually.\n\nBasic functions for controlling dimmer switches works fine from all the apps I have tried. Finding and linking devices works well from the Android and Windows phone apps, but not from the desktop. Scenes only seem to work from the Android app. Scene assignments include adding functions to Insteon keypads. This works fine from the Android app.\n\nOnce the hub is set up the Amazon Echo - Alexa - will integrate with it quickly and easily. Alexa can control physical devices but she cannot currently control scenes, so that means anything controlled by individual keypad buttons. The Alexa app does have the ability to assign devices to groups, but this is limited to the devices she can recognize. Depending on how complete your home automation system is, this can be very limiting. For example, I can tell Alexa to turn on a light or a set of lights, but she cannot control my AV system (at present). The group feature also does not have the flexibility of control over ramp levels and speeds the way that Insteon scenes do. Currently the Insteon Hub is not very good about taking advantage of all the features that Insteon devices offer.\n\nJust in the last few days the Android App was upgraded to add and control X10 devices. This is a power line protocol that dates back to the 1950's and is still widely used. Many Insteon devices are compatible with X10 so this addition really expands the flexibility of the hub. Currently Alexa is not able to control X10 devices - she can discover them, but then there is an message saying that she cannot control them.\n\nI'm giving this hub four stars because it has a long ways to go to become fully functional, but it is also clear that they are actively working to update the apps and add features. I should also mention that the schedule programming in this hub is very limited - on/off at certain times of day and that is all. If you want full program flexibility there are much better options out there. I have had a lot of luck with the JDS HomeRunner RBI. The main reason to get this hub is to allow control over your automation system using the Amazon Echo.\n\nUpdate March 2016: Not integrated with the Amszon Echo. The Echo developers have done only the minimum effort here - it will control individual devices, but it will not activate scenes (groups within the Insteon hub). For example, this makes all the Insteon keypad devices worthless - Alexa cannot do anything with all those buttons. After many complaints over many months they keep saying this is \"high priority\" but we have waited a very long time. I am really fed up."}
{"Author": "Felipe Soares Fernandes", "Date": "on October 2, 2015", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Not ready for prime time...bummer", "Text": "I have been using Insteon for almost two years now and I absolutely love it. The app needed some work but things just worked together once I got it setup. Even my wife, who is not tech-savvy, loves the app and controls our lights and fans using the Insteon app. When I read about Apple's release of HomeKit, I was hoping that Insteon would work with Apple to get everything working seamlessly. I purchased the Insteon Hub Pro and it was not sent out until the HomeKit release from Apple. I have been doing construction on my home and finally got around to installing the new Hub Pro. Unfortunately, nothing really works with the Hub Pro. I have 10 open/close sensors, 1 garage opener, 3 fanlincs/keypadlincs, 9 switches and 1 water sensor. That's plenty of money spent on Insteon products but none of my existing products work with the new Hub Pro according to Insteon because it needs Apple to support the devices. That's fine and I understand that Apple does things their way so there may be some pain along the way. After being a loyal Insteon customer for this long and spending a significant amount of money to outfit my house, I was hoping I could get my money back from Insteon since the Hub Pro does not do what it's advertised to do which is work with Insteon products. It doesn't make any sense why there is no warning/disclaimer that says \"if you are an existing Insteon customer, don't buy the Hub Pro because nothing will work.\" I just want a full refund for my purchase of a device that doesn't work for me but Insteon refuses to do so and only allows me to return if for store credit. I don't need any more sensors or cameras or anything else so store credit does me no good. Real bummer Insteon. I have always recommended your products to others but not sure I can continue to do so after being treated this way. Guess my Hub Pro will just collect dust in the box."}
{"Author": "Jolene", "Date": "on September 30, 2015", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Avoid", "Text": "This model does NOT work with HomeKit. I wish they were more clear in the description about it. Not to mention I spend 20 minutes trying to actually get it to connect. Do not buy!"}
{"Author": "Philip Glassel", "Date": "on September 28, 2015", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "DON'T: if you have more than a very few, simple devices", "Text": "This device deserves 0 stars! The hub and/or its apps are so flawed that it will be impossible to set up anything complex. I used both the Windows 10 PC app and the Android app in an attempt to set up a 60+ device home with 6 8-key pads. If there is a single communication error with any of the keypads during setup, it will completely hose up the scenes for all of the other devices. It will be so bad that you will have to do a factory reset on every device, delete the account in the cloud and start from scratch. After days of going through this cycle, I gave my device away (properly warning the victim, of course).\n\nThere is no error recovery, no backup and restore mode, and other flaws aplenty.\n\nWhile it's pretty nice to use your smart phone to control devices in your home, that thrill is completely negated by the failure to perform anything remotely complex. It will also consume your smartphone's battery. I was only able to set up about 1/2 of my house with a single charge on a phone that I normally recharge every 48 hours. I suppose you could plug it in while doing this, but you will be exhausted by that point anyway.\n\nI now have a Universal Devices ISY994i which is handling my home just fine. You can see my review of that device elsewhere:\nhttps://www.amazon.com/gp/customer-reviews/R1RPGLWOZM240W/ref=cm_cr_pr_rvw_ttl?ie=UTF8&ASIN=B007JM29LU"}
{"Author": "Davepl", "Date": "on September 28, 2015", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Only useful for under 10 devices; software not ready for public release.", "Text": "I would have imagined that the hub could enumerate swtiches and other devices already installed. Instead, you'll be entering and pairing EVERY device you have all over again. If you have a lot of Insteon, as I do, it's just too much. Especially because the software is very broken; you receive Access Denied messages, Comin Soon messages, and blatant bugs. The worst is in the device add, where even the text box for the name has several bugs. Voice recognition doesn't even work properly in their text box, so you'll be typing the name of every device as well.\n\nEntering, linking, and naming each device takes 1-2 minutes, so it's only about an hour for 30 devices, but it's a painful process.\n\nThen, when you create scenes, you get to do it all over again! For each device you add to a scene, run around the house in whatever order it tells you and press the link button manually on every device? That one in the basement crawl space for the circulation pump? Get on your coveralls, you're going down there.\n\nThe web interface is undocumented, labelled as \"BETA\", and doesn't allow you do add/edit/change anything. You cannot add or edit or rename devices in the web interface, which would have at least given you a keyboard way of entering all of this information. Perhaps you can bind a full size bluetooth keyboard to a phone - had not tried that.\n\nThis would have been an AMAZING product if it could have just imported everything from the devices and given me mobile phone control of it. Unfortunately just configuring it is a hobby on its own.\n\nThe integration with the Echo is well done - the Echo just does it's thing and finds everything, but only the devices you've re-entered into the hub. It doesn't work for being \"close\" - it will fail to recognize \"Turn on the Bathroom Tub\" as \"Turn on the Bathroom Rub\", and fail. It should likely have some heuristics to get the \"closest\" sounding device, particularly since you preface every command with \"Turn on\" or \"Turn off\".\n\nCompared to desktop software solutions like Indigo (which is what I've used for years even though it requires a Mac I have no other use for) this is amateurish and rushed to market. Wait six months and see where they're at.\n\nIf, however, you are setting up a brand new Insteon installation of a handful of security lights and so on, this is likely adequate if you work around the frustrations. For a larger pre-existing setup, I will use mine only for the 10 or so devices I -really- want the Echo in control of."}
{"Author": "David Gilbert", "Date": "on September 27, 2015", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Fantastic starter kit", "Text": "Fantastic starter kit, who doesn't use timers? Insteon get's very addictive, now I've got motion sensors, garage door sensors, camera and light switches. Everything works, like magic it's so easy!"}
{"Author": "AV", "Date": "on September 26, 2015", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "This is the one you need to use with Amazon Echo..."}
{"Author": "railfan", "Date": "on September 23, 2015", "Stars": "3.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "I like key the house b", "Text": "I like key the house b. It works well. For a beginner or your general user is designed well. However, I have been working with various home automation systems for years and so it is not as robust as I would like.\nThe hub worked out great for my daughters house. They just needed some simple reliable devices. Basic motion light setups with the ability to remotely check and set. Works well for that.\nFor me it lacks more advanced scheduling. It also doesn't support X10 (I'm migrating off of but have lots of devices) and it doesn't support some of the newer technologies like Z-Wave and Zigbee."}
{"Author": "fat ninja", "Date": "on September 14, 2015", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "New hub is GREAT! and now with Amazon Echo too!", "Text": "I got this as a birthday gift a year or so ago. I never used it because I was using an Insteon PLM with no issues. I got it going the other day and was happily surprised at how well it worked. Adding my insteon devices was a breeze with the hub. I really liked being able to use my windows phone or my wife's IPhone to add and control devices.\n\nWith the hub being cloud based I can turn lights on/off, set the thermostat, and monitor my home while on any network.\nIt is small in size and can be easily put in some back room. I was concerned at first that there may be some latency issues compared to the plm I was using, but have not noticed any delays. Good product with good support people. Would buy again and recommend.\n\nLinked my amazon echo to Insteon and it works great! with the Amazon echo I can create groups of different smarthome brands that the echo works with. The echo will only work with this hub."}
{"Author": "Lloyd A. Lawrence", "Date": "on September 9, 2015", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Nerdvana", "Text": "Glad to have this. I was originally wanting the HomeKit enabled one only to find that it was not a complete solution. That said, this one has done fine for me."}
{"Author": "Scott in Austin, TX", "Date": "on August 31, 2015", "Stars": "2.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "I have been a user of Insteon products since they ...", "Text": "I have been a user of Insteon products since they first became available. I currently use an ISY controller but got this to make it easier to check on the status of the scenes from my phone. I have more than 40 switchlinc and outletlinc responders and this device could only pair with a small subset of them (ones recently purchased) where the ISY device works with them all. I think it won't recognize the older firmware, but I can't find where this is documented."}
{"Author": "Regular Guy", "Date": "on August 30, 2015", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Vastly Improved Over Previous Model Easy to set up", "Text": "Vastly Improved Over Previous Model\nEasy to set up. Great access from the internet to control home. Many desirable control features. Insteon Apple App easy to set up. Now only if this Central Control Hub can interface with Amazon Echo, it would be a dream."}
{"Author": "TXGunLover", "Date": "on August 30, 2015", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "This Insteon product is an unmitigated disaster. If I ...", "Text": "This Insteon product is an unmitigated disaster. If I didn't have dozens of insteon in-wall switches, plug ins, sensors, and hardwired outlets I would switch to Wink/Smartthings Lutron or some other Connected home devices.\n\n1st, as many reviews state, this can't control all of your Insteon devices. So, if you have a previous hub, you have to keep it connected and \"switch houses\" in the Windows App (but no functionality to do so in Android) to use those devices. In my case, it couldn't even find devices it said it supported. The hub just emits a single loud beep when trying to add devices it says it supports.\n\nI'm trying to get all my insteon devices to work with myHarmony remote, but of course, the 2242-222 hub doesn't support that, and this hub evidently can't connect to any existing Insteon devices\n\nTotal and complete disaster for Insteon. They're definitely going the way of X-10."}
{"Author": "rb", "Date": "on August 27, 2015", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Very Happy", "Text": "The start up package was very easy to setup. I have added some things which added easy enough except the camera but their help center was very helpful in getting me up and running. Would highly recommend if your looking for a low cost way to have remote control through your phone."}
{"Author": "gordon strong", "Date": "on August 18, 2015", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Four Stars", "Text": "Works as advertised."}
{"Author": "jf", "Date": "on August 11, 2015", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "I have it located with my network devices and it works good. Only problem I found with it is that ...", "Text": "using with 2475SDB on/off switch on my pool light switch outside. I have it located with my network devices and it works good. Only problem I found with it is that other cables that didn't come with it may have trouble with the contacts in the back. The cable that came with it however works good. the distance between the 2475SDB is a little too long to work with the hub directly, so I purchased two 2992-222 RF extenders (hub worked with the outside 2475SDB with one extender at the other end of the house; ~75ft inside the house separated the exteneder and hub; ~35ft to switch from extender; will keep the other extender for future add ons). It works great with the extenders and the iPhone app. I am very impressed so far and will likely start experimenting with more switches and cameras to further automate my house if these items hold up over time. will try to provide updates overtime."}
{"Author": "jfam5128", "Date": "on July 29, 2015", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Pretty Cool - So Far No Problems", "Text": "I new to this whole smart home deal but I do have this hub and using it to control the lighting in my kitchen which includes a ceiling fan using a Fanlinc module, to accent lights, and then a series of halogen under/over cabinet lights. I do have an 8 button wall controller. So far so good. I've had a few questions along the way but once I figured it out the problem was with me and not the product. I plan to continue to add a little here and a little there."}
{"Author": "mm", "Date": "on July 19, 2015", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Unreliable hardware and terrible software. I do not trust it to keep ...", "Text": "Unreliable hardware and terrible software. I do not trust it to keep my home safe or automated. Look elsewhere. I wish I could return mine."}
{"Author": "SteveH", "Date": "on July 15, 2015", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Stay Away from this product", "Text": "Would like to give it a negative rating. Software too buggy to use. Too many problems to list. Designed by amateurs."}
{"Author": "Scott", "Date": "on June 27, 2015", "Stars": "4.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "dimmer problem", "Text": "This new hub works great with one exception; it is unable to change the on level brightness of dimmers. No matter what on brightness is set with the iOS app, the dimmers turn on at 100%. Please fix this bug with a software update. Otherwise this hub is working flawlessly"}
{"Author": "Amazon Customer", "Date": "on June 2, 2015", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Mostly a good product, but truly odd shortcomings", "Text": "The hub installs easily and links to the dimmer modules are easy to establish. The iPad and Android apps are professionally done, much better than the WeMo product line. But a funny thing happened when configuring the dimmer modules.\n\nThe easily FELL OUT OF THE WALL SOCKET. I've never had a plug or wall outlet until now. It appears that the two blades are at least an eight of an inch too short, and maybe too thin as well. I compared this with a number of other appliances and extension cords and all are the appropriate length. It is truly puzzling that they would cut corners this close on a module that is DESIGNED to stay plugged into the wall outlet. (note these are quality Lutron outlets)\n\nI also added a standard on/off module and find the same short plug blades, but because these are three-wire connections the round ground blade keeps it tightly plugged into the wall."}
{"Author": "Ragbagger", "Date": "on April 27, 2015", "Stars": "1.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "... OK but the software to use it is very poor. What they don't tell you- 1) There is ...", "Text": "Hardware is OK but the software to use it is very poor. What they don't tell you- 1) There is no Windows 7 app. If you don't have Windows 8 you are out your $$ if you want to program the hub via PC. 2) The software for Android is really lame. You cannot delete a scene under Android 4.4.2. After consulting their tech support they blame the android device. 3) The Android software will not control the optional outlet devices properly- it will control only the top outlet so you get half of what you pay for. Tech support says this might be fixed on a later release of software. Overall very disappointing. I would wait until they have a mature product to purchase."}
{"Author": "DIY Extraordinaire", "Date": "on April 8, 2015", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Great product. Plug for dimmer module should be on the side, not the bottom.", "Text": "The insteon starter kit is great. I had a little difficulty finding the hub from my Insteon App, but realized that there must be a timeout between powering up the hub and searching for a hub on the app...so be sure to start the app shortly after powering up the hub. Once I did this setup was a breeze! The product works exactly as I expected. I would like to see a little more functionality, but expect that this will be part of App upgrades thoughout the years.\n\nOne note for the Insteon makers would be to put the plug on the side of the dimmer modules instead of the bottom. My plug receptacles are too close to my baseboard hydronic heat to make these units usable in those locations...I need to turn my wall receptacles upside down in order to plug a lamp into these modules because of this. If the plug was on the side of the dimmer module this would resolve the problem."}
{"Author": "Alexander Suvorov", "Date": "on April 3, 2015", "Stars": "5.0 out of 5 stars", "Title": "Five Stars", "Text": "Ingeniously! Simply and conveniently!"}
